[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Welcome to This Course"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ Hello! I am Vladimir Kramnik, the 14th World Chess Champion, and I would like to present my opening course on e4-e5. I published the first one recently, which was on e4 and all Black’s responses other than e5 and c5 - so Caro Kann, Pirc, French, and everything else.In this course, we will study everything after e4-e5 for both colors. This project sounds very ambitious, and of course, I cannot do it in the usual fashion that opening courses are done, so I will not go through every single line but rather I want to build you a base of understanding in all opening variations and, importantly, the typical pawn structures - what to do, what the dangers are for both sides. Then you can choose what you want to play, as there is a huge selection for both sides, and you can choose your opening repertoire after e4-e5 for White and Black. Nowadays, professional players have e4-e5 in their repertoire for both colors.What is very important is that I will give you the directions, such as which lines are more promising and which are less promising, and I will explain all the move orders, which is also very important. So with this course, you will build a certain base of understanding, such as knowing why some lines are out of fashion, etc, which will increase the speed of your process of learning e4-e5 - otherwise, you are just stuck with a database with thousands of games in each variation. But once you build this understanding of all the nuances and move-orders, and what kind of pawn structure you would like to get, then things are much easier.When I was a kid, our trainers in the Soviet Union always advised us to play, for example, the Ruy Lopez, or e4-e5 with at least one color - and better, with both colors. Why? Well - and I fully agree with all those mighty Soviet trainers - playing and understanding e4-e5 openings improves your general understanding of chess. The reason is that I think it's the richest opening in the theory of chess. Because, most of the time, in different openings, like King's Indian or Grünfeld, or let's say Sicilian, there is still quite a limited amount of pawn structures, and understanding the nuances of different pawn structures is very important.    @@StartBlockQuote@@I believe that the main point of understanding chess is understanding pawn structures.@@EndBlockQuote@@ But after e4-e5, you have almost an unlimited amount of very important pawn structures. Studying the opening lines, and opening variations, playing them, and getting experience, also helps you with feeling the nuances of those pawn structures and simply improving your chess understanding.In this introduction, I want to show you at least some of the pawn structures which can arise after e4-e5, just to show you how rich it is, and how much you will gain in your understanding of the game by studying this opening. }
*

