[Black "Pawn Structures 1: Petroff"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { 2...Nc6  is the main move, but let's look at 2...Nf6. } 2...
Nf6 { The Petroff Defense. } 3. d4
{ Another move.   3.Nxe5  d6  4.Nf3  Nxe4  5.d4  d5  This is a very important main theoretical line.  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  8.c4  Nb4  9.Be2  O-O  10.Nc3  Bf5  11.a3  Nxc3  12.bxc3  Nc6  13.cxd5  Qxd5  So for example, you have this pawn structure with White's central c3- and d4-pawns, where the c-pawn will most likely move to c4. This is a very typical and important pawn structure to understand as it can also happen via d4 first, or with the opposite colors. }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3
{ 4.dxe5  d5  Similar to the Open Ruy Lopez which I will show you later where you will learn typical ideas for this type of structure. }
4... d5 5. Nxe5 Nd7 6. Nc3 { A very fashionable move. } 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Nxe5
8. dxe5
{ This line is one of the main options for Black to play. Another pawn structure, where White's pawn is on e5 and he has the doubled c-pawns, but he has a very serious potential of attack against the king, and this e5-pawn is bothering Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Pawn Structures 2: Scotch"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { Now let's move to 2...Nc6. } 2... Nc6 3. d4 { Scotch. } 3...
exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ 4...Bc5  Another move.  5.Nxc6  Qf6  6.Qd2  dxc6  A very important pawn structure. Without the queens, and with the white pawn on e5, we reach the very famous Berlin endgame.   With the white pawn on e4, there are a lot of nuances, as White has a certain advantage with a more flexible and better pawn structure, but Black has some initiative in return. Understanding when this initiative is enough to equalize, and when White can stabilize and finally start to use his positional advantage @@StartBracket@@because of the black doubled pawns@@EndBracket@@, is a very subtle matter, and studying this variation will help you to understand it. }
5. Nxc6
{ 5.Nc3  Bb4  6.Nxc6  bxc6  7.Bd3  d5  8.exd5  cxd5  A little bit of a different pawn structure, and if you remember the position we saw in the Petroff, we have a similar pawn structure, with reversed colors and its own nuances. }
5... bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5
{ A very original structure. Black's pawns are slightly compromised but the white pawn on e5 can also be vulnerable. So, another important tabiya to study. }
*

