1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { Then finally we move on to the Ruy Lopez. } 3...
a6
{ 3...Nf6   A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d3  Another move.  4...Bc5   A1@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  d5  6.Nbd2  dxe4  7.dxe4  Again, an almost symmetrical pawn structure where Black has a knight on c6, and White has a pawn on c3. There are a lot of nuances here, and White has a more flexible set-up which is why he is still fighting for an advantage. But with accurate play, Black usually is capable of equalizing. It is important to understand the ideas, for example, Black should quite often try to play a5 to stop b4-a4, sometimes maneuvering the knight from c6 to e6 via d8. All these typical ideas are very useful in general for your chess understanding.   A2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bxc6  dxc6  Black has two bishops, but White is maneuvering with his knights. Another important pawn structure that you need to know and understand.   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.Re1  Also a big line.  5...Nd6  6.Nxe5  Be7  7.Bf1  Nxe5  8.Rxe5  White will play d4 and sooner or later, Black will play d5 with a symmetrical pawn structure where White is a couple of tempi up in development. This structure with d4-d5 and the open e-file is another very important pawn structure to learn. }
4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ 5...Nxe4  The Open Ruy Lopez.  6.d4  b5  7.Bb3  d5  8.dxe5  Be6  Now we have the main theoretical position. With a similar pawn structure to the Petroff, but here there is a6 and b5 which makes this position special in its own way. Black has ideas of playing f6 sometimes, White has his own trumps - sometimes a4 is very dangerous, etc. A lot depends on whether Black can keep the knight on e4, or quickly manage Nc5-d4. We will study this as well. }
6. Re1
{ This is more common.   6.d3  b5  7.Bb3  d6  8.c3  O-O  9.Re1  Na5  10.Bc2  c5  11.Nbd2  Nc6  12.Nf1  This will be a big chapter where you will learn how to understand how to play with either color. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. a4
{ 8.c3   Of course now  8...d5  is the Marshall which we will also study.  8...d6  9.h3   A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/2p1bppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/4P3/1BP2N1P/PP1P1PP1/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Na5  10.Bc2  c5  11.d4  Qc7   Now the main move is  12.Nbd2  but very often White sooner or later gets the pawn to d5.  12.d5  And then we get to this structure, where you will get to understand when it's ok for Black and in what situations White is better - White has ideas to play on the kingside and the queenside, and the same goes for Black. This is a very rich position and it is important to understand typical ideas here.   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/2p1bppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/4P3/1BP2N1P/PP1P1PP1/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bb7  10.d4  Re8  11.Nbd2  Let's say Zaistev.  11...Bf8  12.Bc2  g6  13.d5  Nb8  14.b3  Nbd7  15.c4  c6  So now we have this pawn structure which has its own nuances. Of course, you can get these structures via, for example, King's Indian. The pieces are in slightly different places, but understanding the main ideas will also improve your play. }
8... b4 9. d3
{ 9.d4  d6  10.dxe5  dxe5  Also a slightly different structure, because now White can try to make use of the c4-square for the knight. So, also understanding when it is better for White and under what circumstances Black is equalizing will also help you with your play, as such positions can even arise via d4. }
9... d6
{ This is another very important structure, which even happens in the Italian sometimes. }
10. a5 Be6 11. Bxe6 fxe6
{ This type of structure where Black doubles his pawns but gets the f-file for potential counterplay. }
12. Nbd2 Qc8 13. c3 Rb8 14. Nc4
{ Also an extremely important structure to understand, as it can come up quite a lot. Understanding when the a5-pawn can become a weakness, under which circumstance the a6-pawn can become weak, how to deal with the central tension here, @@StartBracket@@as it is not so easy for Black to play d5 and for White to play d4@@EndBracket@@, makes this an extremely rich position.That is why e4-e5 will never totally be refuted or completely be studied, as there are too many positions to know which are all mostly rich for both colors. And that is why I recommend that you study this, no matter your level or if you are an e4-e5 player as it will improve your understanding of chess. Of course, you can play all kinds of strange defenses, like Pirc @@StartBracket@@which I covered in part 1@@EndBracket@@, but e4-e5 is the king of all openings :@@EndBracket@@In this course, I have gone through all the major important lines, I have given a lot of hints and directions which I believe are the best ones in the openings, since I have played them myself with both colors. }
