[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Chessable Note: How To Use This Course"]
[Result "*"]

{ Dear students,    We are happy to welcome you to Part 2 of the 14th World Champion, Grandmaster Vladimir Kramnik's, series - Understanding Chess Openings, 1.e4.   As with GM Kramnik's first course, this course is devoted to the topic of openings and consitutes an exploration of opening theory and ideas after 1. e4. Part 1 dealt with all of Black's responses other than e5 and c5, and part 2 will deal with 1...e5.    This is not a standard opening repertoire since the emphasis is not on concrete lines, analysis and memorization. Instead, GM Kramnik will provide an overview of all the openings that can arise after 1. e4 e5. The focus is more on what the critical ideas and critical variations are for both sides. GM Kramnik also talks about the kind of positions you can expect if you employ a certain opening line with either color. The goal of this approach is to foster understanding and to help you select the opening which suits you the best.    It's also important to note that the variations in this course are presented as a mix of lines from White and Black's perspective. We felt that this way of presenting the material best reflects GM Kramnik's approach to these opening lines. However, this does mean that some variations overlap and some moves have to be learned twice, both from White and Black's perspective. If this does not appeal to you, we suggest you make use of the 'pause variation' function, so that you can skip over lines that you don't want to review from White's perspective or from Black's perspective.    This course is divided into 16 Lessons:     Lesson 10: 2nd Move Sidelines - This chapter considers the moves 2.d4, 2.f4, 2.Nc3, 2.Bc4, and 2.Nf3 d6.  Lesson 11: Petroff Defense with 3.d4.  Lesson 12: Petroff Defense with 3.Nxe5.  Lesson 13: Four Knights  Lesson 14: Scotch  Lesson 15: Italian Sharp Lines  Lesson 16: Italian with c3 and d3  Lesson 17: Spanish, Black's Early alternatives  Lesson 18: Spanish Berlin with 4.d3   Lesson 19: Spanish Berlin with 4.O-O  Lesson 20: Open Spanish & White's Early Alternatives  Lesson 21: Spanish 5...b5 and 5...Bc5  Lesson 22: Spanish 5...Be7 White's Early Alternatives  Lesson 23: Spanish Mainline - Systems with ...d6  Lesson 24: Spanish Mainline - Marshall Gambit  Lesson 25: Spanish Mainline - Anti-Marshalls Each chapter ends with a summary of the main takeaways of the opening that has just been covered.In any case, we hope you will find this course instructive and enjoyable. We wish you the best of luck in applying the variations and ideas presented to your own opening repertoire and games!  With best wishes,  Chessable staff }
