1. e4
{ Starting with this lesson we will move on to 1. e4 e5. The move 1... e5 is probably Black's best in the position and it is very logical. Of course there is a lot of theory, and you can find many books, videos and courses on different variations after 1. e4 e5. My goal is to provide you with directions and to share my opinion on which variations are worth looking into and which ones are dubious.I will try to cover as many variations as possible, but, of course, it is not possible to go through every single line as there is just so much theory after 1. e4 e5.   In this lesson we will look at sidelines after  1.e4  e5  . Some of them are not dangerous at all, but there are some serious tries, such as  2.Bc4  , and Black's move @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  after 2. Nf3. }
1... e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit, a very romantic opening. However, I don't want to spend a lot of time on it, because I think Black is fine - at least equal, probably slightly better - and there are many valid ways in which Black can respond to 2. f4. }
2... exf4 3. Nf3
{ There is also  3.Bc4  ,  which is a bit more interesting than 3. Nf3 in my opinion. After 3. Bc4 Black still has many options. For instance, he can give back the pawn with  3...d5  , which probably leads to equality. But I don't see why Black should give back the pawn. If I were Black I would probably try to play for an advantage with a move like  3...Qh4+  . Also  3...d6  is fine too. }
3... g5
{ Here, too, Black has many different options.  3...d5  is okay, but is more solid and more of an attempt to equalize. Fischer's move  3...d6  is also fine. However, objectively speaking  3...g5  is the most principled move. There is some theory which you would need to study here, but I think Black is just better after  3...g5  .    The King's Gambit is an opening that is playable for White up to a certain level, but I wouldn't recommend it at, for instance, the 2400-2500 level. Among professionals you won't find many grandmasters who are willing to play it as White. As Black, I think practically every system against the King's Gambit is fine. You just need to switch on the engine and take some time to study the theory of this opening.   If you do that, you'll be at least equal out of the opening, and maybe you'll even get a superior position. }
