1... e5 2. Nc3
{ This is a playable move, though I don't think it will cause Black many problems. It will likely transpose to either  2.Bc4  , which is covered later in this lesson, or to the variation  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  ,  which is studied in a separate lesson. }
2... Nf6 3. Bc4
{ This is playable for White, but it gives Black a choice of three good replies. After both  3...Nc6  and  3...Bc5  , White probably has nothing better than  4.d3  ,  when we will transpose to the 2. Bc4 system. However, via the current move order 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4, Black gets the interesting extra possibility of 3... Nxe4. }
3... Nxe4 { A very typical idea. } 4. Bxf7+
{ 4.Nxe4  d5  similarly is good for Black. } 4... Kxf7 5. Nxe4
