1. e4
{ Starting with this lesson we will move on to 1. e4 e5. The move 1... e5 is probably Black's best in the position and it is very logical. Of course there is a lot of theory, and you can find many books, videos and courses on different variations after 1. e4 e5. My goal is to provide you with directions and to share my opinion on which variations are worth looking into and which ones are dubious.I will try to cover as many variations as possible, but, of course, it is not possible to go through every single line as there is just so much theory after 1. e4 e5.   In this lesson we will look at sidelines after  1.e4  e5  . Some of them are not dangerous at all, but there are some serious tries, such as  2.Bc4  , and Black's move @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  after 2. Nf3. }
1... e5 2. Nc3
{ This is a playable move, though I don't think it will cause Black many problems. It will likely transpose to either  2.Bc4  , which is covered later in this lesson, or to the variation  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  ,  which is studied in a separate lesson. }
2... Nf6 3. Bc4
{ This is playable for White, but it gives Black a choice of three good replies. After both  3...Nc6  and  3...Bc5  , White probably has nothing better than  4.d3  ,  when we will transpose to the 2. Bc4 system. However, via the current move order 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4, Black gets the interesting extra possibility of 3... Nxe4. }
3... Nxe4 { A very typical idea. } 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3
{ If  5.Qxe5+  Qe7  the queens are exchanged  6.Qxe7+  Bxe7  and the endgame is equal. Now after 5. Bb3 Black has a choice between a solid, normal game, or to go for a crazy line. }
5... Be7
{ If you enjoy very unbalanced, romantic positions, you can play  5...Nc6  , when there is a critical variation starting with  6.Nb5!?  @@StartBracket@@threatening Nxd6+ followed by mate on f7@@EndBracket@@  6...g6  7.Qf3  f5  8.Qd5  Qe7  9.Nxc7+  Kd8  10.Nxa8  b6  .  Black will follow up with ...Bb7, trapping the knight. The position is very unclear and interesting. If you want to play it safe you should go for 5... Be7 instead. }
6. Qxe5 { White has to take this pawn. } 6... O-O 7. d4 Nc6 8. Qf4
{ Black will play either  8...b6  or  8...b5  followed by ...Na5. The position is roughly equal but still quite complicated. }
