1. e4
{ Starting with this lesson we will move on to 1. e4 e5. The move 1... e5 is probably Black's best in the position and it is very logical. Of course there is a lot of theory, and you can find many books, videos and courses on different variations after 1. e4 e5. My goal is to provide you with directions and to share my opinion on which variations are worth looking into and which ones are dubious.I will try to cover as many variations as possible, but, of course, it is not possible to go through every single line as there is just so much theory after 1. e4 e5.   In this lesson we will look at sidelines after  1.e4  e5  . Some of them are not dangerous at all, but there are some serious tries, such as  2.Bc4  , and Black's move @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  after 2. Nf3. }
1... e5 2. Bc4
{ This is quite a serious move. Many strong players use this move in order to get to the Italian Defense -  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  - without allowing the option of Black playing the Petroff Defense, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nf6  . After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bc4  White often follows up with d3, Nf3 and so on, while Black plays ...Nf6, ...Bc5 and ...Nc6, and thus we get to an Italian game.The move 2. Bc4 has good surprise value. Many players know some theory after the main move 2. Nf3, but don't know anything about 2. Bc4. And it's not like Black can equalize easily; he does have to know what he is doing. }
2... Nf6
{ If you're playing Black and the Petroff is your repertoire after 2. Nf3, you don't necessarily have to enter the Italian though. You can play  2...Nf6  and then after  3.d3  follow up with  3...c6  . }
3. d3 Nc6
{ This is the main continuation, but you should only play it if you are ready to transpose to the Italian in case of White playing 4. Nf3. }
4. Nc3
{ This is the only reasonable way for White to avoid the Italian, followed by f2-f4. This line has actually become a bit popular among top players, at least in rapid games. It's playable for White and there is some venom in this line, but Black has a wide range of perfectly good continuations here. I will show you the three major options. I think all three are good enough to equalize, but you need to choose one and then study some theory. }
4... Na5
{ This is probably the simplest option, just trying to exchange the c4-bishop. }
5. Nge2 Be7
{ Black can also start with  5...c6  , but that should lead to a similar position. }
6. O-O c6 7. a4
{ At some point White usually plays this move, with the 'threat' of tucking the bishop away on a2. }
7... Nxc4 8. dxc4 d6
{ White will put the e2-knight on g3, play b3, Qd3 and has good control over the center, but Black has two bishops and no weaknesses. You can check the database for games with this pawn structure. It's perfectly playable for Black and White has no advantage. }
