1. e4
{ Starting with this lesson we will move on to 1. e4 e5. The move 1... e5 is probably Black's best in the position and it is very logical. Of course there is a lot of theory, and you can find many books, videos and courses on different variations after 1. e4 e5. My goal is to provide you with directions and to share my opinion on which variations are worth looking into and which ones are dubious.I will try to cover as many variations as possible, but, of course, it is not possible to go through every single line as there is just so much theory after 1. e4 e5.   In this lesson we will look at sidelines after  1.e4  e5  . Some of them are not dangerous at all, but there are some serious tries, such as  2.Bc4  , and Black's move @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  after 2. Nf3. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ Before covering the Petroff @@StartBracket@@  2...Nf6  @@EndBracket@@ and the main move  2...Nc6  , there is the Philidor Defense  2...d6  .  Philidor was the best chess player during his time in the 18th century, and he was also a good music composer - quite an accomplished personality! He liked the move 2... d6, even if nowadays this move is not considered to be as strong as 2... Nf6 and 2... Nc6.2... d6 is a playable move and it's not so easy for White to gain an advantage, but White should be somewhat better with correct play. }
3. d4
{ The best move. If White knows what he is doing here, he will get some advantage. Black is not really fighting for the center, so it should not be enough to equalize.   Now after  3.d4  Black ideally wants to get to the position which is reached after e.g.  3...Nf6  4.Nc3  Nbd7  5.Bc4  Be7  ,  the old mainline of the Philidor. However, whether Black starts with 3... Nf6 or 3... Nd7, White has some dangerous alternatives which make it impossible for Black to reach that position via this move order. }
3... Nf6 4. dxe5
{ This is unpleasant for Black. Now Black is forced to take on e4. } 4... Nxe4
5. Qd5 Nc5 6. Bg5
{ This is an old line. Back when I was a kid I tried to make it work for Black, as I wanted to have an opening line where I didn't have to know too much theory. The Philidor appealed to me but I didn't see how to reach the position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nbd7  5.Bc4  Be7  via this move order.   Here White just seems to be better, for example  6...Qd7  7.exd6  Bxd6  8.Nc3  and White will castle long. The pawn structure is symmetrical but White's pieces are much more active. Or there is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p4/2nQP1B1/8/5N2/PPP2PPP/RN2KB1R b KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  7.exd6  cxd6  8.Nc3  and Black is simply a bit worse due to the pawn structure. }
