{ Before covering the Petroff @@StartBracket@@  2...Nf6  @@EndBracket@@ and the main move  2...Nc6  , there is the Philidor Defense  2...d6  .  Philidor was the best chess player during his time in the 18th century, and he was also a good music composer - quite an accomplished personality! He liked the move 2... d6, even if nowadays this move is not considered to be as strong as 2... Nf6 and 2... Nc6.2... d6 is a playable move and it's not so easy for White to gain an advantage, but White should be somewhat better with correct play. }
3. d4
{ The best move. If White knows what he is doing here, he will get some advantage. Black is not really fighting for the center, so it should not be enough to equalize.   Now after  3.d4  Black ideally wants to get to the position which is reached after e.g.  3...Nf6  4.Nc3  Nbd7  5.Bc4  Be7  ,  the old mainline of the Philidor. However, whether Black starts with 3... Nf6 or 3... Nd7, White has some dangerous alternatives which make it impossible for Black to reach that position via this move order. }
3... Nd7
{ If Black tries to reach the classical Philidor via 3... Nd7 there are also multiple hurdles to overcome. }
4. Bc4
{ First of all,  4.c4  is an unpleasant move to face, as after  4...Ngf6  5.Nc3  there arises a King's Indian where Black's knight has been prematurely developed to d7. But 4. Bc4 is a problematic move too. How does Black intend to develop the kingside? }
4... Be7 { This loses a pawn. } 5. dxe5 Nxe5
{ If  5...dxe5  the double attack  6.Qd5  wins the e5-pawn. } 6. Nxe5 dxe5 7.
Qh5 { Again a double attack that wins the e5-pawn, this time via h5. } *

