[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 10: 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ As White, you can try @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bc4  if your opponent plays the Petroff and you want to avoid the Petroff at all costs. After  2.Bc4  there are lines that transpose to the Italian, but there are also some independent variations which are not that well explored. Probably Black will equalize, but at least you can get an interesting game as White.   If after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  you reply  2...d6  as Black, then in case of the critical move  3.d4  ,  3...exd4  is probably the only option that can justify the move 2... d6. After the alternatives  3...Nf6  and  3...Nd7  , Black will end up in an inferior position with no chances of winning. Instead, after  3...exd4  there is no doubt that White has a slight advantage, but the line is playable for Black - you'll get an interesting game at least.In the next lesson we will start analyzing the Petroff, which is a defense to 2. Nf3 that I've played for many years. It is impossible to cover every variation, but I will try to give you some directions to this very solid opening line. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 11: Petroff with 3. d4"]
[Black "Petroff Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ It is time to study the Petroff Defense, an opening that I played a lot during my career. Without false modesty I can state that I contributed significantly to the theoretical development of this opening. Back in the 90s, when I started playing the Petroff, it was quite difficult to make this opening work for Black. Nowadays, it has a solid reputation and it is considered a difficult opening to deal with for White.It is not easy to find an advantage for White because this opening is strategically sound, and Black is not running the risk of getting worse if the theoretical ground is covered. The game often becomes very concrete and many variations can be quite memorization heavy. These long forcing lines convinced me to switch to other openings and allow my memory to have a moment of respite. Of course, it is mainly in top-level chess where the Petroff fits this profile.In the Petroff, Black gets a solid game, but he doesn't obtain great winning chances. Black's strategy relies on getting a sound position  (it might be, at times, slightly worse)  , defend accurately, make a draw and wait for the next day to bring a new opportunity with the white pieces. For a World Championship match, this plan can pay off well. This is why I played the Petroff against Peter Leko in our match in 2004, and after a couple of games he decided to switch from 1.e4 to 1.d4, as the Petroff was giving him a hard time. I also prepared this opening for the match against Vishy Anand in 2008, but Anand had 1.d4 in his repertoire too.For the top level, this opening is a good choice, even though the positions can be a bit unpleasant for Black sometimes. Black has to remember many lines by heart as the game becomes very sharp. In such situations, relying on over the board calculation would be a suicide mission. Having said that, it might be even more difficult to play the white side of the Petroff. If you are facing a strong and well-prepared Grandmaster, the Petroff is known to offer little room for obtaining an opening advantage, and winning a game is almost a mission impossible.On the amateur level, if you are playing chess for your enjoyment, perhaps this is not an opening you should play as Black. A lot of knowledge is required, the game is very positional and there aren't many fancy variations. However, this is also a matter of taste. The Petroff is a perfectly playable opening and many top GMs include it in their arsenal. Fabiano Caruana, for instance, won two games with it in the 2018 Candidates, and then he also played it against Carlsen in the World Championship match. Magnus was not able to pose Caruana any problems in the Petroff, which shows that this opening is a serious weapon.   Back to the position after 2... Nf6: there aren't that many good moves for White, since the e4-pawn is hanging. The question is whether White should grab the e5-pawn immediately with  3.Nxe5  or play  3.d4  . Of course, a move like  3.d3  is not a serious challenge to Black.Let me just add one thing. Throughout this course, I normally try to provide some strategic insights into the openings we are discussing, but here there really aren't that many to give. The positions arising in the Petroff are rather 'simple' and there aren't that many different types of positions that can arise. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 11: Petroff with 3. d4"]
[Black "Petroff 3. Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. In this position there aren't that many good moves for White, since the e4-pawn is hanging. The question is whether White should grab the e5-pawn immediately with  3.Nxe5  or play  3.d4  . Of course, a move like  3.d3  is not a serious challenge to Black. }
3. Nc3
{ This move is a good choice if you have the Four Knights included in your repertoire, since Black's best continuation is probably  3...Nc6  . We are going to have a look at the Four Knights in Lesson 13. The only small issue is that White has a tough time getting anything out of the opening. There are still a few tries and Black must know quite some theory, obviously, but I was happily playing  3...Nc6  in this position. }
3... Bb4
{ There are players who have only studied the Petroff and prefer to have a more compact repertoire, without having to learn the  3...Nc6  variation as well. For them, the move  3...Bb4  is a good alternative. }
4. Nxe5
{ White doesn't have a big choice besides taking the pawn on e5, but he will not be able to hold on to the e4-pawn for long. }
4... O-O 5. Nd3
{ The knight can retreat to d3 immediately or after  5.Be2  Re8  6.Nd3  , which probably transposes to the current variation after a few moves. }
5... Bxc3 6. dxc3 Nxe4 7. Be2
{ Artur Yusupov played this line a lot as, back in the 90s, he was an advocate at the 3... Bb4 system. After 3... Bb4, the position after 7. Be2 appears almost by force, and I believe it is slightly better for White. After all, White's bishop pair is a long-term advantage.   Play usually continues  7...Re8  8.O-O  d6  9.Re1  .  Black's b8-knight is going to d7 or c6 and Black's position is still very solid. However, considering the Petroff as a whole, this variation does offer White some hope, even if minimal. This is the reason why I would recommend 3... Nc6 instead of 3... Bb4. }
