[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 11: Petroff with 3. d4"]
[Black "Petroff 3. d4 exd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. In this position there aren't that many good moves for White, since the e4-pawn is hanging. The question is whether White should grab the e5-pawn immediately with  3.Nxe5  or play  3.d4  . Of course, a move like  3.d3  is not a serious challenge to Black. }
3. d4
{ A very serious and aggressive continuation, but I would say that  3.Nxe5  is nowadays considered to be the main line. }
3... exd4 { This move is possible, but the game becomes very direct. } 4. e5
Ne4 5. Qxd4 d5 6. exd6 Nxd6
{ The position is symmetrical but White gets some initiative due to the badly placed knight on d6. Had the knight been on f6, the position would probably have been equal. }
7. Nc3 Nc6 8. Qf4
{ White often tries to castle long and the d6-knight is not a good piece, making Black suffer in the long run. It is not much for White, never more than slightly better, but to give that for free with Black is unnecessary. White's play is easier and the position very comfortable too, which is why I would not recommend 3...exd4 for Black. }
