1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. In this position there aren't that many good moves for White, since the e4-pawn is hanging. The question is whether White should grab the e5-pawn immediately with  3.Nxe5  or play  3.d4  . Of course, a move like  3.d3  is not a serious challenge to Black. }
3. d4
{ A very serious and aggressive continuation, but I would say that  3.Nxe5  is nowadays considered to be the main line. }
3... Nxe4 4. dxe5
{ An interesting move, especially if you don't want to study all the forced lines introduced by  4.Bd3  . }
4... Bc5
{ A principled move but not to everyone's taste as the game becomes very concrete. }
5. Bc4 Nxf2 6. Bxf7+ { Everything is pretty forced. } 6... Kxf7 7. Qd5+ Kg6 8.
Qxc5 Nxh1
{ Probably this position will lead to a draw. White has quite a number of attacking options, but according to theory, Black always manages to defend. It is not easy, though, to analyze in depth every single variation, nor is it easy to play with the king on g6. }
9. Nc3 h6 10. Qc4
{ Or  10.Qd5  . Now Black has to play @@StartFEN@@rnbq3r/pppp2p1/6kp/4P3/2Q5/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1B1K2n b Q - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Kh7  . White can always give perpetual @@StartBracket@@ with  11.Qe4+  Kg8  12.Qc4+  @@EndBracket@@,  but also play for more by developing the bishop followed by long castle. Also, the knight on h1 is not going to survive and yet Black will still be an exchange up.White has a lot of initiative in this very forcing type of position, and I am not sure whether Black is really holding or not. I haven't analyzed it thoroughly as it is not my cup of tea to play a position where you can miss a hidden resource and lose immediately. Once again, maybe objectively it is enough for a draw, but most of the players opt for 4... d5 instead of 4...Bc5. }
