[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 11: Petroff with 3. d4"]
[Black "Petroff 3. d4 Nxe4 4. dxe5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. In this position there aren't that many good moves for White, since the e4-pawn is hanging. The question is whether White should grab the e5-pawn immediately with  3.Nxe5  or play  3.d4  . Of course, a move like  3.d3  is not a serious challenge to Black. }
3. d4
{ A very serious and aggressive continuation, but I would say that  3.Nxe5  is nowadays considered to be the main line. }
3... Nxe4 4. dxe5
{ An interesting move, especially if you don't want to study all the forced lines introduced by  4.Bd3  . }
4... d5 5. Nbd2
{ White's best move. The position is playable - perhaps there is not much White can fight for, but the game remains complicated. This pawn structure can be quite tricky to handle as well. When the pawn on e5 becomes weak, Black can take over the initiative. Other times, it is White who develops a dangerous attack. }
5... Nxd2
{ Not a very logical exchange, which also helps White develop, and an option I never liked when I was playing this opening. Still, I am not sure whether White can get an advantage. }
6. Bxd2
{ 6.Qxd2  ,  trying to get the queen to f4, is a very typical idea, but more common is the text move. }
6... c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. Bd3
{ Followed by O-O and I am not sure if White has something palpable, but Black has to be careful, there is always a danger of getting under attack. }
