[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 11: Petroff with 3. d4"]
[Black "Petroff 3. d4 Nxe4 4. dxe5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. In this position there aren't that many good moves for White, since the e4-pawn is hanging. The question is whether White should grab the e5-pawn immediately with  3.Nxe5  or play  3.d4  . Of course, a move like  3.d3  is not a serious challenge to Black. }
3. d4
{ A very serious and aggressive continuation, but I would say that  3.Nxe5  is nowadays considered to be the main line. }
3... Nxe4 4. dxe5
{ An interesting move, especially if you don't want to study all the forced lines introduced by  4.Bd3  . }
4... d5 5. Nbd2
{ White's best move. The position is playable - perhaps there is not much White can fight for, but the game remains complicated. This pawn structure can be quite tricky to handle as well. When the pawn on e5 becomes weak, Black can take over the initiative. Other times, it is White who develops a dangerous attack. }
5... Nc5
{ 5...Nc6  is not the most accurate response from Black, and after  6.Bb5  it is generally considered that White has pressure.   5...Be7  is a logical developing move, but it leads to an endgame where Black is facing quite a few problems:  6.Nxe4  dxe4  7.Qxd8+  Bxd8  8.Nd4  and it's not easy for Black to equalize.   Of the alternatives, I've noticed that recently some players choose the computer-looking move  5...Qd7!?  @@StartBracket@@humans would have to overcome some mental barriers before inventing such schemes@@EndBracket@@, with the idea of defending against  6.Nxe4  since  6...dxe4  would be fine now. Another reason behind Black's move is the potential idea of activating the queen via g4 and g6. It is an odd-looking continuation, but it could be analyzed further as there aren't enough games played in this position to offer a clear-cut conclusion. }
6. Nb3
{ White has various ways to get the game going. 6. Be2 is another possible move. }
6... Ne6
{ Black is preparing ...c5, ...Be7, ...O-O and...Nc6, a very logical setup. The resulting positions are playable for White, but I think Black is doing okay. }
7. c4 { 7.Nbd4  is another try. } 7... dxc4 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 9. Bxc4 Be6
{ Black is close to full equality, if not equal already.To conclude: I would recommend 4. dxe5, as White gets some play without having to memorize everything. To be honest, it is very difficult to get a playable position in the Petroff or fight for an opening advantage. White has many tries, some of them very forcing and dangerous for Black, but if your opponent is well prepared, the game often goes into a dry direction. Sometimes the positions can lack strategical content and in the hands of a skillful player, the game liquidates into arid and drawish positions. Therefore, attention has moved towards 4. Bd3, which has become the main try after 3. d4 Nxe4 nowadays. }
