1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. In this position there aren't that many good moves for White, since the e4-pawn is hanging. The question is whether White should grab the e5-pawn immediately with  3.Nxe5  or play  3.d4  . Of course, a move like  3.d3  is not a serious challenge to Black. }
3. d4
{ A very serious and aggressive continuation, but I would say that  3.Nxe5  is nowadays considered to be the main line. }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 Nc6
{ I remember very well that at the beginning of the 90s, this was a stunning novelty brought to life by the creative GM Jacob Murey. In those times when computers didn't play a major role, imagination was a key factor for the game preparation. I think Garry Kasparov showed me this move in 1994 or 1995 and it was quite a discovery for me to see this move, which is actually not bad at all. Since then, a lot of theory has emerged and it is still not easy for White to get an advantage. }
5. O-O
{ White's best attempt, as  5.dxe5  Nc5  followed by ...d6 seems to be fine for Black. }
5... d5 6. dxe5
{ This line is known to give White a slight edge and it is most probably the reason why 4... Nc6 is not so popular as of late. The knight has been developed to c6 a bit too early, especially if we consider Black's usual plan, which consists of ...Nc5, ...Be7, ...O-O, and then ...c6 and ...Nd7.Here the knight is already on c6, and according to theory White keeps some pressure.   6.c4  − If I remember correctly, Kasparov was telling me that this is an interesting way to continue. Of course, we are talking about the pre-computer era, and I wouldn't advise playing 6. c4 without having it tested first with an engine. I doubt it is a good move though, in the sense that it would lead to anything for White. }
