1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. In this position there aren't that many good moves for White, since the e4-pawn is hanging. The question is whether White should grab the e5-pawn immediately with  3.Nxe5  or play  3.d4  . Of course, a move like  3.d3  is not a serious challenge to Black. }
3. d4
{ A very serious and aggressive continuation, but I would say that  3.Nxe5  is nowadays considered to be the main line. }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5
{ Defending the e4-knight has proven to be stronger than  4...Nc6  .  White now has a choice of taking on e5 with either the pawn or the knight. }
5. dxe5 Nc5
{ Now we are going to see the plan I mentioned in the previous variation @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.O-O  d5  6.dxe5  @@EndBracket@@  for Black. I've also played this variation once or twice but, generally speaking, I think it is hard to find any line in the Petroff that doesn't have at least one or two games with my name attached. I've played this opening for many years and I remember that taking on e5 with the pawn was quite fashionable at some point for White. But Black has found a clear, clean and safe way to equalize by now. }
6. Be2
{ Another way for White to fight for an advantage is to spend a tempo to keep the bishop. }
6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Be3 c6
{ This is what I meant before. ...c6 is more to the point, compared with the 4...Nc6 line where Black's pieces lack harmonious development. Here, Black just wants to continue developing with ...Nbd7 folowed by ...f6. }
9. c4 dxc4
{ I've analyzed this line myself and I don't think Black has anything to worry about. Sure, White can try a bit but, objectively, if Black knows what to do, the advantage is out of stock for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 11: Petroff with 3. d4"]
[Black "Petroff 3. d4, 5. Nxe5 Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. In this position there aren't that many good moves for White, since the e4-pawn is hanging. The question is whether White should grab the e5-pawn immediately with  3.Nxe5  or play  3.d4  . Of course, a move like  3.d3  is not a serious challenge to Black. }
3. d4
{ A very serious and aggressive continuation, but I would say that  3.Nxe5  is nowadays considered to be the main line. }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5
{ Defending the e4-knight has proven to be stronger than  4...Nc6  .  White now has a choice of taking on e5 with either the pawn or the knight. }
5. Nxe5 Bd6
{ This line was always considered a bit dubious, if not just refuted, for Petroff standards that is. What I mean is, White's position was considered to be slightly better and White gets long-term pressure.But recently, there is a new idea in this position for Black that is worth investigating further. The lines are sharp and perfectly suited for engine check-ups. Depending on your findings and taste, these direct variations could prove handy. I just wanted to mention that the 5... Bd6 lines are not as dubious as they were considered in the past. }
6. Nc3
{ An interesting try, and another reason why 5... Bd6 was not very fashionable earlier. However, play gets very concrete again, and for the final assessment, more analysis is required. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 O-O 8. O-O Nd7 9. Re1
{ Such positions are quite dangerous for Black as White can develop a dangerous initiative. Now there is the rather odd move  9...Qh4  ,  played by a strong player in a game where Black managed to equalize, so perhaps Black can play this way. Nevertheless, 6. Nc3 is surely an interesting option. }
*

