{ The starting position of the Petroff. In this position there aren't that many good moves for White, since the e4-pawn is hanging. The question is whether White should grab the e5-pawn immediately with  3.Nxe5  or play  3.d4  . Of course, a move like  3.d3  is not a serious challenge to Black. }
3. d4
{ A very serious and aggressive continuation, but I would say that  3.Nxe5  is nowadays considered to be the main line. }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5
{ Defending the e4-knight has proven to be stronger than  4...Nc6  .  White now has a choice of taking on e5 with either the pawn or the knight. }
5. Nxe5 Nd7
{ This is also how I was playing as Black and it is by far the main move. I don't think Black has any problems in this variation. Black is equalizing, and I remember that in the 90s this was one of the most popular lines against the Petroff, which I spent countless hours analyzing. In this position White has quite a number of tries, which is why Black must be well prepared. Back then, without strong engines, evaluating the ensuing positions and drawing conclusions was much more difficult. Since then, a lot of games have been played as well, putting the line to the test, which also contributes towards having a well-informed wrap-up.Generally, Black is holding in all the lines, but the typical issues or challenges for the black player in the Petroff Defense are: it has to be analyzed accurately and it is memorization heavy. Often, the variations go as deep as move 30, and the move orders are essential too. Otherwise Black is just slightly worse. But for a diligent player who doesn't shy away from using an engine and spending a lot of time to understand the positions, this opening can prove a reliabe asset.Thus, the Petroff is quite a sterilized opening where only a few lines don't have a completely clear assessment. Strategically, the positions are quite simple: the pawn structure is symmetrical and the question is whether White is fast enough to create some problems for Black, perhaps hinting at the shaky knight on e4. If not, there is no reason for White to claim any advantage or winning chances, as the game is quite forcing. }
6. Nc3
{ A more serious attempt, and a move that has become more fashionable lately. }
6... Nxe5
{ Black can also start with  6...Nxc3  7.bxc3  Nxe5  ,  transposing. However, after exchanging on c3, Black should not continue  7...Bd6  8.O-O  O-O  9.Re1  with a quite dangerous position.   Also possible is  6...Nef6  7.O-O  Be7  . I am not sure White has that much play, but probably he can try to squeeze an opening advantage. }
7. dxe5 Bb4
{ This is one of White's problems − once again, Black needs to know the resulting forced lines as well. }
8. O-O Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bxc3 10. Rb1
{ Threatening Ba3, so Black must castle now as otherwise he will never be able to do so. }
10... O-O 11. Bxh7+ Kxh7 12. Qd3+ { A very concrete line. } 12... Kg8 13. Qxc3
{ Because Black's king is a bit weak, Black faces a certain degree of danger. White is trying to play Qg3, Bg5, and sometimes the rook can be activated via b4. }
13... a5
{ Computers are not impressed by White's menacing plans, but this is an important move, with the idea to bring the a8-rook into defense. I couldn't find anything for White in this line, but still, 6. Nc3 is a playable and interesting option. However, if Black's opening moves prove to be bullet-proof, then White must search elsewhere as the variation is quite forced. This is why many players prefer to go down the 6. Nxd7 route instead. }
