6. Nxd7 Bxd7 7. O-O Bd6
{ An important position, for Black mostly, as playing White is a bit easier. There are several tries White could go for, although none of them really works either. And yet, Black can still be put to the test in terms of memory and preparation. Petroff was practically my only weapon against 1. e4 and I had good analysis but even with serious commitment and effort, I was still getting confused now and then. I remember a rapid game against Vishy Anand in a line which I had it analyzed until draw but I just couldn't remember the exact move order and I lost out of the opening. That can always happen but if you have no memory issues then you can score a lof of draws with Black, if you are happy about it, of course. For professional players, neutralizing White's play and getting a draw out of home preparation could be a desirable outcome. But if you want to just enjoy playing chess, then I am not sure Petroff is the right choice. Analyzing every single line until a draw is not to everyone's liking, although relying on a forced draw out of the opening could be a clinical solution in certain circumstances. }
