11. Re1 c6
{ The potential strategical threat in the position lies in c4, exchanging the dark-squared bishops, and after a rook lands on e5 followed by Rae1, White will simply be better. The question is whether all of that can actually be achieved. With precise play by Black, it should not be the case. }
12. Bg5 Qc7 13. Re3 g6 14. Qh4 Rae8 15. Rae1
{ Again, we have very concrete play. } 15... Rxe3 16. Rxe3 b5
{ A long time ago already I found this important remedy for this line, after which Black equalizes comfortably in all the ensuing variations.  16...Re8  17.c4  was played in Nepomniachtchi-Yu Yangyi 2019, where White obtained a tricky position. If White's c4 is stopped, there are no real ideas White can play for. Perhaps just some tactical tricks with Be7, but objectively, Black should be able to hold. }
