[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 11: Petroff with 3. d4"]
[Black "Petroff 3. d4, 5. Nxe5 Nd7 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. In this position there aren't that many good moves for White, since the e4-pawn is hanging. The question is whether White should grab the e5-pawn immediately with  3.Nxe5  or play  3.d4  . Of course, a move like  3.d3  is not a serious challenge to Black. }
3. d4
{ A very serious and aggressive continuation, but I would say that  3.Nxe5  is nowadays considered to be the main line. }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5
{ Defending the e4-knight has proven to be stronger than  4...Nc6  .  White now has a choice of taking on e5 with either the pawn or the knight. }
5. Nxe5 Nd7
{ This is also how I was playing as Black and it is by far the main move. I don't think Black has any problems in this variation. Black is equalizing, and I remember that in the 90s this was one of the most popular lines against the Petroff, which I spent countless hours analyzing. In this position White has quite a number of tries, which is why Black must be well prepared. Back then, without strong engines, evaluating the ensuing positions and drawing conclusions was much more difficult. Since then, a lot of games have been played as well, putting the line to the test, which also contributes towards having a well-informed wrap-up.Generally, Black is holding in all the lines, but the typical issues or challenges for the black player in the Petroff Defense are: it has to be analyzed accurately and it is memorization heavy. Often, the variations go as deep as move 30, and the move orders are essential too. Otherwise Black is just slightly worse. But for a diligent player who doesn't shy away from using an engine and spending a lot of time to understand the positions, this opening can prove a reliabe asset.Thus, the Petroff is quite a sterilized opening where only a few lines don't have a completely clear assessment. Strategically, the positions are quite simple: the pawn structure is symmetrical and the question is whether White is fast enough to create some problems for Black, perhaps hinting at the shaky knight on e4. If not, there is no reason for White to claim any advantage or winning chances, as the game is quite forcing. }
6. Nxd7 Bxd7 7. O-O Bd6
{ An important position, for Black mostly, as playing White is a bit easier. There are several tries White could go for, although none of them really works either. And yet, Black can still be put to the test in terms of memory and preparation. Petroff was practically my only weapon against 1. e4 and I had good analysis but even with serious commitment and effort, I was still getting confused now and then. I remember a rapid game against Vishy Anand in a line which I had it analyzed until draw but I just couldn't remember the exact move order and I lost out of the opening. That can always happen but if you have no memory issues then you can score a lof of draws with Black, if you are happy about it, of course. For professional players, neutralizing White's play and getting a draw out of home preparation could be a desirable outcome. But if you want to just enjoy playing chess, then I am not sure Petroff is the right choice. Analyzing every single line until a draw is not to everyone's liking, although relying on a forced draw out of the opening could be a clinical solution in certain circumstances. }
8. c4 { This is considered to be the main move. } 8... O-O
{ A computerish decision − I've never really analyzed it, as I thought  8...c6  is practically forced, but  8...O-O  might be enough for equality. Still, most players go the ...c6 route as they don't like to castle short immediately. I am not sure why though. The engines suggest that Black is doing fine after castling, and if it does equalize, then 8... O-O might be simpler. After 8... c6, as you will see, Black has to memorize many lines. }
9. c5
{ I think I wasn't too happy about this move. In case of  9.cxd5  there is  9...f5  10.Nc3  Qf6  and the computer holds with Black without too many problems. Maybe @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pppb1ppp/3b4/3P4/3Pn3/3B4/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Re8  is also fine. }
9... Be7 { The bishop is a bit passive on e7. } 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3
{ White has more active pieces and hopes to get some initiative. } 11... g6
{ Statistically, the score is close to 50% in computer games, so perhaps White has nothing here. Therefore, 8... O-O could be investigated further. }
