[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ After  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  , the move  3.d4  is quite similar to the  3.Nxe5  line but perhaps a bit less forcing. And yet, the general picture is very similar to that of the mainline Petroff Defense. If Black spends hours on end pushing the engine's start button and memorizing the lines, every White try should be neutralized at the end of the day.However, there are also not many chances for Black to play for a win. 90% of the time, Black will get positions where it is not realistic to play for a win and he simply has to accurately make a draw. From a different perspective, if you are happy with this scenario, then objectively I don't see any advantage for White in the 3. d4 variation.Perhaps this is the reason why 3. Nxe5 is nowadays the main try, which we are going to have a look at in the next lesson. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 12: Petroff with 3. Nxe5"]
[Black "Petroff 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5
{ This move is quite similar to the  3.d4  line, in that the resulting positions aren't strategically complicated and they are very solid for Black. Black has no weaknesses and development generally runs smoothly. That means the only chance for White to play for an advantage is to opt for a very aggressive and forceful way of playing.In general, this is the situation not only in the  3.Nxe5  line, but in the entirety of the Petroff. That's why this is one of the only openings where I am going to be feeding you a lot of concrete lines.   Throughout this course, I normally try to provide some strategic insights into the openings we are discussing, but here there really aren't that many to give. The positions arising in the Petroff are rather 'simple' and there aren't that many different types of positions that can arise - the only exception being the 5. Nc3 variation which we will discuss in this lesson. After 5. Nc3 the lines are a bit more unbalanced and original. However, in general the nature of the Petroff from Black's point of view is such that it pretty much comes down to knowing precise sequences and tries by White. }
3... Nxe4
{ Grabbing the pawn was always considered a blunder, but in fact it is not. It is not too bad, but I don't see much sense in playing it anyway. After  4.d4  it's not clear to me if Black has anything better but to transpose back to known lines with either  4...d6  or  4...d5  . }
4. Qe2 Qe7
{ The knight can't retreat, as  4...Nf6  5.Nc6+  Be7  6.Nxd8  wins Black's queen. }
5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6 8. f4
{ If White tries to keep the pawn, Black gets quite some compensation. } 8...
Bg4
{ Even if White is objectively better here, it is not easy to play this position at all. }
