[White "Lesson 12: Petroff with 3. Nxe5"]
[Black "Petroff 3. Nxe5, 5. Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5
{ This move is quite similar to the  3.d4  line, in that the resulting positions aren't strategically complicated and they are very solid for Black. Black has no weaknesses and development generally runs smoothly. That means the only chance for White to play for an advantage is to opt for a very aggressive and forceful way of playing.In general, this is the situation not only in the  3.Nxe5  line, but in the entirety of the Petroff. That's why this is one of the only openings where I am going to be feeding you a lot of concrete lines.   Throughout this course, I normally try to provide some strategic insights into the openings we are discussing, but here there really aren't that many to give. The positions arising in the Petroff are rather 'simple' and there aren't that many different types of positions that can arise - the only exception being the 5. Nc3 variation which we will discuss in this lesson. After 5. Nc3 the lines are a bit more unbalanced and original. However, in general the nature of the Petroff from Black's point of view is such that it pretty much comes down to knowing precise sequences and tries by White. }
3... d6 4. Nf3 { The most logical move. } 4... Nxe4 5. Bd3
{ A very original idea, first played against me by Peter Leko. One of the points is that after  5...Nc5  6.Be2  White is going to push d2-d4, winning time by attacking Black's knight.   I've also played a few games against Alexander Morozevich in this line, in which I played  5...d5  . I now think that White has chances for an advantage after  5...d5  , which is why I recommend a different move. }
5... Nf6 6. O-O Be7
{ Nothing special is going on, even though it is of course playable for White. }
7. c3 O-O
{ White continues  8.h3  and then wants to play Bc2 and d4. Note that after the immediate  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/8/2PB1N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bc2  , Black can play  8...Bg4  .  While it's obviously not very dangerous for Black, this variation is playable for White and doesn't require much theoretical knowledge. For those of you wanting to play a game without much theory while keeping all the pieces on the board, and a slightly @@StartBracket@@very slightly@@EndBracket@@ better position, 5. Bd3 is an option. With Black, you also have to be ready for such lines, both mentally and professionally. Playing the Petroff, there are many lines like this one where you will have to slowly equalize. }
