[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 12: Petroff with 3. Nxe5"]
[Black "Petroff 3. Nxe5, 5. Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5
{ This move is quite similar to the  3.d4  line, in that the resulting positions aren't strategically complicated and they are very solid for Black. Black has no weaknesses and development generally runs smoothly. That means the only chance for White to play for an advantage is to opt for a very aggressive and forceful way of playing.In general, this is the situation not only in the  3.Nxe5  line, but in the entirety of the Petroff. That's why this is one of the only openings where I am going to be feeding you a lot of concrete lines.   Throughout this course, I normally try to provide some strategic insights into the openings we are discussing, but here there really aren't that many to give. The positions arising in the Petroff are rather 'simple' and there aren't that many different types of positions that can arise - the only exception being the 5. Nc3 variation which we will discuss in this lesson. After 5. Nc3 the lines are a bit more unbalanced and original. However, in general the nature of the Petroff from Black's point of view is such that it pretty much comes down to knowing precise sequences and tries by White. }
3... d6 4. Nf3 { The most logical move. } 4... Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ A very serious move, and one where as Black you need to know exactly what you are doing. It's not a very forcing line, though over the past years, as 5. Nc3 gained in popularity, a lot of theory has amassed, meaning there are some direct forcing lines as well. In general, though, the nature of the position is not very forcing, at least compared to the main line after 5. d4.   After  5.Nc3  Black has a choice between two moves. First of all, the third move  5...d5  doesn't work well after  6.Qe2  which threatens d2-d3 and forces Black to give up a pawn with  6...Be7  , for which Black doesn't get enough compensation after  7.Nxe4  dxe4  8.Qxe4  . }
5... Nxc3 6. dxc3
{ At first sight, it doesn't look like there should be a reason why White would be better in this position. But the strategic idea is that White is aiming to castle queenside in this position, when the pawn structure a2, b2, c2, c3 provides good cover for the king. If Black decides to castle kingside, White will then start to slowly push the kingside pawns and organize an attack.This is a very serious line where a lot of different setups are available for Black, which I can't cover all in detail. I will give my general opinion about the positions that arise in this variation. Before doing so, let me state that I would advise players from the white side of the Petroff to incorporate this system in their repertoire, as it's a very serious line indeed. }
6... Be7
{ Of course, castling kingside is not part of White's plan, so in order to castle on the other side of the board, White needs to develop the c1-bishop. The choice is between e3 and f4. Both have their pluses and minuses, but I am not at all sure which move is stronger. In any case, 7.Be3 is the main move for now. }
7. Bf4 Nc6
{ One of the potential downsides of 7.Bf4 is that the plan with ...Nc6 followed by ...Be6, ...Qd7 and castling queenside seriously limits White's options. }
8. Qd2 Be6 9. O-O-O Qd7
{ If White's bishop would be on e3 here, White would have more ways to fight for an advantage. Later when we're considering 7. Be3 we will see why. }
10. Ng5 { Here this is probably the only way to play for an advantage. } 10...
Bxg5 11. Bxg5 f6 12. Be3
{ Now, after  12...O-O-O  13.b3  Rhe8  ,  Black is of course extremely solid and close to equal, but not quite there. I noticed that myself in a rapid game against Teimour Radjabov. White usually tries to play Be2, h3, Rhe1, Kb2 and then starts to play on the kingside, pushing the pawns. Black remains very solid, but the plan mapped out above, as well as the long-term asset of the two bishops, together mean that the position is not completely equal. }
