3... d6 4. Nf3 { The most logical move. } 4... Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ A very serious move, and one where as Black you need to know exactly what you are doing. It's not a very forcing line, though over the past years, as 5. Nc3 gained in popularity, a lot of theory has amassed, meaning there are some direct forcing lines as well. In general, though, the nature of the position is not very forcing, at least compared to the main line after 5. d4.   After  5.Nc3  Black has a choice between two moves. First of all, the third move  5...d5  doesn't work well after  6.Qe2  which threatens d2-d3 and forces Black to give up a pawn with  6...Be7  , for which Black doesn't get enough compensation after  7.Nxe4  dxe4  8.Qxe4  . }
5... Nxc3 6. dxc3
{ At first sight, it doesn't look like there should be a reason why White would be better in this position. But the strategic idea is that White is aiming to castle queenside in this position, when the pawn structure a2, b2, c2, c3 provides good cover for the king. If Black decides to castle kingside, White will then start to slowly push the kingside pawns and organize an attack.This is a very serious line where a lot of different setups are available for Black, which I can't cover all in detail. I will give my general opinion about the positions that arise in this variation. Before doing so, let me state that I would advise players from the white side of the Petroff to incorporate this system in their repertoire, as it's a very serious line indeed. }
6... Be7
{ Of course, castling kingside is not part of White's plan, so in order to castle on the other side of the board, White needs to develop the c1-bishop. The choice is between e3 and f4. Both have their pluses and minuses, but I am not at all sure which move is stronger. In any case, 7.Be3 is the main move for now. }
