8... Nd7 9. O-O-O { Here, Black has tried almost all possible plans. } 9... Nf6
{ Nowadays this is the main continuation. } 10. Bd3
{ Logical, now that the knight has commited to f6 and can no longer bother the bishop on d3. }
10... c5
{ A very interesting and fashionable move − Black tries to organize counterplay on the queenside quickly with ...Qa5, ... Be6 and ...b5 etc. This plan has been championed by Duda, who played it for instance against Caruana and Karjakin. It needs to be analyzed carefully, as it's very concrete. }
11. Rhg1
{ Caruana, one of the biggest specialists on the Petroff, played this move. }
11... b5 12. g4 { And the game with Duda took a very sharp course. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 12: Petroff with 3. Nxe5"]
[Black "Petroff 3. Nxe5, 5. Nc3 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5
{ This move is quite similar to the  3.d4  line, in that the resulting positions aren't strategically complicated and they are very solid for Black. Black has no weaknesses and development generally runs smoothly. That means the only chance for White to play for an advantage is to opt for a very aggressive and forceful way of playing.In general, this is the situation not only in the  3.Nxe5  line, but in the entirety of the Petroff. That's why this is one of the only openings where I am going to be feeding you a lot of concrete lines.   Throughout this course, I normally try to provide some strategic insights into the openings we are discussing, but here there really aren't that many to give. The positions arising in the Petroff are rather 'simple' and there aren't that many different types of positions that can arise - the only exception being the 5. Nc3 variation which we will discuss in this lesson. After 5. Nc3 the lines are a bit more unbalanced and original. However, in general the nature of the Petroff from Black's point of view is such that it pretty much comes down to knowing precise sequences and tries by White. }
3... d6 4. Nf3 { The most logical move. } 4... Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ A very serious move, and one where as Black you need to know exactly what you are doing. It's not a very forcing line, though over the past years, as 5. Nc3 gained in popularity, a lot of theory has amassed, meaning there are some direct forcing lines as well. In general, though, the nature of the position is not very forcing, at least compared to the main line after 5. d4.   After  5.Nc3  Black has a choice between two moves. First of all, the third move  5...d5  doesn't work well after  6.Qe2  which threatens d2-d3 and forces Black to give up a pawn with  6...Be7  , for which Black doesn't get enough compensation after  7.Nxe4  dxe4  8.Qxe4  . }
5... Nxc3 6. dxc3
{ At first sight, it doesn't look like there should be a reason why White would be better in this position. But the strategic idea is that White is aiming to castle queenside in this position, when the pawn structure a2, b2, c2, c3 provides good cover for the king. If Black decides to castle kingside, White will then start to slowly push the kingside pawns and organize an attack.This is a very serious line where a lot of different setups are available for Black, which I can't cover all in detail. I will give my general opinion about the positions that arise in this variation. Before doing so, let me state that I would advise players from the white side of the Petroff to incorporate this system in their repertoire, as it's a very serious line indeed. }
6... Be7
{ Of course, castling kingside is not part of White's plan, so in order to castle on the other side of the board, White needs to develop the c1-bishop. The choice is between e3 and f4. Both have their pluses and minuses, but I am not at all sure which move is stronger. In any case, 7.Be3 is the main move for now. }
7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2
{ The choice here is mainly for Black. White's play is pretty much the same whatever Black does; castle queenside, perhaps include Kb1, push h2-h4, and start attacking with moves like Bd3 and Ng5. Once again, I would recommend you to study games in this variation of strong players: Carlsen, Aronian, Caruana and so on. }
8... Nd7 9. O-O-O { Here, Black has tried almost all possible plans. } 9... Re8
{ A useful move, waiting for White to show his cards. Depending on White's plan, Black will act accordingly. }
10. Kb1
{ The same waiting strategy that Black uses! White could also start with 10.h4 and each move carries its own nuances. }
10... Nf6 11. Bd3 Bd7
{ A plan that is becoming more and more popular. The idea will soon become clear. }
12. Rhe1 c5 13. c4 a6
{ Black intends to play ...Bc6 and ...b5 and has quite decent practical results with this plan.What can we conclude about the 5.Nc3 variation? Play is very straightforward for White, and it is quite clear what White is supposed to do in this line. Black has a much wider choice of setups and plans. If you don't know exactly what you are doing here, chances are high that you will end up in trouble. All in all, though, seeing the latest games, I feel there are more interesting ideas for Black than for White in this variation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 12: Petroff with 3. Nxe5"]
[Black "Petroff 3. Nxe5, 5. Qe2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5
{ This move is quite similar to the  3.d4  line, in that the resulting positions aren't strategically complicated and they are very solid for Black. Black has no weaknesses and development generally runs smoothly. That means the only chance for White to play for an advantage is to opt for a very aggressive and forceful way of playing.In general, this is the situation not only in the  3.Nxe5  line, but in the entirety of the Petroff. That's why this is one of the only openings where I am going to be feeding you a lot of concrete lines.   Throughout this course, I normally try to provide some strategic insights into the openings we are discussing, but here there really aren't that many to give. The positions arising in the Petroff are rather 'simple' and there aren't that many different types of positions that can arise - the only exception being the 5. Nc3 variation which we will discuss in this lesson. After 5. Nc3 the lines are a bit more unbalanced and original. However, in general the nature of the Petroff from Black's point of view is such that it pretty much comes down to knowing precise sequences and tries by White. }
3... d6 4. Nf3 { The most logical move. } 4... Nxe4 5. Qe2
{ A popular line among players who want to make a draw or play an extremely safe game. Another very safe line is  5.d3  Nf6  and now  6.d4  d5  leads to an Exchange French, which is not dangerous for Black, to put it mildly. }
5... Qe7 6. d3 Nf6 7. Nc3 Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 Be7
{ One of Black's possible plans is to play  8...Nbd7  and aim for ...g6. In any case, the structure is symmetrical, and despite White having a few extra tempi, it is not enough for White to seriously claim an advantage. Nevertheless, if you feel your opponent is not comfortable in the endgame, this could still be a line to consider. White is nominally better in this endgame but obviously not much is happening, realistically speaking. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 12: Petroff with 3. Nxe5"]
[Black "Petroff 3. Nxe5, 6... Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5
{ This move is quite similar to the  3.d4  line, in that the resulting positions aren't strategically complicated and they are very solid for Black. Black has no weaknesses and development generally runs smoothly. That means the only chance for White to play for an advantage is to opt for a very aggressive and forceful way of playing.In general, this is the situation not only in the  3.Nxe5  line, but in the entirety of the Petroff. That's why this is one of the only openings where I am going to be feeding you a lot of concrete lines.   Throughout this course, I normally try to provide some strategic insights into the openings we are discussing, but here there really aren't that many to give. The positions arising in the Petroff are rather 'simple' and there aren't that many different types of positions that can arise - the only exception being the 5. Nc3 variation which we will discuss in this lesson. After 5. Nc3 the lines are a bit more unbalanced and original. However, in general the nature of the Petroff from Black's point of view is such that it pretty much comes down to knowing precise sequences and tries by White. }
3... d6 4. Nf3 { The most logical move. } 4... Nxe4 5. d4 d5
{ On the board we have an Exchange French where Black has the 'extra' move ...Nf6-e4, which White tries to prove is in fact worse than the knight being on f6. The knight could be shaky on e4 and White will attempt to undermine it. }
6. Bd3 { Now Black has a choice to place the bishop on d6 or e7. } 6... Bd6
{ A very direct line, which is currently making it hard for white players to find an advantage. Here, the power of your engine can be decisive - at least at the top level! }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6
{ White's only advantage, given the symmetry of the position, lies in the small lead in development, which means White needs to be very quick in finding ways to attack the knight on e4 or otherwise develop some kind of initiative. Quiet moves like  9.h3  or  9.a3  would immediately lead to an equal game. }
9. Qc2
{ This was considered very dangerous in the 90s. New engines and new games, however, have shown Black has a few interesting ways to play too. }
9... Bg4
{ Computers have come up with some new ways of playing in this line as well. For example, there is  9...h6  - a very surprising move to me, but the engine statistics are fine for Black here. The idea is to simply sacrifice a pawn on e4 and play for long-term compensation. }
10. Bxe4
{ 10.Ne5  was considered bad for Black for a long time, but there is a very fresh and interesting idea  10...Be6!? }
10... dxe4 11. Qxe4 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Qh4
{ This was Black's idea, quickly regaining the pawn on d4. On top of that, Black often also simply has long-term compensation after 11. Qxe4 and can decide not to immediately regain the pawn. }
*

