{ White's only advantage, given the symmetry of the position, lies in the small lead in development, which means White needs to be very quick in finding ways to attack the knight on e4 or otherwise develop some kind of initiative. Quiet moves like  9.h3  or  9.a3  would immediately lead to an equal game. }
9. Qc2
{ This was considered very dangerous in the 90s. New engines and new games, however, have shown Black has a few interesting ways to play too. }
9... Na6
{ The main move in the position.  9...Re8  10.Nc3  Bf5  11.Re1  Na6  12.a3  is not totally satisfactory for Black according to theory. }
10. a3 Bg4
{ I played this move myself on various occasions, but at the time engines were not yet strong enough to determine if it's acceptable for Black. Play now becomes very direct. }
11. Ne5 Bxe5 12. dxe5 Nac5 13. f3 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Nc5 15. Qd4 Nb3 16. Qxg4 Nxa1
17. Bh6 g6
{ A long forced variation that looks pretty terrible for Black, but for a long time computers were unable to find an advantage. I managed to even win a game with Black here, but later on I found ways for White to gain an advantage. It's clearly a very dangerous line for Black. }
