{ This move is quite similar to the  3.d4  line, in that the resulting positions aren't strategically complicated and they are very solid for Black. Black has no weaknesses and development generally runs smoothly. That means the only chance for White to play for an advantage is to opt for a very aggressive and forceful way of playing.In general, this is the situation not only in the  3.Nxe5  line, but in the entirety of the Petroff. That's why this is one of the only openings where I am going to be feeding you a lot of concrete lines.   Throughout this course, I normally try to provide some strategic insights into the openings we are discussing, but here there really aren't that many to give. The positions arising in the Petroff are rather 'simple' and there aren't that many different types of positions that can arise - the only exception being the 5. Nc3 variation which we will discuss in this lesson. After 5. Nc3 the lines are a bit more unbalanced and original. However, in general the nature of the Petroff from Black's point of view is such that it pretty much comes down to knowing precise sequences and tries by White. }
3... d6 4. Nf3 { The most logical move. } 4... Nxe4 5. d4 d5
{ On the board we have an Exchange French where Black has the 'extra' move ...Nf6-e4, which White tries to prove is in fact worse than the knight being on f6. The knight could be shaky on e4 and White will attempt to undermine it. }
6. Bd3 { Now Black has a choice to place the bishop on d6 or e7. } 6... Bd6
{ A very direct line, which is currently making it hard for white players to find an advantage. Here, the power of your engine can be decisive - at least at the top level! }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6
{ White's only advantage, given the symmetry of the position, lies in the small lead in development, which means White needs to be very quick in finding ways to attack the knight on e4 or otherwise develop some kind of initiative. Quiet moves like  9.h3  or  9.a3  would immediately lead to an equal game. }
