[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 12: Petroff with 3. Nxe5"]
[Black "Petroff 3. Nxe5, 6... Be7 7. O-O Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5
{ This move is quite similar to the  3.d4  line, in that the resulting positions aren't strategically complicated and they are very solid for Black. Black has no weaknesses and development generally runs smoothly. That means the only chance for White to play for an advantage is to opt for a very aggressive and forceful way of playing.In general, this is the situation not only in the  3.Nxe5  line, but in the entirety of the Petroff. That's why this is one of the only openings where I am going to be feeding you a lot of concrete lines.   Throughout this course, I normally try to provide some strategic insights into the openings we are discussing, but here there really aren't that many to give. The positions arising in the Petroff are rather 'simple' and there aren't that many different types of positions that can arise - the only exception being the 5. Nc3 variation which we will discuss in this lesson. After 5. Nc3 the lines are a bit more unbalanced and original. However, in general the nature of the Petroff from Black's point of view is such that it pretty much comes down to knowing precise sequences and tries by White. }
3... d6 4. Nf3 { The most logical move. } 4... Nxe4 5. d4 d5
{ On the board we have an Exchange French where Black has the 'extra' move ...Nf6-e4, which White tries to prove is in fact worse than the knight being on f6. The knight could be shaky on e4 and White will attempt to undermine it. }
6. Bd3 { Now Black has a choice to place the bishop on d6 or e7. } 6... Be7
{ Placing the bishop on e7 guarantees less tactical risk than in the lines arising after 6... Bd6, which is one of the main reasons why I always preferred to play 6... Be7 myself.   It's possible to play  6...Nc6  as well, but that already means that Black chooses to put the dark-squared bishop on e7 next. We will consider the position after  6...Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  via the move order 6... Be7.   You should note that  6...Nc6  7.O-O  Bd6  8.c4  leads to problems for Black, as does @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n5/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bg4  8.c4  . }
7. O-O Nc6
{ I have played around a million games in this position, and I have analyzed this variation a lot. As usual in the Petroff, a lot of knowledge of concrete lines is required. It's the standard Petroff story: Black can equalize, but needs to do the homework in order to do so, while White has many different ways to fight for a small advantage. }
8. Re1 Bg4
{ There is a huge amount of theory here. Instead,  8...Bf5  leads to variations where it would be more logical to start with ...Bf5 instead of prematurely playing ...Nc6. }
9. c3 f5
{ One of the few lines in the Petroff where Black can try to play for a win. Play is very sharp. }
10. Qb3 O-O 11. Nbd2 Na5
{ Black can also try to sacrifice the pawn on b7 but it's unclear if it really gives a good game. }
12. Qc2 { 12.Qa4  Nc6  is another theoretical direction. } 12... Nc6
{ We, of course, assume White does not want to repeat moves with  13.Qb3  and make a draw. }
13. b4 a6 14. a4
{ White intends to push b5 at the right moment to kick out the knight from c6 and gain acces to the e5-square. I have played many games in the 8... Bg4 variation and believe Black has enough resources to equalize, but it's a very sharp game. }
