7. O-O Nc6
{ I have played around a million games in this position, and I have analyzed this variation a lot. As usual in the Petroff, a lot of knowledge of concrete lines is required. It's the standard Petroff story: Black can equalize, but needs to do the homework in order to do so, while White has many different ways to fight for a small advantage. }
8. Nc3 { Quite a serious move as well. } 8... Nxc3 { My preferred choice. } 9.
bxc3 Bg4 10. Rb1 Rb8
{ This position was one of the main issues in the 6...Be7 variation, so for some time I analyzed it quite extensively. I think my game against Alexander Grischuk from the 2011 Candidates tournament in Kazan still stands the test of time, and I've always preferred this way of playing over 8... Bf5, which I find more risky.Nevertheless, before playing it, one of course needs to check the latest games and analyze it properly as there are some tries for White. We can say that from White's perspective 8. Nc3 is a very pleasant and safe way to play against the Petroff, but there is no guarantee for an edge. }
