{ Placing the bishop on e7 guarantees less tactical risk than in the lines arising after 6... Bd6, which is one of the main reasons why I always preferred to play 6... Be7 myself.   It's possible to play  6...Nc6  as well, but that already means that Black chooses to put the dark-squared bishop on e7 next. We will consider the position after  6...Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  via the move order 6... Be7.   You should note that  6...Nc6  7.O-O  Bd6  8.c4  leads to problems for Black, as does @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n5/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bg4  8.c4  . }
7. O-O Nc6
{ I have played around a million games in this position, and I have analyzed this variation a lot. As usual in the Petroff, a lot of knowledge of concrete lines is required. It's the standard Petroff story: Black can equalize, but needs to do the homework in order to do so, while White has many different ways to fight for a small advantage. }
8. c4 { The main move in the position, trying to destabilize Black's center. }
8... Nb4
{ The most principled reply, and also the most popular move in the position, which requires extensive knowledge of theory. }
9. cxd5 { A very direct way of playing, but Black equalizes here. } 9... Nxd3
10. Qxd3 Qxd5 11. Re1 Bf5
{ Of course, it looks a bit scary with the king and pieces on the e-file, but practice has shown that everything is fine for Black. }
12. g4 Bg6 13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. Qxc3
{ When the move 12.g4 was first discovered, computer engines were quite weak, and I lost one game to Vishy Anand because I was following the engine's recommendation at the time. Analyzing it deeper later on, I discovered an improvement for Black which looks dangerous, but I think it still holds to this day. }
14... f6
{ It is important to cover the e5-square and the other point comes apparent when White takes the pawn on c7. }
15. Qxc7
{ 15.Nh4  Kf7  16.Qxc7  Rhe8  is something that also needs to be checked with modern engines. Perhaps they will say something that was not found by me back in those times, but I think Black should still equalize. }
15... O-O 16. Rxe7 Qxf3 17. Rxg7+ Kh8 { And Black has enough play for a draw. }
