{ Placing the bishop on e7 guarantees less tactical risk than in the lines arising after 6... Bd6, which is one of the main reasons why I always preferred to play 6... Be7 myself.   It's possible to play  6...Nc6  as well, but that already means that Black chooses to put the dark-squared bishop on e7 next. We will consider the position after  6...Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  via the move order 6... Be7.   You should note that  6...Nc6  7.O-O  Bd6  8.c4  leads to problems for Black, as does @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n5/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bg4  8.c4  . }
7. O-O Bf5
{ A new and very fashionable system. White, for now, has a very hard time proving any advantage. Of course, the line is fresh and new ideas may be found, but for now Black is holding here. Players facing the Petroff with White or wanting to adopt the Petroff with Black are advised to start by analyzing this variation. If Black is fine here, the entire 7... Nc6 variation and its abundance of theory may not need to be studied at all. }
8. c4
{ This is an important move in the position, but since most top players are playing  8.Re1  these days, I assume no advantage is to be found after  8.c4  currently.  8.Ne5  is also an interesting try. }
8... dxc4
{ Now we see one point of 7... Bf5: since the knight on e4 is protected, Black is able to take on c4. }
9. Bxc4 O-O 10. Nc3 Nc6
{ In the days when I played and studied the Petroff, this position was considered dubious because of White's next move. }
11. Re1 Nd6 12. Bf1 { Or  12.Bd3  Bf6  . } 12... Nb4
{ Machines are happy with this position. Black always manages to create enough counterplay in this variation. }
