{ A new and very fashionable system. White, for now, has a very hard time proving any advantage. Of course, the line is fresh and new ideas may be found, but for now Black is holding here. Players facing the Petroff with White or wanting to adopt the Petroff with Black are advised to start by analyzing this variation. If Black is fine here, the entire 7... Nc6 variation and its abundance of theory may not need to be studied at all. }
8. Re1 O-O 9. Nbd2 { White's main try as of late. } 9... Nd6
{ Forced, as  9...Nxd2  10.Bxf5  hands White the pair of bishops. I've mentioned before that in the Petroff, d6 is not a great square for the knight, but here it is the only move, so there isn't much choice for Black. }
10. Nf1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3
{ With the knight on f6 instead of d6, Black would equalize easily, but here it still looks a tad better for White, at least optically. In practice, Black has managed to equalize quite comfortably though, and perhaps the computer is right that the position is more or less equal. }
11... c6 { Another possible continuation is  11...Nd7  12.Bf4  Re8  . } 12. Bf4
Na6
{ Black prepares to reroute the knight to  e6  . While it looks a bit passive, nobody has as yet proven any advantage for White. If White plays a natural move like  13.Ne3  , Black will slowly neutralize the pressure:  13...Nc7  14.Re2  Ne6  15.Bxd6  Bxd6  16.Rae1  Qd7  17.g3  Rae8  and Black is fully mobilized.   Instead, the latest attempt is  13.h4  ,  after which White tries to jump in with Ng5. Nepomniachtchi used it against Wang Hao in the Candidates and he managed to win that game, although it was not because of the opening. }
