{ Concluding, we can say @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bf5  is more straightforward compared to  7...Nc6  , where White has many ways to apply pressure. As dubious as  7...Bf5  looks, there is no refutation at the moment and with that we come to an end of our discussion of the Petroff Defense.I apologize for feeding you with so many variations, much more so than we have done in previous lessons so far. However, as I've explained, knowing precise and concrete move orders is essential in the Petroff, much more so than in other opening variations that we have seen until now. That is because of the rather simple strategic nature of the opening. For a professional player this is definitely not a bad opening, as you probably possess a good memory, have good engines and work hard on your game. That is a package that could work well with the Petroff, where you have a solid position and good chances to equalize.Without that package, things are a bit more complicated. I believe this is not an opening for a non-professional chess player because as a non-professional, you normally like the game of chess, and like to play something a bit more interesting or less equalizing/drawish.For White, the good thing is the wide amount of choices that there are against the Petroff. Even if there is no objective advantage in any line, there are so many different variations where you can try to test your opponent, be it after 3. d4 or 3. Nxe5 @@StartBracket@@5. Nc3@@EndBracket@@. It is also not like Black is equalizing with ease everywhere. }
