1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ After having studied  2...Nf6  in the previous two lessons, now we are moving on to  2...Nc6  ,  the most popular move for Black after 2. Nf3. In this lesson we'll consider the 'Four Knights', which arises after  3.Nc3  Nf6  .  As I've already mentioned in my coverage of the Petroff, the position after 3. Nc3 Nf6 can also be reached via  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  and now Black's best move is  3...Nc6  , as the positions arising after  3...Bb4  4.Nxe5  are slightly better for White. So, by playing 3. Nc3 White is playing an opening which can be used against both 2... Nc6 and 2... Nf6. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ This is the starting position of the Four Knights. As mentioned previously, this variation is a tempting option for White because it provides a repertoire against the entirety of 1... e5. The only problem is that, according to the current state of theory, Black is equalizing comfortably.However, there are still some lines you can try as White even if your opponent is very well prepared and knows all the theory. In any case, in this chapter I will try to show you what I think is the best way to equalize with Black against all of White's tries here, and I will also try to show you some directions you can choose as White in order to get an interesting game with chances for an advantage.   After  3...Nf6  there are several ways that White can play the position, but the main moves are  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  . }
4. g3
{ This is an interesting and quite playable system. It doesn't lead to a tangible advantage for White, but at the same time Black cannot just force a draw and you'll get an interesting game at least. After 1. e4 e5, in many lines Black often equalizes and kills the game off, but that's not really possible here.   Now after  4.g3  Black has two principled ways of continuing:  4...d5  and  4...Bc5  . }
4... d5 { Very logical. Black immediately fights for the center. } 5. exd5 Nxd5
6. Bg2
{ I think this position, even if it is objectively equal, is a bit easier to play with White. }
6... Nxc3
{ This is what is played in most games, but I discovered that there's also a way of playing with  6...Nf6  . The line continues  7.O-O  Bc5  8.d3  Bb6  . Black probably equalizes, but as is typical for this system Black does need to be accurate and White can try to get a small advantage. }
7. bxc3 Bc5 { This is how the main line continues. } 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
{ It should be noted that the pawn on e5 is not actually hanging here. Still, while the position is close to equal, I find it a bit more comfortable to play as White. There are always some ideas on the queenside or kingside for White. }
9... Re8 { Now White can use a small tactical motif to force through d2-d4. }
10. d4 exd4 11. Rxe8+
{ Thanks to this in-between move, the pawn on d4 is not hanging. } 11... Qxe8
12. cxd4 Bb6 13. c4
{ Black now plays  13...Bg4  etc. I'm not sure if Black equalizes here or not. White has the idea of pushing the c-pawn further and it's not so easy for Black to solve all problems. }
*

