3. Nc3 Nf6
{ This is the starting position of the Four Knights. As mentioned previously, this variation is a tempting option for White because it provides a repertoire against the entirety of 1... e5. The only problem is that, according to the current state of theory, Black is equalizing comfortably.However, there are still some lines you can try as White even if your opponent is very well prepared and knows all the theory. In any case, in this chapter I will try to show you what I think is the best way to equalize with Black against all of White's tries here, and I will also try to show you some directions you can choose as White in order to get an interesting game with chances for an advantage.   After  3...Nf6  there are several ways that White can play the position, but the main moves are  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  . }
4. g3
{ This is an interesting and quite playable system. It doesn't lead to a tangible advantage for White, but at the same time Black cannot just force a draw and you'll get an interesting game at least. After 1. e4 e5, in many lines Black often equalizes and kills the game off, but that's not really possible here.   Now after  4.g3  Black has two principled ways of continuing:  4...d5  and  4...Bc5  . }
4... Bc5
{ This is a very solid option and probably the simplest way for Black to play against the 4. g3 system. I myself moved from  4...d5  to  4...Bc5  at some point, as there are less potential tactical problems to worry about and there is less theory. }
5. Bg2 d6 6. d3
{ I would advise White players to start with this move. It's not recommended to play  6.O-O  first, because in that case Black has additional possibilities such as  6...h5  followed by ...Bg4 and ...h4.   After  6.d3  there are a lot of games you can study in this variation. I think the position is equal. Of course, if I was asked whether I want to play White or Black here I would choose White, but the game is pretty much equal. }
6... a5
{ I saw that lately computers have been preferring this move over 6. .. a6. In the Lesson on the slow Italian, you'll see this idea as well - gaining space is important, whether you're White or Black.Of course, ...a6 looks safer, as you're probably not going to castle long if you advance the pawn to a5 instead. However, Black does gain the idea of advancing the pawn further to a4 with good play on the queenside. }
7. O-O O-O
{ It's also possible to try to exchange a pair of knights with  7...Nd4  followed by ...c6. White usually replies  8.h3  followed by Be3, or perhaps takes on d4 and then moves the king to h2, in order to prepare f2-f4. }
8. Bg5
{ This is a typical idea after Black castles, but I'm not sure it works here. }
8... h6 9. Bh4 Bg4
{ White's idea is that after  9...g5  there is the standard sacrifice  10.Nxg5  hxg5  11.Bxg5  and I'm not sure that Black can save himself, for instance  11...Kg7  12.Nd5  and the pin is fatal.   But instead,  9...Bg4  is a typical answer. Black wants to play ...g5 next, so White is forced to take  10.Bxf6  Qxf6  11.Nd5  Qd8  , but this should be equal. }
