[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 13: Four Knights"]
[Black "2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ I want to draw your attention to the fact that White can also play the g3 system starting with 2. Nc3. }
2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3
{ In case of  3...d5  the game will likely transpose to the Four Knights with 4. g3. For example:  4.exd5  Nxd5  5.Bg2  Nxc3   @@StartBracket@@here there is the interesting option  5...Nf6!?  too@@EndBracket@@  6.bxc3  Bc5  7.Nf3  Nc6  and we've transposed. }
3... Bc5
{ If Black wants to play the setup with ...Bc5, White has some additional options compared to the 'normal' 4. g3 system. }
4. Bg2
{ In case Black just wants to transpose to the Four Knights with  4...Nc6  , White has the additional option of  5.Nge2  .  It's not clear to me that the knight is necessarily better placed here than on f3, but at least it's an interesting option to explore. }
4... c6
{ I faced this position three times in classical chess and I played  4...c6  in all cases, which is a very direct move, preparing ...d5. }
5. Nge2
{ The main move. It seems that Black is doing fine after  5.Nf3  d5  , for example  6.Nxe5  dxe4  and Black has no problems. }
5... d5 6. exd5 cxd5 7. d4
{ The only real chance White has to fight for an advantage. } 7... exd4 8. Nxd4
O-O 9. O-O Bg4
{ This is the most accurate move. I played this position twice. The first time was against the Chinese player Li Chao in Stavanger 2016. Now some possible lines are:  10.Qd3  Bxd4  11.Qxd4  Nc6  12.Qc5  d4  is no problem at all for Black, who is very active.   10.Nde2  is what Adhiban played against me in Wijk aan Zee 2018, and it is the best move according to the machine. Now in case of  10...d4  11.h3  Bxh3  12.Bxh3  dxc3  White is a little better after taking  13.Nxc3  due to the bishop pair, but it's close to equality. Instead, I played @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp3ppp/5n2/2bp4/6b1/2N3P1/PPP1NPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qc8  which leads to a very complicated position after  11.Bg5  d4  12.Na4  Be7  .  I managed to win this game in the end, but at some point White was slightly better.To sum up, the 4. g3 system is perfectly playable for White, and it's quite an interesting choice. It's not very popular, so if you're playing it with White, in all likelihood your opponents probably don't know all the nuances of the system. White has some chances to get an opening advantage, and you don't need to study too much theory. }
