1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ After having studied  2...Nf6  in the previous two lessons, now we are moving on to  2...Nc6  ,  the most popular move for Black after 2. Nf3. In this lesson we'll consider the 'Four Knights', which arises after  3.Nc3  Nf6  .  As I've already mentioned in my coverage of the Petroff, the position after 3. Nc3 Nf6 can also be reached via  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  and now Black's best move is  3...Nc6  , as the positions arising after  3...Bb4  4.Nxe5  are slightly better for White. So, by playing 3. Nc3 White is playing an opening which can be used against both 2... Nc6 and 2... Nf6. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ This is the starting position of the Four Knights. As mentioned previously, this variation is a tempting option for White because it provides a repertoire against the entirety of 1... e5. The only problem is that, according to the current state of theory, Black is equalizing comfortably.However, there are still some lines you can try as White even if your opponent is very well prepared and knows all the theory. In any case, in this chapter I will try to show you what I think is the best way to equalize with Black against all of White's tries here, and I will also try to show you some directions you can choose as White in order to get an interesting game with chances for an advantage.   After  3...Nf6  there are several ways that White can play the position, but the main moves are  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  . }
4. d4 { A straightforward move, occupying the center. } 4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ 5...Bc5  is what Aronian played against me in Zurich 2012. We got a very interesting and entertaining game. However, this move is a bit dubious. I would advise Black to play ...Bb4 instead, after which he is doing very well nowadays. It's playable for White, but Black is equalizing after  5...Bb4  . }
