{ A very serious and very logical move. I think it would have been more popular if Black didn't have the strong reply  4...Nd4! }
4... Nd4
{ This move is doing very well. White is really struggling to find a good idea in this variation. The only issue for Black is that he needs to be aware of all the theoretical details.The move 4... Nd4 was discovered by Akiba Rubinstein, a very strong and influential player from the early 20th century. I would recommend that you study his games, as he was a great positional player and made many discoveries, not just in the opening but in general in the strategy of chess.If you want to clearly equalize, you need to analyze and memorize some variations here, but at the moment White is struggling to find any constructive ideas after 4... Nd4. }
5. Nxd4
{ This is an old, well-known line, but it's only used nowadays if White wants to make a draw due to the following sequence. }
5... exd4 6. e5 dxc3 7. exf6
{ Now Black should not take  7...cxd2+  because the position after  8.Bxd2  is dangerous. White would get a powerful initiative for the pawn. }
7... Qxf6
{ After  8.dxc3  the position becomes very drawish. For instance, Black can play  8. ..Qe5+  and White often replies  9.Qe2  followed by the exchange of queens. But Black can also play @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pppp1ppp/5q2/1B6/8/2P5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bc5  , which I played twice and I even managed to win a game in this line against Nigel Short. But in any case Black has no problems at all. }
