{ This move is doing very well. White is really struggling to find a good idea in this variation. The only issue for Black is that he needs to be aware of all the theoretical details.The move 4... Nd4 was discovered by Akiba Rubinstein, a very strong and influential player from the early 20th century. I would recommend that you study his games, as he was a great positional player and made many discoveries, not just in the opening but in general in the strategy of chess.If you want to clearly equalize, you need to analyze and memorize some variations here, but at the moment White is struggling to find any constructive ideas after 4... Nd4. }
5. Ba4
{ This used to be the main line, but I would not recommend White players to play this move, as Black has too many good options which lead to dangerous positions for White. So, as White, you would need to know a lot of theory, and even then you probably don't get more than an equal position. }
5... Bc5 6. Nxe5 O-O
{ You can see that the knight on d4 is very dangerous. If White would just castle here, for example, then ...d6 followed by ...Bg4 is difficult to deal with for White, who can even get mated very quickly.   The main line continues  7.Nd3  Bb6  8.e5  Ne8  9.Nd5  d6  10.Ne3  c6  11.c3  Nf5  .  White is a pawn up, but his development is lagging. The knight on d3 is also not helping. White is not worse objectively, but you have to enjoy playing with an undeveloped queenside and a bad knight on d3. }
