1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ After having studied  2...Nf6  in the previous two lessons, now we are moving on to  2...Nc6  ,  the most popular move for Black after 2. Nf3. In this lesson we'll consider the 'Four Knights', which arises after  3.Nc3  Nf6  .  As I've already mentioned in my coverage of the Petroff, the position after 3. Nc3 Nf6 can also be reached via  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  and now Black's best move is  3...Nc6  , as the positions arising after  3...Bb4  4.Nxe5  are slightly better for White. So, by playing 3. Nc3 White is playing an opening which can be used against both 2... Nc6 and 2... Nf6. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ This is the starting position of the Four Knights. As mentioned previously, this variation is a tempting option for White because it provides a repertoire against the entirety of 1... e5. The only problem is that, according to the current state of theory, Black is equalizing comfortably.However, there are still some lines you can try as White even if your opponent is very well prepared and knows all the theory. In any case, in this chapter I will try to show you what I think is the best way to equalize with Black against all of White's tries here, and I will also try to show you some directions you can choose as White in order to get an interesting game with chances for an advantage.   After  3...Nf6  there are several ways that White can play the position, but the main moves are  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  . }
4. Bb5
{ A very serious and very logical move. I think it would have been more popular if Black didn't have the strong reply  4...Nd4! }
4... Nd4
{ This move is doing very well. White is really struggling to find a good idea in this variation. The only issue for Black is that he needs to be aware of all the theoretical details.The move 4... Nd4 was discovered by Akiba Rubinstein, a very strong and influential player from the early 20th century. I would recommend that you study his games, as he was a great positional player and made many discoveries, not just in the opening but in general in the strategy of chess.If you want to clearly equalize, you need to analyze and memorize some variations here, but at the moment White is struggling to find any constructive ideas after 4... Nd4. }
5. Ba4
{ This used to be the main line, but I would not recommend White players to play this move, as Black has too many good options which lead to dangerous positions for White. So, as White, you would need to know a lot of theory, and even then you probably don't get more than an equal position. }
5... c6 { This was how I played this variation. } 6. Nxe5
{ If White castles  6.O-O  then  6...a5!?  is considered to be a strong reply, threatening to trap the a4-bishop with ...b5, but even the immediate  6...b5  7.Bb3  Nxb3  8.axb3  followed by  8...d6  is fine for Black in my opinion. This is why 6. Nxe5 is considered to be White's only real try for an advantage, even though it is very dangerous. }
6... d5
{ I played  6...d6  myself, when the line continues  7.Nf3  Bg4  8.d3  d5  .  There is some theory here and Black is doing perfectly fine. But maybe the immediate 6... d5 is even simpler, a move which is approved by the computer. }
7. d3
{ Here, for instance,  7.exd5  Bd6  followed by castling is already very dangerous for White. Black develops a powerful initiative. }
7... Bd6 8. Nf3
{ If  8.f4  then  8...Bc5  is very annoying, making it hard for White to get castled. As you can see, in many of these lines Black gets a nice initiative for the pawn and White has to be very careful. }
8... Nxf3+ 9. gxf3
{ This recapture is necessary, as  9.Qxf3?  already loses material after  9...d4  followed by either ...Bg4 and/or ...Qa5+. }
9... O-O 10. Bb3 Re8
{ Black has a long-term initiative here and has very good compensation. In a practical sense, White's position is much more difficult to play. This is one of the reasons why, in my opinion, 5. Ba4 is not a very appealing move. }
