{ What can I say about the Four Knights? The line with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  will lead to an interesting game - not an advantage for White necessarily, but at least it will give White a game. Meanwhile, against a well-prepared Black player it's difficult to obtain any advantage after either  4.d4  or  4.Bb5  .   In the line with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d4  exd4  5.Nxd4  Bb4  ,  Black has a choice between playing either the old main line with ...O-O followed by ...d5, obtaining a normal game, or trying to make a forced draw by playing an early ...d5 followed by ...Bg4.   Finally, the variation @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bb5  would be quite playable for White, if not for the line  4...Nd4!  5.Bc4  Bc5!  If Black knows the theory, he can equalize, if not force a direct draw. I don't see any ways here for White to fight for an advantage without taking huge risks. }
