[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ It is time for us to examine the Scotch,  3.d4  ,  which is a very serious opening. Just before we dive into the Scotch, though, let's see a couple more sidelines for White after 2. Nf3 Nc6. }
3. g3
{ A possible move that often transposes to variations we've seen in the previous Lesson  @@StartBracket@@perhaps you remember the setup in the Four Knights where White plays g3@@EndBracket@@, with a very similar type of play. }
3... Nf6 { The most logical continuation, simply developing. } 4. d3
{ 4.Nc3  would directly transpose to the Four Knights. } 4... Bc5
{ Also possible is  4...d5  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Bc5  .  Most likely, White will end up playing Nc3 sooner or later, landing into the aforementioned type of position we have checked already in the Four Knights lesson. }
5. Bg2 d6 6. c3
{ Again,  6.Nc3  would transpose to the Four Knights, but with the text move White intends to take the game into Italian-style play. }
6... a5
{ It is important to note that this is much more precise than  6...a6  .  After ...a6 we get a typical situation for the Italian, where White can get b4 in and apply pressure. In that case I am not sure Black will manage to solve all opening problems and equalize. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Re8
{ A standard position, which you'll see more of in the Italian, where d3-d4 is not really working well. Sometimes opening the center like this is punished tactically, but often Black can rely on positional play as well. }
9. a4
{ Preventing ...a4. If  9.Nbd2  Black plays  9...a4  . This is one of Black's main plans, gaining space on the queenside, with a fine position. }
9... h6
{ Black is playing healthy moves, preparing for a ...d5 break in the center. The position is playable for White, but no more than that. For instance,  10.Be3  would be a safe choice, but it's also difficult to claim an advantage after exchanging the dark-squared bishops. }
10. Na3 Be6 { Computers are quite happy to keep developing naturally. } 11. Nb5
d5 { Breaking through in the center. } 12. exd5 Bxd5
{ According to statistics, Black is doing fine in these lines. To summarize, the 3. g3 system is playable, but I doubt it will yield anything special for White. }
