1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ This is an old line. It can be used as a surprise weapon by White from time to time. Even Magnus Carlsen employed it against Harikrishna in Wijk aan Zee 2013 and he won the game. Black needs to know the moves and plans, of course, but has a few ways to get an acceptable position. }
3... Nf6
{ Apart from the mainline with  3...d5  , this is also an okay way for Black to play. }
4. d4 Nxe4 5. Bd3
{ To be on the safe side, White can play this instead of  5.d5  . } 5... d5 6.
Nxe5 Nxe5 7. dxe5
{ We are getting into the Petroff all of a sudden, but White has played c2-c3, which is not such a useful move. }
7... Bc5 { The position seems to be equal. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 14: Scotch"]
[Black "3. c3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ This is an old line. It can be used as a surprise weapon by White from time to time. Even Magnus Carlsen employed it against Harikrishna in Wijk aan Zee 2013 and he won the game. Black needs to know the moves and plans, of course, but has a few ways to get an acceptable position. }
3... Nf6
{ Apart from the mainline with  3...d5  , this is also an okay way for Black to play. }
4. d4 Nxe4 5. d5 { This is what is recommended by theory. } 5... Bc5
{ A very computer-ish response, which leads to interesting play.  5...Ne7  6.Nxe5  Ng6  is also very close to equality, but at least it is White who is calling the shots. }
6. dxc6 Bxf2+ 7. Ke2 Bb6 8. Qd5 Nf2
{ The best moves according to the engines @@StartBracket@@at least some years ago@@EndBracket@@. It is hard to attach a human explanation to the computer's brute calculation. Perhaps nowadays the latest programs can come up with different moves.   Play continues with  9.Rg1  O-O  10.cxb7  Bxb7  11.Qxb7  Qf6  .  There are quite a large number of games in this position, making it an interesting variation to play and analyze. Black is two pieces down, but plays as if nothing is wrong with his position. Actually, statistically speaking, Black is doing fine as well. Play is exciting and fascinating. }
