1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ This is an old line. It can be used as a surprise weapon by White from time to time. Even Magnus Carlsen employed it against Harikrishna in Wijk aan Zee 2013 and he won the game. Black needs to know the moves and plans, of course, but has a few ways to get an acceptable position. }
3... d5
{ I think this is the simplest route to equality and it's what I would recommend. }
4. Qa4
{ A strange move to play in the opening. The idea is that if Black plays  4...dxe4  , White has  5.Nxe5  . Black can still continue with  5...Qd5  , but the resulting position is considered to be better for White by theory.   Instead,  4.Bb5  does not work so well:  4...dxe4  5.Nxe5  Qg5  6.Qa4  Qxg2  . The position is very sharp, but this time Black seems to prevail in the complications. }
4... f6
{ A very solid choice. I would also recommend that you analyze  4...Bd7  , which is a very direct way of approaching this opening. Usually, this is not played in human practice, but the resulting positions are very interesting. After  5.exd5  Nd4  Black has compensation for the pawn, for instance  6.Qd1  Nxf3+  7.Qxf3  Nf6  8.Bc4  e4  9.Qe2  Bd6  with an unclear position. Black has quite some play for the material investment in this aggressive variation. }
5. d3 Be6 { Black can also start with  5...Ne7  . } 6. Be2 Bd6
{ A very solid setup and the simplest, in my opinion. Black's setup is based on ... Ne7 and ...O-O next. }
7. exd5 Bxd5 8. d4
{ White has to react fast to not end up in a worse position, since 4.Qa4 was a rather ambitious opening approach. }
8... exd4 9. cxd4 Ne7 10. Nc3 Bf7
{ Followed by ...O-O. The position is equal, I don't see any problems for Black. }
