[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 14: Scotch"]
[Black "Scotch: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ A very dangerous, logical and serious move. The Scotch is very interesting and leads to complicated positions in many lines. It makes Black's life quite difficult. Facing this opening is not easy, as White has many ways of playing it.In the beginning of the 90s, Kasparov contributed to the rebirth of this variation. He started playing the Scotch against Karpov, even though this opening was out of fashion at that time. Kasparov found many new ideas and won many games too, as this opening suited his playing style. Also, he emphasized how important home preparation is in the Scotch - as was usual during Garry's long career, his preparation was impeccable. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4
{ White has control over the center and if his development can be completed smoothly, White is simply better. But nowadays computers 'spoil the fun' for White, especially in the main line, which is good news for Black and for professional players.At the top level it is possible to analyze everything in depth with strong engines, to memorize forced lines and dare to play them. On the club level, though, going for the Scotch is a very good choice as White if you like sharp and original play. The positions are often non-trivial and not easy to play @@StartBracket@@for either side@@EndBracket@@, but there is often a strategical danger for Black, especially in the  4...Nf6  lines.Concerning Black when facing this opening: the forcing variations should be studied meticulously. Just playing based on general opening principles will lead to a worse position for Black. The theory must be known, but if Black does know it, there is nothing to worry about either.The Scotch is a bit out of fashion these days, because White is struggling finding an advantage - especially in the main line, which is  4...Nf6  . At the top level this opening is currently undergoing a crisis in finding ideas for White. And since Black has to rely on memory in many lines anyway, I would recommend going for the most principled and straighforward choice which I already mentioned @@StartBracket@@  4...Nf6  @@EndBracket@@. Going for the main lines gives Black the chance to fight for the initiative as well.However,  4...Bc5  is a solid choice too, and there is nothing wrong with it. The issue is that it gives White multiple different options to fight for an advantage.I've played both  4...Nf6  and  4...Bc5  many years ago, when computers were not where they are now. The positions after  4...Nf6  are so original and unique that when I was preparing for the match in 2000 against Garry Kasparov, I was afraid to emerge in such messy waters against him. Losing out of the opening was not on my agenda, so I was actually preparing the  4...Bc5  line instead.Later, the state of theory changed a bit, and at some point I moved to  4...Nf6  and won quite a lot of games with it against various strong players. I have nothing to complain about with Black, playing  4...Nf6  against the Scotch! }
