[Black "Scotch 4... Bb4+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ A very dangerous, logical and serious move. The Scotch is very interesting and leads to complicated positions in many lines. It makes Black's life quite difficult. Facing this opening is not easy, as White has many ways of playing it.In the beginning of the 90s, Kasparov contributed to the rebirth of this variation. He started playing the Scotch against Karpov, even though this opening was out of fashion at that time. Kasparov found many new ideas and won many games too, as this opening suited his playing style. Also, he emphasized how important home preparation is in the Scotch - as was usual during Garry's long career, his preparation was impeccable. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4
{ White has control over the center and if his development can be completed smoothly, White is simply better. But nowadays computers 'spoil the fun' for White, especially in the main line, which is good news for Black and for professional players. }
4... Bb4+
{ I've played this system myself, which is probably the best one from all the sidelines @@StartBracket@@compared to the mainlines of  4...Bc5  and  4...Nf6  @@EndBracket@@. I believe that White is slightly better with perfect play, but still, it is a decent and playable line that avoids large chunks of theory. }
5. c3 Bc5
{ It looks very odd to give up a tempo like that, but in many lines it is important that White cannot develop the knight to c3 any longer. I played this variation in the World Cup 2013 against Vachier-Lagrave, which I managed to win in the semi-final, in a tiebreak game. }
6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3
{ Maxime didn't play very well and actually lost rather quickly. } 7... Qh4 8.
Qe2 { Or  8.Qf3  . } 8... Nf6
{ As shaky as it looks, it is perfectly playable for Black. } 9. h3
{ Perhaps the most critical continuation, stopping ...Ng4. } 9... O-O
{ Of course Black's strategy is daring, yet it is risky at the same time with the queen on h4. On the other hand, if ...d5 can be played soon, Black will be doing well. }
10. g3 { The most principled line. } 10... Qh5
{ Exchanging queens cannot be too promising for White. } 11. g4 Qe5 12. g5 Ne8
13. f4 Qe7
{ White has gained a lot of space, but the king is still in the center and there are also certain development issues. }
14. Nd2 d5
{ This is how play continues. The line is very sharp, and at the time I was using it, I considered it perfectly playable for Black. }
