1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ A very dangerous, logical and serious move. The Scotch is very interesting and leads to complicated positions in many lines. It makes Black's life quite difficult. Facing this opening is not easy, as White has many ways of playing it.In the beginning of the 90s, Kasparov contributed to the rebirth of this variation. He started playing the Scotch against Karpov, even though this opening was out of fashion at that time. Kasparov found many new ideas and won many games too, as this opening suited his playing style. Also, he emphasized how important home preparation is in the Scotch - as was usual during Garry's long career, his preparation was impeccable. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4
{ White has control over the center and if his development can be completed smoothly, White is simply better. But nowadays computers 'spoil the fun' for White, especially in the main line, which is good news for Black and for professional players. }
4... Bc5
{ A solid system, against which White has quite a number of options. It leads to less forcing variations than 4... Nf6, but I wouldn't mind playing the Scotch as White if I knew beforehand that Black will go for 4... Bc5.From the choice that White has in this position, three continuations are dangerous and all three give chances for an opening advantage. }
5. Be3 { The most logical way of playing, threatening Nxc6. } 5... Qf6 6. c3
Nge7
{ A perfectly playable line, which can be deduced by the fact that a large number of games have been played in this position, leading to long theoretical discussions. White has tried almost every legal move in this position, and I will show some of them.Obviously, if you are on Black's side, you should become very familiar with the ensuing variations. If White manages to finish development, he will naturally be slightly better. Therefore, Black has to be very precise and push ...d5 in the right moment, which means he needs to know many forced lines. }
7. Bc4
{ The old main line. It's also possible to play  7.Bb5  , which looks rather odd. Now the best continuation is  7...O-O  8.O-O  Bb6  9.a4  d6  10.Re1  . White has some chances for an opening advantage here as well. }
7... Ne5
{ Play requires speed and Black tries to get ...d5 in fast, otherwise, if White develops unhindered, the position will be worse for Black. For instance, after f4 the queen on f6 will be misplaced. }
8. Be2
{ If allowed, White's next move will be f4, hitting the exposed e5-knight.  8.Bb3  is less accurate because of  8...Qa6  ,  threatening ...Nd3+ and trying to stop White from castling short. Additionally, Black has the simple  8...d6  followed by ...Ng4. }
8... Qg6 9. O-O d6
{ Black is just in time to stop f4 since the pawn on e4 is hanging, while ...Bh3 is also on the cards. }
10. f3 O-O 11. Nd2
{ This is one of the most important positions in the 5.Be3 variation. } 11...
d5
{ After checking computer games, I noticed that  11...f5  is doing well, statistically, so it could be worth investigating as well. }
12. Kh1
{ Theory goes on and on from here on. White is pressing a bit but if Black is well prepared, the positions should boil down to equality. And yet, it is not an easy line to face as Black. }
