[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ A very dangerous, logical and serious move. The Scotch is very interesting and leads to complicated positions in many lines. It makes Black's life quite difficult. Facing this opening is not easy, as White has many ways of playing it.In the beginning of the 90s, Kasparov contributed to the rebirth of this variation. He started playing the Scotch against Karpov, even though this opening was out of fashion at that time. Kasparov found many new ideas and won many games too, as this opening suited his playing style. Also, he emphasized how important home preparation is in the Scotch - as was usual during Garry's long career, his preparation was impeccable. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4
{ White has control over the center and if his development can be completed smoothly, White is simply better. But nowadays computers 'spoil the fun' for White, especially in the main line, which is good news for Black and for professional players. }
4... Bc5
{ A solid system, against which White has quite a number of options. It leads to less forcing variations than 4... Nf6, but I wouldn't mind playing the Scotch as White if I knew beforehand that Black will go for 4... Bc5.From the choice that White has in this position, three continuations are dangerous and all three give chances for an opening advantage. }
5. Nxc6 { Kasparov's choice after he abandoned  5.Be3  . } 5... Qf6
{ By threatening mate on f2, Black intends to recapture on c6 with the d-pawn. After  5...bxc6  6.Bd3  White can get full control over the center with Nc3 next. Black is not fully equalizing in these positions, which is why 5... Qf6 is preferred. }
6. Qd2
{ Kasparov found some interesting new ideas in the 6. Qd2 line back in the 90s. }
6... dxc6 7. Nc3 Be6
{ The pawn structure is in White's favor, but Black is very active too. This position was considered playable and fine for Black, until the moment Kasparov discovered  8.Na4  . }
8. Na4
{ A weird move, but it can cause Black a few problems. The variations tend to get very complicated and theory must be mapped out carefully. }
8... Rd8
{ Another line is  8...Bd6  9.Qe3  Nh6  10.h3  .  It is clear that Black has a much better development, but White's structure has the potential to advance with f4 and g4. Black has to respond quickly by creating counterplay. }
9. Bd3 Bd6 { 9...Bd4  is also possible. } 10. f4
{ Play now becomes very concrete and complicated. } 10... Nh6 11. e5
{ Black's idea is based on the fact that this tactic doesn't quite work for White. }
11... Bxe5 12. fxe5 Qh4+ 13. Qf2 Qxa4 14. Bxh6 gxh6
{ Probably, this position is equal. After @@StartFEN@@3rk1nr/ppp2ppp/2pbbq2/8/N3PP2/3B4/PPPQ2PP/R1B1K2R b KQk - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nh6  White doesn't have to push e5, of course, and the position is quite tricky for both sides. Black is in strategical danger − if White manages to develop and coordinate the pieces, White will enjoy a superior position.On the other hand, White is in tactical danger due to a lack of development @@StartBracket@@the knight is misplaced on a4@@EndBracket@@. Further and deeper analysis is required for both sides, especially since the final evaluation is quite unclear. }
