[Black "Scotch 4... Bc5 5. Nb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ A very dangerous, logical and serious move. The Scotch is very interesting and leads to complicated positions in many lines. It makes Black's life quite difficult. Facing this opening is not easy, as White has many ways of playing it.In the beginning of the 90s, Kasparov contributed to the rebirth of this variation. He started playing the Scotch against Karpov, even though this opening was out of fashion at that time. Kasparov found many new ideas and won many games too, as this opening suited his playing style. Also, he emphasized how important home preparation is in the Scotch - as was usual during Garry's long career, his preparation was impeccable. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4
{ White has control over the center and if his development can be completed smoothly, White is simply better. But nowadays computers 'spoil the fun' for White, especially in the main line, which is good news for Black and for professional players. }
4... Bc5
{ A solid system, against which White has quite a number of options. It leads to less forcing variations than 4... Nf6, but I wouldn't mind playing the Scotch as White if I knew beforehand that Black will go for 4... Bc5.From the choice that White has in this position, three continuations are dangerous and all three give chances for an opening advantage. }
5. Nb3
{ This continuation is considered to be the most dangerous nowadays. For quite a long time, Nb3 was regarded as harmless, but in modern days it has become a very serious line. You could include 5. Nb3 in your repertoire and check these lines before even looking at White's alternatives, since here there is much less theory. And again, things are not easy for Black. Consequently, as Black, the 5. Nb3 variation has to be studied carefully, to avoid ending up in a worse position. }
5... Bb4+
{ Black is losing a tempo but wants to provoke c3, taking away the square from the knight on b1. }
6. c3
{ Actually, I am not sure whether the position after  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.Bd3  is completely okay for Black. At some point Black will play ...Bxc3+ followed by ...d6, but White will push f4 and castle short. The game is complicated. }
6... Be7 7. Bf4
{ The preferred choice of computers, but  7.f4  d6  8.Bd3  is also an interesting choice. }
7... d6 8. Bc4 Nf6 9. N1d2
{ Followed by castle and, at least statistically, White is doing well in the games played by computers. Probably, Black doesn't get enough munition to fully equalize, which is the biggest danger in this structure where White has control in the center. Without ...d5 under good circumstances, very often Black will have to defend a worse position. }
