[White "Lesson 14: Scotch"]
[Black "Scotch 4... Nf6, 6. Qe2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ A very dangerous, logical and serious move. The Scotch is very interesting and leads to complicated positions in many lines. It makes Black's life quite difficult. Facing this opening is not easy, as White has many ways of playing it.In the beginning of the 90s, Kasparov contributed to the rebirth of this variation. He started playing the Scotch against Karpov, even though this opening was out of fashion at that time. Kasparov found many new ideas and won many games too, as this opening suited his playing style. Also, he emphasized how important home preparation is in the Scotch - as was usual during Garry's long career, his preparation was impeccable. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4
{ White has control over the center and if his development can be completed smoothly, White is simply better. But nowadays computers 'spoil the fun' for White, especially in the main line, which is good news for Black and for professional players. }
4... Nf6
{ Directly attacking the pawn on e4 forces White to choose from fewer options. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. Qe2
{ This is a move I faced more than once as Black. White's idea is to meet  6...Qe7  with  7.Nc3  ,  since rushing with e4-e5 is not needed. }
6... d5
{ A very aggressive try. Instead, I played  6....d6  against Nakamura, London 2012, followed by ...Be7, got a nice position and won the game too. It is a playable line but probably White has some chances for a plus in the opening. For obvious reasons, White's main issue is the queen on e2. With the f1-bishop on d3 we would have a different story, where Black would be slightly worse. If you don't want to dive into complicated and long forcing lines, playing 6... d6 as Black is a viable solution. }
7. exd5+ Be7 8. dxc6 O-O
{ Of course, and I repeated it many times, after careful analysis and investigations, Black should be able to equalize in all the lines. It is a very straightforward way of playing and if you are well prepared, that would probably be enough to hold the balance and spoil all the fun for White. }
