8. c4
{ The main move, against which Black has a choice between two major theoretical variations. Apart from  8.h4  there aren't really any alternatives for White. Both  8.Nd2  and  8.g3  are considered dubious because White will have to play c2-c4 sooner or later anyway, and delaying it gives Black the luxury of choice to face c4 on better terms. After both @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/8/8/PPP1QPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nd2  g6  and @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/8/8/PPP1QPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.g3  g6  Black is considered to be doing fine. }
8... Nb6
{ This is a good choice and the line I played myself initially, after which I switched to  8...Ba6  . I didn't switch because there were real problems for Black after  8...Nb6  , but  8...Ba6  seems to give White less room for finding new ideas. }
9. Nd2
{ Black has lots of different options once again. Generally, the knight is better placed on c3, but from d2 is covering the c4-pawn. }
9... Bb7
{ One of the possible and logical moves, leading to unclear positions. } 10. b3
g6 11. Bb2 Bg7
{ One of the natural and main ideas at Black's disposal in this system is to develop with ...g6 followed by ...Bg7. In general, in this set of positions with 4... Nf6 and 8... Nb6 or 8... Ba6, ...g6 is one of the most important concepts for Black. }
12. O-O-O O-O-O 13. f4 c5
{ We've landed in a very unbalanced position. Black is better developed, but White has the better pawn structure. Also, the knight on b6 could cause further issues for Black. If White manages to stop ...d6 or ...f6, Black can end up just being worse. But if Black is first and gets ...d6 in, the tables can turn quickly in this double-edged position.   Now after  14.Nf3  Rhe8  the position is approximately equal according to the computer. }
