[Black "Scotch 4... Nf6, 8. c4 Nb6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ A very dangerous, logical and serious move. The Scotch is very interesting and leads to complicated positions in many lines. It makes Black's life quite difficult. Facing this opening is not easy, as White has many ways of playing it.In the beginning of the 90s, Kasparov contributed to the rebirth of this variation. He started playing the Scotch against Karpov, even though this opening was out of fashion at that time. Kasparov found many new ideas and won many games too, as this opening suited his playing style. Also, he emphasized how important home preparation is in the Scotch - as was usual during Garry's long career, his preparation was impeccable. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4
{ White has control over the center and if his development can be completed smoothly, White is simply better. But nowadays computers 'spoil the fun' for White, especially in the main line, which is good news for Black and for professional players. }
4... Nf6
{ Directly attacking the pawn on e4 forces White to choose from fewer options. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ An important reply, otherwise White is simply better. } 7. Qe2
{ A forced reaction, since  7.f4  is met by  7...d6  . } 7... Nd5
{ The tabyia of the 4...Nf6 variation, developed by Kasparov back in the 90s, who scored many points in this line. He had a very good feeling for these unbalanced positions but, obviously, theory has developed significantly since that time. It seems that nowadays White is struggling to find even the slightest advantage at top-level chess. However, the position remains very interesting, sharp and unbalanced, making it perfectly suitable for club-level play.The price of each move is very high − one inaccurate move and Black can be clearly worse. In this pawn structure, the knight on d5 is often challenged by c2-c4 When Black has a choice between the pin ...Ba6 and the retreat ...Nb6, after which the knight is a bit out of play.It is more than advisable for Black to do the homework in these lines, even more so than in the Ruy Lopez. It is not possible to play the variations based on general considerations and classical principles. Black can very easily end up in a bad position. }
8. c4
{ The main move, against which Black has a choice between two major theoretical variations. Apart from  8.h4  there aren't really any alternatives for White. Both  8.Nd2  and  8.g3  are considered dubious because White will have to play c2-c4 sooner or later anyway, and delaying it gives Black the luxury of choice to face c4 on better terms. After both @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/8/8/PPP1QPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nd2  g6  and @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/8/8/PPP1QPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.g3  g6  Black is considered to be doing fine. }
8... Nb6
{ This is a good choice and the line I played myself initially, after which I switched to  8...Ba6  . I didn't switch because there were real problems for Black after  8...Nb6  , but  8...Ba6  seems to give White less room for finding new ideas. }
9. Nc3 Ba6 { The main line as of late. } 10. Qe4
{ Now Black has two options, probably enough to equalize, but still it is only White who can be slightly better. }
10... g6
{ The ensuing variations are sharp and very unclear, once again. The engine should be your best friend here, as is always the case in concrete situations. }
11. c5
{ A typical idea against the b6-knight and a6-bishop. Here I switched on my own analysis from 2012, so perhaps this is no longer relevant these days; you would have to do your own research. But I wanted to show you how the game can develop - in quite an entertaining fashion! Note that the endgame after  11.f4  f5  12.exf6  Qxe4+  13.Nxe4  Bxc4  is close to equal. }
11... Bxf1 12. cxb6 f5
{ The best move, with the idea that  13.exf6  Qxe4  14.Nxe4  Bxg2  is not playable for White. }
13. b7
{ At least according to my old analysis, this is the best continuation. } 13...
Rb8 14. Qe3
{ The line continues  14...Bxg2  15.Rg1  Bd5  16.Qxa7  Qxe5+  17.Be3  Bb4  18.Qxb8+  Kf7  .  According to my notes, this variation would lead to a draw.To summarize, 8... Nb6 is an extremely sharp line, leading to very complicated positions. White has a choice between 9. Nc3, which is a good continuation, but also 9. Nd2 or 9. b3 are playable. Most of the time the positions become double-edged, but White does get a chance to fight for advantage, especially if he is more booked up.8... Nb6 is a risky path Black is walking, but the upside is that, perhaps, there is more play here than after 8... Ba6. If Black is not afraid of this type of sharp play and wants to play for a win, then 8... Nb6 gives more options. Objectively though, 8... Ba6 is stronger and a more clear-cut way to achieve a good position. }
