{ The best continuation, in my opinion. It is riskier than 8...Nb6, but it is very concrete and according to modern theory, White is struggling to find an advantage.For the time being, Black intends to keep the knight on d5 and prepares ...O-O-O in some cases as well. The nature of play now becomes quite forcing, and White is given less choices along the way than in the 8... Nb6 variation. }
9. b3
{ The main line where White has to be ready to face a variety of continuations and setups. }
9... g6
{ White struggles to find an advantage in this line. Most top players are choosing  9...g6  , but  9...O-O-O  and even  9...g5  are viable continuations too. }
10. Ba3 { This is another idea, trying to lure the black knight to b4. } 10...
Nb4 11. Bb2 Bg7 12. a3 Nd5 13. Nd2
{ White at least has managed to get control over the b4-square. } 13... O-O 14.
O-O-O Rfe8
{ The position is very tactical in nature. However, it seems that this variation has already been sterilized in practice. There was a recent game from the Candidates 2021 between Wang Hao and Ding Liren where the players repeated a well-known and theoretical line which leads to a draw. I also analyzed this position a lot some years ago, without being able to find any advantage for White. }
15. Qf3
{ White can try to go for this line and if the opponent is not aware of all the tactical resources, things can go downhill for Black. }
15... Nb6 16. Ne4
{ The most principled move but, in fact, it leads to a forced draw. } 16...
Bxe5 17. Bxe5 Qxe5 18. Nf6+ Kf8
{ 18...Kh8  is also possible. After  19.Nxe8  , Black gives perpetual check with  19...Qa1+  and ...Qa2+. }
