8. c4
{ The main move, against which Black has a choice between two major theoretical variations. Apart from  8.h4  there aren't really any alternatives for White. Both  8.Nd2  and  8.g3  are considered dubious because White will have to play c2-c4 sooner or later anyway, and delaying it gives Black the luxury of choice to face c4 on better terms. After both @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/8/8/PPP1QPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nd2  g6  and @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/8/8/PPP1QPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.g3  g6  Black is considered to be doing fine. }
8... Ba6
{ The best continuation, in my opinion. It is riskier than 8...Nb6, but it is very concrete and according to modern theory, White is struggling to find an advantage.For the time being, Black intends to keep the knight on d5 and prepares ...O-O-O in some cases as well. The nature of play now becomes quite forcing, and White is given less choices along the way than in the 8... Nb6 variation. }
9. b3
{ The main line where White has to be ready to face a variety of continuations and setups. }
9... g6
{ White struggles to find an advantage in this line. Most top players are choosing  9...g6  , but  9...O-O-O  and even  9...g5  are viable continuations too. }
10. g3 { The old main line which leads to an endgame almost by force. } 10...
Bg7 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Bg2
{ If White develops the pieces undisturbed and manages to castle, White's position will be better due to the preferable pawn structure. Black has to be quick with generating counterplay. }
12... Rae8 13. O-O Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Qxe5 15. Qxe5 Rxe5 16. cxd5 Bxf1 17. Kxf1 cxd5
{ This endgame has been played many times. White has tried to get some advantage and indeed, is not worse nor risking much, but with two pawns and a rook against two pieces, Black is actually doing fine. }
18. Nc3 c6 19. Rd1
{ The best try for White − White wants to bring the rook to a4 or play the Nc3-a4-c5 maneuver, but that is easier said than done. Black can also get the advantage if the rooks become active and White is not cautious enough or starts overpressing. For instance, if one pair of rooks gets off the board and the black king reaches d6, it is only Black who can play for a win - White would have zero chances.If White wants to make a draw, that is possible of course, since Black doesn't have a clear-cut plan without being given opportunities by White. However, that shouldn't normally be White's dream from the opening. Still, there is some venom left in this endgame if you want to go for it as White, but care is needed too. }
19... Rb8
{ I remember that when I was preparing against the Scotch, my intention was to go for the text move. Another possible line is  19...Rfe8  - tying White's rook to d1, followed by bringing the king over to d6. For example  20.Bf3  Kf8  21.Ne2  Ke7  22.Rd4  Kd6  23.Ra4  Ra8  .  The rook is passive on a8, but Black has managed to activate the king. After  24.b4  a5  the game becomes double-edged. }
20. Rd4 { The same plan of bringing the rook to a4 is no longer valid. } 20...
Rbe8 { White should not allow the black rook to enter on the 1st rank. } 21.
Bf3
{ White should minimize the damage and go for the sad retreat  21.Rd1  ,  which is why 20. Rd4 is not an option in the first place. }
21... Re1+ 22. Kg2 Rc1
{ Black is simply better thanks thanks to the active rooks. } *

