20. Bf3 { White is preparing Rd4. } 20... a5 { A solid way of playing. } 21.
Na4
{ Black's idea becomes visible after  21.Rd4  Rb4  ,  preventing White's assault with Ra4. }
21... Kg7
{ Black plays useful moves, preparing for ...f5 and ...Kf6, asking White which are the real intentions in this ending. }
22. Nc5 Re7 23. Rd4 Rb5
{ White's idea is  23...Rb4  24.Rxb4  axb4  25.Nd3  ,  attacking the b4-pawn. }
24. Nd3 f5 25. Ra4
{ White finally got the rook to a4 but what is the follow-up? An idea for White would be to play Be2 but whenever the knight leaves, Black will have ...Rc5 available. It is hard for White to improve this position and I also don't see how exactly. Of course, there is always a degree of danger and I saw a couple of computer games where water got squeezed out of stone. }
25... Kf6 26. h4 Re4
{ Just for illustrative purposes, at some point this idea could suddenly become possible. }
27. Bxe4 fxe4
{ Out of nowhere, Black has a powerful pawn chain. After the knight moves, Black will have ...Rc5, ...Ke5, and the position remains unclear. In other words, I believe this endgame is rather equal and Black has nothing to fear if the nuances are handled correctly. }
