[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 14: Scotch"]
[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ I believe that the Scotch Defense is an excellent opening for club players, for amateurs that like interesting, tasty chess and don't shy away from diving into complicated waters. For professional level, though, something must be found for White against the main line, which is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  .   For Black, the main message is: do not be lazy, and learn the theory! This system is asking Black the toughest questions; in general, the Scotch is a dangerous opening for Black in a practical sense, which is why my advice would be to study this line and make your opponent stop playing the Scotch Defense.In fact, @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/2P5/8/PP2QPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Ba6  is the variation that convinced many players to abandon this opening. Nepomniachtchi, for instance, who liked the Scotch a lot and had very good results with it, stopped playing it precisely because of the  8...Ba6  line. But you never know, there are always new ideas being discovered in chess, and maybe White will find some interesting ideas that will resurrect the Scotch.All the other variations do give White a choice and a chance for an advantage in otherwise rich positions, but the @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/2P5/8/PP2QPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Ba6  line is clearly a problem for White. If you are playing the Scotch on a permanent basis, some original tries should be found in this system, otherwise this opening is more suited as a surprise weapon.  We will now move on to the Italian, which is a completely different picture: very positional, strategical, with small nuances depending on the move orders. I will try my best to give you a proper overview. The Petroff Defense and the Scotch Defense are very direct openings, where it is important to know by heart concrete variations. In the Italian, especially with d3 and c3, we will talk more about general ideas and principles in the resulting positions. The Italian is very popular nowadays, which makes the following lessons very important for an 1. e4 e5 repertoire. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 15: Italian Sharp Lines"]
[Black "Italian: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ In this Lesson we will begin our study of Italian, 3. Bc4. Nowadays this is the most popular move on the top level. For quite a long time, 3. Bb5 the Spanish or Ruy Lopez was the most played move after 2... Nc6, but a combination of factors has turned the tide in favor of the Italian.Firstly, the Italian used to be seen as an easy to play opening, but one where White cannot really fight for an opening advantage. However, it was discovered that the positions in the 'slow Italian' - where White plays c3 and d3 - are actually quite venomous.   Secondly and more importantly, it has become more and more difficult for White to demonstrate any advantage at all after  3.Bb5  , in multiple different lines that Black can choose: the Berlin  3...Nf6  ,  the Marshall Attack, and the Akrhangelsk ...Bc5 lines as well. Because Black can equalize in multiple ways, White players instead started to play an opening @@StartBracket@@the Italian@@EndBracket@@ where they can fight for an advantage with much less theory to study.I have a lot of experience with the Italian, and if you know your theory I don't think White has any clear advantage. In general Black is doing fine. However, everywhere White is a tiny bit more comfortable, has a little bit of pressure, and that is what top players want to achieve with the Italian - a game where Black can't make a forced draw. And of course 3. Bc4 can't be a bad move, as the a2-g8 diagonal is very good for White's bishop. So logically speaking it must be a serious move.One more note: there are so many different lines and move orders after 3. Bc4 that I cannot cover them all. I would probably need 15 more hours just to explore all the ideas and variations in the Italian.Instead, I will just give you the general state of theory, the ideas behind different systems, and my assessment of various lines. You can also help yourself by studying the games of top players in the Italian, of which there is no deficit, as almost all top players nowadays have this opening in their repertoire - with both colors!I have divided the material on the Italian into two lessons. In the current lesson we'll consider White's more direct lines, i.e. lines with Ng5 or d2-d4. Variations with d2-d3, the so-called 'slow Italian', will be considered in the next lesson. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 15: Italian Sharp Lines"]
[Black "Italian 3... Nf6 4. d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ In this position Black can either play  3...Bc5  or  3...Nf6  . Both are perfectly fine, though  3...Bc5  is more popular. The choice between  3...Nf6  and  3...Bc5  boils down to which variations you want to allow White to play. In case of  3...Nf6  4.d3  it doesn't really matter, as Black can continue  4...Bc5  and the position will be the same as after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  4.d3  Nf6  .   However, after  3...Nf6  White has the additional options of playing  4.Ng5  and  4.d4  , whereas after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  White can play lines with  4.c3  and 5. d4. I think Black is fine in all of these variations, but as Black you'll need to pick either 3... Bc5 or 3... Nf6 and study the theory of the associated sidelines. }
3... Nf6
{ As said, most players begin with 3... Bc5, but there is nothing wrong with developing the knight first. Now there are two lines we should check:  4.d4  and  4.Ng5  . }
4. d4
{ This is an old line which is no longer so popular, but as White you could still try this, as Black does need to know what he is doing. }
4... exd4 5. O-O
{ If White castles, Black can just take the e4-pawn without any issues. } 5...
Nxe4 6. Re1 d5 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3
{ A nice way for White to get back the piece, thanks to multiple pins, but Black is fine regardless. }
8... Qh5 { 8...Qa5  is also good. } 9. Nxe4 Be6
{ There is some theory here, but Black isn't experiencing any problems at all. }
