1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ In this position Black can either play  3...Bc5  or  3...Nf6  . Both are perfectly fine, though  3...Bc5  is more popular. The choice between  3...Nf6  and  3...Bc5  boils down to which variations you want to allow White to play. In case of  3...Nf6  4.d3  it doesn't really matter, as Black can continue  4...Bc5  and the position will be the same as after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  4.d3  Nf6  .   However, after  3...Nf6  White has the additional options of playing  4.Ng5  and  4.d4  , whereas after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  White can play lines with  4.c3  and 5. d4. I think Black is fine in all of these variations, but as Black you'll need to pick either 3... Bc5 or 3... Nf6 and study the theory of the associated sidelines. }
3... Nf6
{ As said, most players begin with 3... Bc5, but there is nothing wrong with developing the knight first. Now there are two lines we should check:  4.d4  and  4.Ng5  . }
4. d4
{ This is an old line which is no longer so popular, but as White you could still try this, as Black does need to know what he is doing. }
4... exd4 5. e5 { This is the main point of 4. d4. } 5... d5
{ This is the old main line of 4. d4, but I think that White can at the very least get an interesting game here, even if White can't really get an advantage. }
6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O
{ The starting position of this variation, which was considered to be fine for Black, but today's computers are not so sure about that verdict. }
9... Bc5
{ The main move. It's also possible to play  9...Be7  10.f3  Nc5  ,  but I think 9... Bc5 has a better reputation. }
10. f3 Ng5 11. f4
{ White has other options besides pushing the f-pawn, but I think this is the best. }
11... Ne4 12. Be3
{ Next White will play Nd2. Strategically Black's position is a bit dangerous - if White manages to exchange knights and the dark-squared bishops, he might get the remaining knight to c5 in the future. Therefore Black needs to play actively and try to push ...c5 and ...d4. }
12... Bb6 13. Nd2 Nxd2 14. Qxd2
{ This is the main line. Now White has a positional threat of Nb3-c5, so Black's hand is more or less forced. }
14... c5 15. Nf3 d4 16. Bf2
{ With a double-edged position. Black has the two bishops and a powerful light-squared bishop, but the bishop on b6 is not impressive to say the least, and Black's pawn structure is compromised. Therefore, I think White has some chances to get an advantage here - at the very least it's not clear-cut equality for Black. }
*

