[Black "Italian 3... Nf6 4. Ng5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ In this position Black can either play  3...Bc5  or  3...Nf6  . Both are perfectly fine, though  3...Bc5  is more popular. The choice between  3...Nf6  and  3...Bc5  boils down to which variations you want to allow White to play. In case of  3...Nf6  4.d3  it doesn't really matter, as Black can continue  4...Bc5  and the position will be the same as after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  4.d3  Nf6  .   However, after  3...Nf6  White has the additional options of playing  4.Ng5  and  4.d4  , whereas after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  White can play lines with  4.c3  and 5. d4. I think Black is fine in all of these variations, but as Black you'll need to pick either 3... Bc5 or 3... Nf6 and study the theory of the associated sidelines. }
3... Nf6
{ As said, most players begin with 3... Bc5, but there is nothing wrong with developing the knight first. Now there are two lines we should check:  4.d4  and  4.Ng5  . }
4. Ng5 { A very direct move, simply attacking the f7-pawn. } 4... d5
{ 4...d5  is necessary to prevent a disaster on f7. Actually, there is also the move  4...Bc5!?  ,  which at least doesn't lose directly, and it was quite popular at some point - in the time that computers were not so powerful yet. I don't believe that it works, though. Nobody really plays like this anymore because Black sacrifices a pawn and his king will have to stay in the center.However, there are a lot of tactics, so depending on your level you can try to surprise your opponent with 4... Bc5. But I would not recommend it against a well-prepared opponent. }
5. exd5 Na5
{ A very strange way of playing as Black, but it's necessary because  5...Nxd5  is not good as we've just seen. }
6. Bb5+
{ If  6.d3  Black is just in time to get a good game with  6...h6  7.Nf3  e4  . }
6... c6
{ There is an alternative here in  6...Bd7!?  7.Qe2  Be7  which might not be so bad for Black. Black just intends to castle and then retake the pawn on d5. I'm not sure whether this line has been refuted. This is one of those rarely played variations which might either be refuted or rehabilitated depending on what computers think of it in a few years time, since every couple of years the strength of computers increases significantly. In any case, 6... Bd7 is a move to consider. }
7. dxc6 bxc6
{ Now a very strange position arises. White is a pawn up, Black's pawn structure is weakened and Black's knight on a5 is not well-placed. However, the position is very tactical in nature, and the most important factor is that White does not have enough time to position his pieces correctly. If White had enough time to play d2-d3 then White would be practically winning, but this isn't going to happen unfortunately.The resulting variations are very complicated, and whether you play them with White or Black you need to study them very carefully. According to the current state of theory Black is doing fine, but the positions are very strange and complicated. }
8. Be2
{ This would be White's preferred way of playing, trying to play d2-d3 next. }
8... h6 { However, now White has an issue with the g5-knight. } 9. Nf3 e4 10.
Ne5 Bc5
{ Next White will play  11.c3  followed by d4, while Black will castle and take en passant on d3 as soon as White plays d4. The knight is not great on d3 and Black has good compensation for the pawn according to theory.   That's why after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/p4ppp/2p2n2/nB2p1N1/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be2  h6  , more often  9.Nh3  is played, but again a very strange position arises. Both sides will castle short and at some point Black will probably take ...Bxh3 gxh3 with an unclear position. Black has some positional compensation for the pawn, and my feeling is that the position is dynamically equal. }
