8... Nd5 { The most popular move in the position. } 9. Nf3
{ 9.h4  is also possible. } 9... Bd6 10. O-O O-O
{ If White can finish his development he will be better, but Black is quick with developing an initiative on the kingside. }
11. Re1
{ This has recently become popular on the top level, for example in a game between Wesley So and Magnus Carlsen. Black sacrifices the e5-pawn as well. }
11... f5 12. Nxe5 Qf6 13. Nf3 g5
{ Again the position is a complete mess, and I don't know what the assessment is. Black is two pawns down but has a huge advantage in development. Carlsen won the game with Black, but this doesn't necessarily mean that Black is doing fine here. You'll need to analyze this position carefully in order to understand what exactly is going on! }
