1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ In this position Black can either play  3...Bc5  or  3...Nf6  . Both are perfectly fine, though  3...Bc5  is more popular. The choice between  3...Nf6  and  3...Bc5  boils down to which variations you want to allow White to play. In case of  3...Nf6  4.d3  it doesn't really matter, as Black can continue  4...Bc5  and the position will be the same as after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  4.d3  Nf6  .   However, after  3...Nf6  White has the additional options of playing  4.Ng5  and  4.d4  , whereas after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  White can play lines with  4.c3  and 5. d4. I think Black is fine in all of these variations, but as Black you'll need to pick either 3... Bc5 or 3... Nf6 and study the theory of the associated sidelines. }
3... Bc5
{ As mentioned,  3...Bc5  is more popular than  3...Nf6  . This is because the sidelines after  3...Nf6  are considered to be more dangerous than the sidelines that White can play after  3...Bc5  . However, this is not a settled debate, and in any case I think both moves are perfectly playable for Black. }
4. b4
{ The Evans Gambit. At first sight it looks like a crazy idea which shouldn't work, but in fact it's not a bad move at all. I don't think Black can get any advantage here. It's quite dangerous for Black and he really needs to know what he is doing, otherwise he can quickly get into trouble. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3
{ White sacrificed a pawn to get an important tempo with c2-c3 so that he can get play quickly with d2-d4 and Qb3. It becomes more difficult for Black to finish his development properly. }
5... Be7 { This is what I used to play against the Evans Gambit. } 6. d4 Na5
{ A very strange move, which is the mainline here. The issue with Black's position is that he plays the 'normal' move  6...d6  , then after  7.Qb3  it is difficult to protect the pawn on f7. }
7. Nxe5
{ White can regain the pawn this way, but it takes the sting out of his play. }
7... Nxc4 8. Nxc4 d5
{ This move should equalize comfortably. That's why after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/ppppbppp/2n5/4p3/2BPP3/2P2N2/P4PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Na5  White usually retreats the bishop to either e2 or d3. There is some theory after that, but I think Black is doing quite fine in general, at least he is not worse. But at the same time it's playable for White as well. }
