3... Bc5
{ As mentioned,  3...Bc5  is more popular than  3...Nf6  . This is because the sidelines after  3...Nf6  are considered to be more dangerous than the sidelines that White can play after  3...Bc5  . However, this is not a settled debate, and in any case I think both moves are perfectly playable for Black. }
4. b4
{ The Evans Gambit. At first sight it looks like a crazy idea which shouldn't work, but in fact it's not a bad move at all. I don't think Black can get any advantage here. It's quite dangerous for Black and he really needs to know what he is doing, otherwise he can quickly get into trouble. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3
{ White sacrificed a pawn to get an important tempo with c2-c3 so that he can get play quickly with d2-d4 and Qb3. It becomes more difficult for Black to finish his development properly. }
5... Ba5
{ The most straightforward and probably the best move. If you want to 'kill' the Evans Gambit, you should play this way, though you'll need to put in significant study.After 5... Ba5 Black just wants to finish development with ...d6 and ...Nf6 and he'll just be a pawn up, so White has to hurry. }
6. d4 d6
{ Black can take another pawn with  6...exd4  , but then White castles  7.O-O  and the position becomes quite dangerous for Black, who has issues with his development. Therefore I recommend you to play 6... d6. }
7. Qb3
{ This is necessary because  7.O-O  is too slow. Almost any black move is fine - for instance, Black can play  7...Bg4  8.Qb3  Qd7  and Black is better. After 7. Qb3 Black doesn't have a very comfortable way of protecting the f7-pawn. }
7... Qd7
{ This is the most straightforward move. Now Black doesn't have to worry about the trick d4-d5, as White no longer has the check on a4 with the queen. White now has to do something; he can either castle or play dxe5. }
8. dxe5 Bb6
{ An important move. Black wants to follow up with ...Na5, which is an important resource in the Evans Gambit. This position has been reached in various high-level games, such as Nakamura-Anand London 2014, and it seems that Black is doing fine after this move. }
9. Nbd2 Na5 10. Qc2 Ne7
{ Black just wants to castle next, play ...Ng6 and so on. The bishop on b6 is a very powerful piece and I don't think White has any advantage here at all @@StartBracket@@though he is not worse either@@EndBracket@@.  10...Nxc4  11.Nxc4  d5  is probably also enough to equalize for Black. }
