{ In this position Black can either play  3...Bc5  or  3...Nf6  . Both are perfectly fine, though  3...Bc5  is more popular. The choice between  3...Nf6  and  3...Bc5  boils down to which variations you want to allow White to play. In case of  3...Nf6  4.d3  it doesn't really matter, as Black can continue  4...Bc5  and the position will be the same as after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  4.d3  Nf6  .   However, after  3...Nf6  White has the additional options of playing  4.Ng5  and  4.d4  , whereas after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  White can play lines with  4.c3  and 5. d4. I think Black is fine in all of these variations, but as Black you'll need to pick either 3... Bc5 or 3... Nf6 and study the theory of the associated sidelines. }
3... Bc5
{ As mentioned,  3...Bc5  is more popular than  3...Nf6  . This is because the sidelines after  3...Nf6  are considered to be more dangerous than the sidelines that White can play after  3...Bc5  . However, this is not a settled debate, and in any case I think both moves are perfectly playable for Black. }
4. c3 { The mainline of the Italian. } 4... Nf6 5. d4
{ 5.d3  is what we will consider in the next lesson, but  5.d4  is also a serious move. For many years it was considered to be harmless, but it is actually experiencing a new wave of popularity based on the variation  5...exd4  6.e5  . }
5... exd4 6. cxd4 { This is the old main line of the Italian. } 6... Bb4+
{ This line was played a lot in the 19th century, especially the positions after  6...Bb4+  7.Nc3  . Of course these lucky people had no computers to spoil the fun, so there were a lot of romantic sacrificial games after  7...Nxe4  . However, nowadays it is clear that Black has more than one way to be fine after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/8/1bBPP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nc3  , and  7.Nbd2  and  7.Bd2  are both considered harmless as well. }
7. Nc3
{ Nowadays this is not dangerous at all - unless Black doesn't know anything about the theory here! }
7... Nxe4 8. O-O
{ You can see that White is not averse to giving up more material. } 8... Bxc3
{ This is the easiest way for Black to neutralize White's opening play. } 9. d5
{ The best move, even though I wouldn't recommend this line as White as Black has more than one way to equalize. }
9... Ne5
{ The simplest reply in my view. There is also  9...Bf6  when theory continues  10.Re1  Ne7  11.Rxe4  d6  12.Bg5  . Black needs to know some variations here, but it seems he is at least equal. }
10. bxc3 Nxc4 11. Qd4
{ You can see why this line was attractive for White players - sacrificing material, then 9. d5 instead of taking back the piece on c3, then allowing the bishop on c4 to be captured to follow it up with 11. Qd4 regaining the piece, and so on.However, in the computer era it's not practical to play this way. If Black now simply gives back the knight, there are multiple ways in which he can get an equal position. }
11... O-O { Also after  11...f5  12.Qxc4  d6  Black is not worse. } 12. Qxe4
Nd6 13. Qf4 Re8
{ Black can continue with ...b6 and ...Ba6. White has maybe enough compensation for the pawn, but again, if someone is fighting for the advantage it is Black. }
