3... Bc5
{ As mentioned,  3...Bc5  is more popular than  3...Nf6  . This is because the sidelines after  3...Nf6  are considered to be more dangerous than the sidelines that White can play after  3...Bc5  . However, this is not a settled debate, and in any case I think both moves are perfectly playable for Black. }
4. c3 { The mainline of the Italian. } 4... Nf6 5. d4
{ 5.d3  is what we will consider in the next lesson, but  5.d4  is also a serious move. For many years it was considered to be harmless, but it is actually experiencing a new wave of popularity based on the variation  5...exd4  6.e5  . }
5... exd4 6. e5
{ This is a tricky move and quite popular on a high level at the moment. } 6...
d5
{ A very typical response to the e4-e5 advance in the Italian. Now  7.exf6  dxc4  8.fxg7  Rg8  is not good for White - Black is actually better. }
7. Be2
{ This is possible, but it leads to a more passive version of the mainline  7.Bb5  . }
7... Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6
{ On the one hand, with the bishop on e2, White is protecting himself against Black's ...Bg4 move. On the other hand, there is now no pressure on the knight on c6, which means that it's much easier for Black to execute the typical idea of ...f6, attacking the pawn on e5. }
9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 Be6
{ It's also possible to play  10...Bg4  , when after  11.Be3  the position strongly resembles the mainline with 7. Bb5. But, I prefer 10... Be6 instead, protecting d5 and preparing ...f6. }
11. Be3 f6
{ Black's typical pawn break in this structure. The position is equal and it's perfectly playable for both sides. }
