{ 5.d3  is what we will consider in the next lesson, but  5.d4  is also a serious move. For many years it was considered to be harmless, but it is actually experiencing a new wave of popularity based on the variation  5...exd4  6.e5  . }
5... exd4 6. e5
{ This is a tricky move and quite popular on a high level at the moment. } 6...
d5
{ A very typical response to the e4-e5 advance in the Italian. Now  7.exf6  dxc4  8.fxg7  Rg8  is not good for White - Black is actually better. }
7. Bb5 { The most principled move. } 7... Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6
{ This position was for a long time considered to be perfectly good for Black, as he's very active with his knight on e4 and pressure against the d4-pawn @@StartBracket@@also the bishop is coming to g4 next, etc.@@EndBracket@@.However, things are not so easy for Black. Objectively Black is fine, but Black needs to know a lot of theory, as it's not that easy to undermine White's strong pawn center. Players like Wesley So and Levon Aronian are playing this variation with White still. }
9. Nc3
{ Almost all legal moves have been tried here for White. I cannot go into all of them - you should just review the top games with a computer engine. Strategically, the position is fairly simple, as Black just wants to finish development and then @@StartBracket@@at the right moment@@EndBracket@@ attack the center with ...f6. White, in turn, wants to make it difficult for Black to execute this plan by putting pressure on the e4-knight and d5-pawn. }
9... O-O 10. Be3
{ The most common move. Now  10...f6  does not work because of  11.Qb3  and Black's d5 and Ne4 are difficult to protect. }
10... Bg4
{ The most common reply. In this position, White has tried almost every legal move. The most popular is  11.h3  , as after most other moves it seems that Black can get in ...f6. For example  11.O-O  f6  when White will probably have to capture on f6 and then return the bishop to e2 at some point, in order to protect the knight on f3. }
11. Qc2
{ This should be compared with the mainline  11.h3  Bh5  12.Qc2  - see the variation. }
11... Bf5
{ The difference is that with the bishop on f5 instead of g6, there are some tactics that work in Black's favor if White now continues 12. Qb3. }
12. Qb3 Na5 { Practically forcing White to grab the d5-pawn. } 13. Qxd5 Qe7
{ Threatening ...c6. White cannot grab the knight on e4. } 14. Nxe4 Be6
{ The queen is trapped. Note that  15.Bg5  can be answered by  15...Qb4+  16.Bd2  Qxb2  and Black wins. }
*

