{ Since we've seen that  11...Bxf3  is not that good,  11...Bh5  is the main move instead. I've played this myself more than once. Now again, White has tried almost every legal move in the position after  11...Bh5  . Even a move like  12.Rc1  has been played, even though I can't understand what it's trying to achieve - but apparently the computer likes it. }
12. O-O { This is an important move to know. } 12... Nxd4
{ The second point is that this move actually leads to a forced draw - a very important resource for Black. }
13. Bxd4 Bxf3 14. gxf3
{ 14.Qxf3  Bxd4  just leads to mass exchanges and a draw:  15.Nxe4  dxe4  16.Qxe4  Bxb2  17.Rab1  Bd4  followed by ...c5, and so on. }
14... Qg5+ 15. Kh1 Qf5
{ Here White has to allow a draw by perpetual check. For instance  16.fxe4  Qxh3+  17.Kg1  Bxd4  and here it's probably best for White to retake  18.Qxd4  when  18...Qg4+  19.Kh1  Qh3+  etc. is a draw; or @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/ppp2ppp/1b6/1B1pPq2/3Bn3/2N2P1P/PP3P2/R2Q1R1K w - - 3 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Bxb6  Qxh3+  17.Kg1  Ng3  when White has to take the knight, again resulting in a perpetual. }
