1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ In this position Black can either play  3...Bc5  or  3...Nf6  . Both are perfectly fine, though  3...Bc5  is more popular. The choice between  3...Nf6  and  3...Bc5  boils down to which variations you want to allow White to play. In case of  3...Nf6  4.d3  it doesn't really matter, as Black can continue  4...Bc5  and the position will be the same as after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  4.d3  Nf6  .   However, after  3...Nf6  White has the additional options of playing  4.Ng5  and  4.d4  , whereas after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  White can play lines with  4.c3  and 5. d4. I think Black is fine in all of these variations, but as Black you'll need to pick either 3... Bc5 or 3... Nf6 and study the theory of the associated sidelines. }
3... Bc5
{ As mentioned,  3...Bc5  is more popular than  3...Nf6  . This is because the sidelines after  3...Nf6  are considered to be more dangerous than the sidelines that White can play after  3...Bc5  . However, this is not a settled debate, and in any case I think both moves are perfectly playable for Black. }
4. c3 { The mainline of the Italian. } 4... Nf6 5. d4
{ 5.d3  is what we will consider in the next lesson, but  5.d4  is also a serious move. For many years it was considered to be harmless, but it is actually experiencing a new wave of popularity based on the variation  5...exd4  6.e5  . }
5... exd4 6. e5
{ This is a tricky move and quite popular on a high level at the moment. } 6...
d5
{ A very typical response to the e4-e5 advance in the Italian. Now  7.exf6  dxc4  8.fxg7  Rg8  is not good for White - Black is actually better. }
7. Bb5 { The most principled move. } 7... Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6
{ This position was for a long time considered to be perfectly good for Black, as he's very active with his knight on e4 and pressure against the d4-pawn @@StartBracket@@also the bishop is coming to g4 next, etc.@@EndBracket@@.However, things are not so easy for Black. Objectively Black is fine, but Black needs to know a lot of theory, as it's not that easy to undermine White's strong pawn center. Players like Wesley So and Levon Aronian are playing this variation with White still. }
9. Nc3
{ Almost all legal moves have been tried here for White. I cannot go into all of them - you should just review the top games with a computer engine. Strategically, the position is fairly simple, as Black just wants to finish development and then @@StartBracket@@at the right moment@@EndBracket@@ attack the center with ...f6. White, in turn, wants to make it difficult for Black to execute this plan by putting pressure on the e4-knight and d5-pawn. }
9... O-O 10. Be3
{ The most common move. Now  10...f6  does not work because of  11.Qb3  and Black's d5 and Ne4 are difficult to protect. }
10... Bg4
{ The most common reply. In this position, White has tried almost every legal move. The most popular is  11.h3  , as after most other moves it seems that Black can get in ...f6. For example  11.O-O  f6  when White will probably have to capture on f6 and then return the bishop to e2 at some point, in order to protect the knight on f3. }
11. h3 Bh5
{ Since we've seen that  11...Bxf3  is not that good,  11...Bh5  is the main move instead. I've played this myself more than once. Now again, White has tried almost every legal move in the position after  11...Bh5  . Even a move like  12.Rc1  has been played, even though I can't understand what it's trying to achieve - but apparently the computer likes it. }
12. Qc2
{ The latest fashion and the main move, simply attacking the knight on e4 and trying to force a concession from Black. I think Black has more than one way to be okay here, but the position is tricky. }
12... Bg6 13. Qb3
{ This is one of the ideas behind 12. Qc2. White has forced Black to put the bishop on g6, so that he no longer has the piece sacrifice idea with ...Bxf3 and ...Nxf2, and compared to 11. Qc2 after  13...Na5  now White can just grab the d5-pawn as Black no longer has the ...Be6 resource.   That being said, I think that after  13...Ne7  Black's position is fine, though of course it's complicated and playable for White. I played a game in this line against Naiditsch, a complicated game with ups and downs, eventually ending in a draw. }
