{ To summarize, after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  the move  4.d4  exd4  5.e5  is a half-forgotten line which shouldn't cause Black any problems. My advice is not to play  5...d5  , even though Black is probably okay there too, but instead to look into  5...Ne4  and  5...Ng4  . After either of those moves it seems easier for Black to equalize than after  5...d5  .   After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  Black also needs to be ready to face  4.Ng5  . The positions that arise from this variation are very complicated and unbalanced. For both White and Black this is a risky way of playing, and it's a matter of taste.   If as Black you prefer safer, more positional variations, you should try @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  instead. Against the Evans Gambit  4.b4  Bxb4  5.c3  , the line  5...Ba5  is doing very well according to theory.Meanwhile, after  4.c3  Nf6  5.d4  exd4  , the only line which poses Black some problems is  6.e5  d5  7.Bb5  Ne4  .  I'm sure that Black is doing fine here, but the arising positions are not as simple as they was thought to be some 20 years ago. It's not a bad idea as White to have this line in this repertoire, because if Black misplays it you can easily get a better position.Playing this line as Black, you need to carefully study the lines with a strong engine and check the games of top players. If you do your homework I'm sure you won't encounter any real problems here.Now in the next lesson we will consider the slow Italian with c3 and d3. It may be a bit difficult to follow, as there are a lot of important move order nuances in this line, but it's also really important to understand as this variation is extremely popular nowadays. If you play 1. e4 e5 as Black, it will probably quite often appear in your games. }
