1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Let's start with the 3...Nf6 system. } 3... Nf6 4.
d3 { Let's start with Be7. } 4... Be7 5. O-O O-O
{ Here Black in general would like to play d5, if possible, because what if Black puts the pawn on d6? Of course the bishop on e7 is more solid. In Italian, you will see that very often - the Bishop on the g1-a7 diagonal is much more active. Although, Black has to secure the c5-bishop by playing a6 or a5, and possibly Ba7 losing some tempi.Be7 is more solid if you want a more simple system. But, in general, I wouldn't say it doesn't fully equalize, but as a person who played a lot of Italian with White in the last recent years, I was quite happy when my opponents played Be7. Even though again, I want to repeat that it's a perfectly playable system for Black. }
6. c3
{ The idea is that if White plays normally here, then Black can play d5 and is perfectly fine. }
6... d5 { This seems to be enough to equalize. } 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Re1 Bg4
{ An important move, otherwise it is not easy to adequately protect the e5-pawn. }
9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Rxe5
{ It's very dangerous for White to take this pawn. } 12... c6
{ Followed by Bd6 and f5, and the position is probably already in Black's favor. So, I think that @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppppbppp/2n2n2/4p3/2B1P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c3  is not the most accurate move-order. }
