[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 16: Italian with c3 and d3"]
[Black "Italian 3... Nf6 4. d3 Be7 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Let's start with the 3...Nf6 system. } 3... Nf6 4.
d3 { Let's start with Be7. } 4... Be7 5. O-O O-O
{ Here Black in general would like to play d5, if possible, because what if Black puts the pawn on d6? Of course the bishop on e7 is more solid. In Italian, you will see that very often - the Bishop on the g1-a7 diagonal is much more active. Although, Black has to secure the c5-bishop by playing a6 or a5, and possibly Ba7 losing some tempi.Be7 is more solid if you want a more simple system. But, in general, I wouldn't say it doesn't fully equalize, but as a person who played a lot of Italian with White in the last recent years, I was quite happy when my opponents played Be7. Even though again, I want to repeat that it's a perfectly playable system for Black. }
6. Bb3
{ I played this myself as White a couple of times in the mid-90s in rapid chess against Garry Kasparov. If  6...d6  then White wants to play  7.c3  . }
6... d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Re1
{ The most principled move. I played  8.h3  against Kasparov but didn't really achieve much. }
8... Bg4 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nd4
{ Is a way to have both knights in a very comfortable position. } 11. Qxd5
{ The principled move. Otherwise, if the queen retreats then Black can just take on b3, play f6, and probably equalize quite easily. }
11... Qxd5 12. Bxd5 Nxc2 { The main line goes as follows: } 13. Bd2 Nxa1 14.
Rc1 c6 15. Bf3
{ Now, if Black goes for  15...Rfd8  to take on d3, White will play  16.Nc3  and recapture the knight on a1. This position is probably close to equal, but maybe still a little bit more comfortable for White, who is playing for a win even though I am not sure if he can really achieve much. }
