[Black "Italian 3... Nf6 4.d3 Be7 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Let's start with the 3...Nf6 system. } 3... Nf6 4.
d3 { Let's start with Be7. } 4... Be7 5. O-O O-O
{ Here Black in general would like to play d5, if possible, because what if Black puts the pawn on d6? Of course the bishop on e7 is more solid. In Italian, you will see that very often - the Bishop on the g1-a7 diagonal is much more active. Although, Black has to secure the c5-bishop by playing a6 or a5, and possibly Ba7 losing some tempi.Be7 is more solid if you want a more simple system. But, in general, I wouldn't say it doesn't fully equalize, but as a person who played a lot of Italian with White in the last recent years, I was quite happy when my opponents played Be7. Even though again, I want to repeat that it's a perfectly playable system for Black. }
6. Re1
{ After the 90's, White came up with this totally different concept, which is still considered to be the best. And I myself, was planning to play like this when my opponents would play Be7 variations. The idea is that Black has to play d6. He cannot play d5 as the e5-pawn will be hanging. }
6... d6 7. a4
{ Sometimes  7.a3  is more useful than a4, but most of the time it's better to gain more space by playing  7.a4  . Now Black has a few different plans.   7.c3  Na5  8.Bb5  a6  9.Ba4  b5  10.Bc2  c5  11.Nbd2  Nc6  The same story that we have already seen. }
7... Kh8
{ This is one of the plans, followed by Ng8 and f5 which can work sometimes, but might be a bit artificial. }
8. a5
{ A typical move because White very often wants to play a6. So, usually Black sooner or later has to play a6 himself. }
8... a6 9. h3 Ng8
{ The big difference is that, compared to the positions when White already has a pawn on c3, here White has Nc3 and the knight gets to d5. }
10. Nc3 f5 11. Nd5
{ And there are some games here. For example, there is a Caruana - Grischuk rapid game here. Black doesn't have enough play for equality because a5 is strong and White is sometimes playing b4-Bb2 here, followed by breaking in the center with d4. I think this position is in White's favor. }
