1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Let's start with the 3...Nf6 system. } 3... Nf6 4.
d3
{ White has some active options like  4.d4  and  4.Ng5  , so if you're playing 3...Nf6 with Black, you must be ready for those aggressive moves. But very often White is just playing d3. Most often, Black players start with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  , instead of  3...Nf6  , to avoid  Ng5  .  So, let's consider the other options.For Black, 3...Bc5 has been the most common move for a very long time and was almost the only system that Black played. If he doesn't want to put the bishop on c5, then Be7 and h6 are also possible moves. Trying to develop the bishop to g7 is also becoming quite popular. }
4... h6
{ This started to be popular with the idea that after White plays  5.O-O  , Black has to play 5...d6 first because  5...g5  is too aggressive here and leads to a worse position after  6.d4  . }
5. O-O d6 { After d6, White is usually playing c3. } 6. c3 g5
{ This is a very interesting system, which I can recommend if you're ready to play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  instead of  3...Bc5  with Black against 3.Bc4 @@StartBracket@@which might be the most interesting system to study@@EndBracket@@.   The idea is not that Black wants to play g4-h5 to mate, but rather it's like a prolonged fianchetto with the potential of g4. It's a bit more difficult for White to develop here as g4 is always on the agenda, especially when the d2- and e1-squares are occupied, like when White plays Nbd2 and Re1. After g4 in such a position, he has problems with the knight. }
7. Bb3
{ Is usually played. As we will see in the Italian defense, it's always an option to play a4. But, when studying the system, I thought Bb3, in this particular case, might be a bit more accurate because White very often uses the c4-square for the knight and plays, Nd2-Nc4. }
7... Bg7
{ Well, the downside of g5 compare to g6, is the potential of the f5-square for White's knight. This will be very painful, but it's still far from being realized. Nevertheless, that makes this variation not bulletproof. It's perfectly playable as it's not easy for White to get an advantage, but, there is a strategic danger with this f5-square. }
8. Nbd2 g4
{ As mentioned, Black's idea is not to try to mate or anything here, so this is not really leading anywhere. }
9. Ne1
{ Now sometimes White has the resource f4 or f3, opening up the f-file for the attack. }
