1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This lesson is going to be about all the Italian lines with White playing d3. Most of the time c3 is also included, but not always, where White tries to play a slow positional game. This is a very popular set-up nowadays, and a very popular concept. }
3... Bc5
{ Now let's move to Bc5. There is much, much more theory here, which is developing rapidly. In the last year, at least all the best players have played this position with both colors. It will be quite a journey, so fasten your seatbelts as I will try to explain all the move orders and positional nuances of this very fashionable system. }
4. O-O Nf6 5. d3
{ And now in case of  5...d6  , White just plays  6.c3  and transposes to other lines with d6. In the case of 5...O-O here, White has a number of options without c3 just to avoid d5 systems. There are so many options that sometimes I also played d5 from time to time as Black, but I was really getting a bit confused with all the possible move orders. }
5... O-O 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 Be7
{ Trying to get Nh5. A very typical idea in these variations for instance, if  8.c3  then Black can usually play  8...Nh5  immediately.   If  7...d6  then  8.c3  once again. }
8. Bg3
{ This is an option that I don't really think is too dangerous for Black, but it's playable. }
8... d6 9. h3 { Just trying to stop Nh5. } 9... Na5
{ Maybe @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1bpp1/2np1n1p/4p3/2B1P3/3P1NB1/PPP2PPP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.c3  would work as after  9...Nh5  , White might have  10.Nxe5  . }
