3... Bc5
{ Now let's move to Bc5. There is much, much more theory here, which is developing rapidly. In the last year, at least all the best players have played this position with both colors. It will be quite a journey, so fasten your seatbelts as I will try to explain all the move orders and positional nuances of this very fashionable system. }
4. c3 { Let's investigate the direct play with c3. } 4... Nf6 5. d3
{ Let's now move to the more quiet kind of classical systems. I don't think it gives White a real advantage, but it is comfortable and safe, you can always keep the pressure. From the Black point of view, I think it's comfortable and very solid, you can't go wrong. }
5... O-O 6. O-O d5
{ This is actually very straightforward and direct. Quite interesting for Black - in general the only minus is that White has quite a number of options. }
7. exd5 Nxd5
{ Of course this is very healthy. In general, very often in these structures and in the Ruy Lopez, playing d5 is Black's main idea. If Black gets d5 with good development, you will more likely be more than fine. However, there are a lot of tactical ideas for White, especially with trying to attack this e5-pawn. So, if you want to play this system with Black, you really need to study it move by move, as there is quite a lot of theory.I think that in general, Black is doing fine here and I don't think there is any way for White to get an advantage, but there are many tries. The precision and the knowledge of theory here is much more important compared to the d6 lines, where after d6 most of the time Black can play slowly and get a good position. On the other hand, d5 is much more direct. }
8. a4
{ This was the main move and it's still a serious attempt. White is preparing a5-b4 with a pawn march on the queenside. Black has many moves here. a5 was considered to be the main line for a long time, but maybe Nb6 is interesting. }
8... Nb6
{ This might actually equalize, but that is really trying just to force a draw in a slightly worse position. }
9. Bg5 Qd6
{ Very direct play, so it is important that you know it move per move here. Especially as it looks like Black just blundered a piece! }
10. b4 Nxc4 11. bxc5 Qg6 12. dxc4 e4
{ This works perfectly well, and I think it's basically a draw here. } *

