12... Nxg3 13. Nxc6 { 13.Bxf7+  Kd8  . } 13... Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 Nxh1+ 15. Qxh1
bxc6 { Black is just winning here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 16: Italian with c3 and d3"]
[Black "Italian 5. d3 d6 6. Bg5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This lesson is going to be about all the Italian lines with White playing d3. Most of the time c3 is also included, but not always, where White tries to play a slow positional game. This is a very popular set-up nowadays, and a very popular concept. }
3... Bc5
{ Now let's move to Bc5. There is much, much more theory here, which is developing rapidly. In the last year, at least all the best players have played this position with both colors. It will be quite a journey, so fasten your seatbelts as I will try to explain all the move orders and positional nuances of this very fashionable system. }
4. c3 { Let's investigate the direct play with c3. } 4... Nf6 5. d3
{ Let's now move to the more quiet kind of classical systems. I don't think it gives White a real advantage, but it is comfortable and safe, you can always keep the pressure. From the Black point of view, I think it's comfortable and very solid, you can't go wrong. }
5... d6 { Now let's consider all the possible move orders. } 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4
{ I don't think there is a big reason to be afraid of Bg5, because it also gives Black chances to play for a win here. In general, I believe that this Bg5-Bh4 system is interesting and playable for White, but I was always happy to play it with Black because Black can potentially get even better out of the opening. }
7... a6
{ This is always very useful in this position especially after Bg5-Bh4 and then g5-Bg3 White is very often threatening d4.  White needs to do something with their c4-bishop because often Na5 is becoming a threat trying to take it.   Recently I saw Giri playing  7...a5  and then trying the plan with Bd7-Qe7 and even sometimes O-O followed by g5. A very complicated position which I think is risky for White but, again, White can get better if his preparation is superior to his opponent's. }
8. a4 Ba7 9. Nbd2
{ The main idea is that if Black manages just to play g5-Nh5 then he will be at least equal but it just doesn't work tactically. }
9... Qe7 10. O-O
{ White's best try is to castle, but that is really dangerous, and there is a lot of theory here. Before the computer era, I think nobody in their right mind would actually go for these positions because it looks awfully dangerous for White. But, somehow, the computer is showing that it's not so clear, but again if you're Black, you have to be very well-prepared against this line. }
10... g5 11. Bg3
{ Black can always play  11...Bg4  in these positions and it's perfectly playable, but the main line for Black is a strange move -  11...Nd7  or  11...Nh7  because it follows with Nf8. I think Nd7 is a bit more accurate.   11...h5  is straightforward and looks very good but after  12.h4  the computer is happy with White.   11...O-O  is not such a good version because Black has played Qe7 which is absolutely not necessary anymore. White probably has decent chances to get an advantage here for instance  12.b4  a very typical idea followed by b5. }
11... Nd7
{ The game is completely crazy and you just need to analyze it with the engine and check games. I think it's unclear, probably objectively equal. }
12. b4 Nf8 { Preparing Ng6 with h5-h4-g4. } 13. b5 Nd8
{ 13...Na5  is also possible. } 14. d4 Ng6 15. h3 h5 16. Bd5
{ And finally, Dominguez managed to win this game. But all in all, a very sharp and complicated line. }
*

