1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This lesson is going to be about all the Italian lines with White playing d3. Most of the time c3 is also included, but not always, where White tries to play a slow positional game. This is a very popular set-up nowadays, and a very popular concept. }
3... Bc5
{ Now let's move to Bc5. There is much, much more theory here, which is developing rapidly. In the last year, at least all the best players have played this position with both colors. It will be quite a journey, so fasten your seatbelts as I will try to explain all the move orders and positional nuances of this very fashionable system. }
4. c3 { Let's investigate the direct play with c3. } 4... Nf6 5. d3
{ Let's now move to the more quiet kind of classical systems. I don't think it gives White a real advantage, but it is comfortable and safe, you can always keep the pressure. From the Black point of view, I think it's comfortable and very solid, you can't go wrong. }
5... d6 { Now let's consider all the possible move orders. } 6. O-O
{ This is White's most popular choice. There will be a lot of different move orders and the system is very fashionable nowadays, so there are many games by top players here - and the theory has grown enormously in the last 10 years. But there are still some things to discover and so new games are coming out all the time with some new adjustments and ideas. One thing is clear, though - White doesn't have much if Black knows what he's doing, analyzes it well, and is very well prepared, as then he should be able to equalize. But, even if Black equalizes, the positions can still be rich and filled with ideas where White can still play for the win.  For the Black player, if you decide to play with d6 I would advise you to choose the system you want to play, as there are different systems - sometimes you can put a pawn on a5 or a6 and so on. It might be best to choose two systems and then to get some practice with games to get the feeling for those middle games positions which arise in these variations. }
6... a6 { This line is actually not bad, and makes sense. } 7. Re1 Ba7 8. a4 h6
{ Black is trying to play g5 without castling. } 9. b4 O-O
{ Now  9...g5  should not be working anymore because White has  10.Be3  followed by Nbd2 at some point.  This line should be further investigated, especially if you want to avoid the main line. Objectively this h6-g5 plan is dubious, but it is still something you can have in your repertoire as Black. }
