{ This is actually is a very serious move. I think Grischuk likes to play like this. It's not easy for White to get anything. The idea is that in case of  8.h3  Black is playing  8...Ne7  with the idea of Ng6-Bc7.   If  8.Nbd2  , nothing has really changed and Black has the same idea with  8...Ng4  9.Re2  Kh8  10.h3  f5  which is working well for Black. }
8. a4 { A useful move that stops Ne7 because of a5. } 8... a5 9. h3
{ Most of the time this particular variation with a4 and a5 is slightly in White's favor. }
9... Ne7 10. d4 Ng6 11. Bd3 Re8 12. Nbd2 c6
{ A very typical position. There are so many transpositions from different move-orders to more or less this same position. You would be surprised but this exact position can also arise from Berlin with d3. }
13. Nf1 d5 14. Bg5
{ A very tactical position were probably Black equalizes if he is very precise but White has some chances for an opening advantage. }
*

