{ If you want to play for an opening advantage as White, you're almost forced to start with h3. Usually Black has different options, but most of the time I mean the most logical is to play h6 Nbd2 and Re8. }
9... h6 10. Nbd2 Nh5 11. Nf1 Qf6 12. Ne3
{ 12.Be3  is also quite serious, but this  12.Ne3  setup is quite interesting for White. }
12... Nf4 13. Ng4 Qg6 14. Bxf4 { A pawn sacrfice which is best for White. }
14... exf4 15. d4 Bxg4 16. hxg4 Qxg4 17. Qd3
{ And there is at least enough compensation if not more for White because the a7-bishop is actually quite a bad piece even though probably with very precise play Black can equalize. But again all in all, @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/bpp2pp1/p1np1n1p/4p3/4P3/1BPP1N1P/PP1N1PP1/R1BQR1K1 b - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nh5  is a bit dubious. }
