[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 16: Italian with c3 and d3"]
[Black "Italian 7. Re1 a6 8. Bb3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This lesson is going to be about all the Italian lines with White playing d3. Most of the time c3 is also included, but not always, where White tries to play a slow positional game. This is a very popular set-up nowadays, and a very popular concept. }
3... Bc5
{ Now let's move to Bc5. There is much, much more theory here, which is developing rapidly. In the last year, at least all the best players have played this position with both colors. It will be quite a journey, so fasten your seatbelts as I will try to explain all the move orders and positional nuances of this very fashionable system. }
4. c3 { Let's investigate the direct play with c3. } 4... Nf6 5. d3
{ Let's now move to the more quiet kind of classical systems. I don't think it gives White a real advantage, but it is comfortable and safe, you can always keep the pressure. From the Black point of view, I think it's comfortable and very solid, you can't go wrong. }
5... d6 { Now let's consider all the possible move orders. } 6. O-O
{ This is White's most popular choice. There will be a lot of different move orders and the system is very fashionable nowadays, so there are many games by top players here - and the theory has grown enormously in the last 10 years. But there are still some things to discover and so new games are coming out all the time with some new adjustments and ideas. One thing is clear, though - White doesn't have much if Black knows what he's doing, analyzes it well, and is very well prepared, as then he should be able to equalize. But, even if Black equalizes, the positions can still be rich and filled with ideas where White can still play for the win.  For the Black player, if you decide to play with d6 I would advise you to choose the system you want to play, as there are different systems - sometimes you can put a pawn on a5 or a6 and so on. It might be best to choose two systems and then to get some practice with games to get the feeling for those middle games positions which arise in these variations. }
6... O-O
{ White has two main setups:   • One is the old setup where White plays Bb3 at some point, for instance against a6.  • The new way of playing is to play a4 with the same idea to secure the bishop because sooner or later Black wants to play Na5, especially when the c5-bishop will retreat to b6 or a7. }
7. Re1
{ White doesn't need to hurry with Bb3. So now of course Ng4 is not working so well yet so Black has to secure his bishop. And well,  most of the time in the past Black would play a6-Ba7 because you actually need to solve this problem with the bishop.   7.h3  This is possible. Also, if Black castles before playing d6, then @@StartBracket@@in order to avoid c3-d5@@EndBracket@@ White can start with h3-d6-c3 which would lead to this same position after a few moves. However, I think Re1 leaves White with more options. }
7... a6 { The old fashioned way. } 8. Bb3
{ Black has some options like  8...Re8  or  8...h6  , but then you can already play  9.Nbd2  . }
8... Ba7 { Now the move order is very important to remember. } 9. h3
{ If you want to play for an opening advantage as White, you're almost forced to start with h3. Usually Black has different options, but most of the time I mean the most logical is to play h6 Nbd2 and Re8. }
9... h6 10. Nbd2 Re8
{ Is usually played here and you will see the differences - we could have the same position with a pawn on a4 and bishop on c4 which is also one of the main systems for Black. But then White starts to push b4 and he's getting some play on the queenside. Here, White doesn't have this option. }
11. Nf1 Be6 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Nxe3 Qd7 14. Bxe6 Rxe6
{ This position is very close to equal. Of course, there is very little for White, but still he has a little bit more of a flexible structure. It's possible to play this with White. If you're Black, don't think that the old dangers are gone and that the position is totally equal. No, you still have to be a bit accurate here, but in general Black will be able to equalize normally. }
*

