[White "Lesson 16: Italian with c3 and d3"]
[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this lesson I’ve tried to explain the general state of theory of the Italian with d3 and c3. As I’ve made clear, there is a choice of various setups for both colors, especially for Black. If you play against the Italian as Black, you need to choose a system to your liking, while as White you have to be ready for all of Black’s different systems.For White, the good thing about the Italian with d3/c3 is that if you play in a positional way with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/2b1p3/2B1P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.O-O  ,  even if you don’t know the theory very well, there is very little risk of getting a worse position. But if you still want to pose some problems for the Black player, then you’ll need to spend some time preparing and understanding the nuances of different move orders.Objectively speaking, the Italian with d3/c3 doesn’t give White any advantage, but it’s a comfortable and safe way of playing, and White always keeps a bit of pressure and can ask Black some practical questions. I’ve won many games in this opening against strong opponents, even though I didn’t get any real advantage out of the opening – for instance against Michael Adams in Shamkir 2017. As Black I’ve also felt comfortable playing these positions, as Black’s position in general is sound and very solid.For the club/amateur level, the information provided in this lesson should be enough to get you playing this opening. Of course, on the professional level you would have to go a bit deeper still. As I’ve mentioned repeatedly, the main thing is to understand all the subtle move orders in this variation.   Next we will move on to the Ruy Lopez, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  , which comprises the bulk of this course. The Spanish has traditionally been White’s main try against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  . I will try to cover each system, starting with Black’s alternatives to  3.Bb5  a6  , then White’s early alternatives, slowly moving on to the traditional main line of  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.O-O  Be7  . }
1. -- *

