1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ So let's finally investigate the Bb5 Ruy Lopez, the most popular move with the biggest amount of theory. White's problem is that with time and with the development of engines, Black is discovering more and more resources to equalize in various lines. So I would say that there are a few major systems against Bb5 which are very difficult for White to deal with, in the sense of getting a real advantage.  First of all, there is the Berlin with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  which is covered in chapters18 and19. Then after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.O-O  , there are lines with  5...Bc5  , or the immediate @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  ,  followed by b5. And of course, there is Nxe4 Open Spanish.   Then there is also @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b - - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7  , followed by Marshall.  So quite a number of serious lines. But still, I wouldn't say that there is clear-cut equality in each of these lines. Nevertheless, we know that Bb5 has been considered by far to be the main move in the position @@StartBracket@@along with Bc4@@EndBracket@@ and most of our theoretical discussions will go in there. So with Bb5, there is a lot of theory, and each of the major systems will be a subject of separate chapters. In this chapter, I want to show you the major sidelines. }
3... d6 4. d4 Bd7 5. Nc3 exd4 6. Nxd4
{ White is at least slightly better here without even being forced to fight for an advantage as Black gave White this space advantage. It's not very bad for Black, but it makes little sense to play like this. }
