1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ So let's finally investigate the Bb5 Ruy Lopez, the most popular move with the biggest amount of theory. White's problem is that with time and with the development of engines, Black is discovering more and more resources to equalize in various lines. So I would say that there are a few major systems against Bb5 which are very difficult for White to deal with, in the sense of getting a real advantage.  First of all, there is the Berlin with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  which is covered in chapters18 and19. Then after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.O-O  , there are lines with  5...Bc5  , or the immediate @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  ,  followed by b5. And of course, there is Nxe4 Open Spanish.   Then there is also @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b - - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7  , followed by Marshall.  So quite a number of serious lines. But still, I wouldn't say that there is clear-cut equality in each of these lines. Nevertheless, we know that Bb5 has been considered by far to be the main move in the position @@StartBracket@@along with Bc4@@EndBracket@@ and most of our theoretical discussions will go in there. So with Bb5, there is a lot of theory, and each of the major systems will be a subject of separate chapters. In this chapter, I want to show you the major sidelines. }
3... Bc5
{ This move is not too bad for Black. Of course, the test is  4.c3  because now White wants to play d4 but it seems that after  4...f5  it is not so clear. It's not so simple in my opinion, so maybe Black is okay objectively even if it is hard to believe as I may be skeptical about Black playing f5 at such an early stage of the game. But at least with the help of computers, so far no clear advantage has been found for White. }
4. O-O
{ Of course, Black can play  4...Nf6  and transfer to the system that we are going to investigate later, but I think that this system is not entirely correct. After  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.d4  which we will see later.   Then of course  4...d6  is probably not great because White has  5.c3  with d4 next and White enjoys a nice plus here. Therefore, the text move  4...Nd4  is not too bad where the Nd4 system is quite playable for Black. I advise you to have a look at it as a surprise weapon as I don't believe that you can play this system all the time with Black, at least in classical chess. Objectively it is not good, but it's not too bad and I think that it's a pretty rare line which not many White players would know well. }
4... Nd4 5. Nxd4
{ If you want to be slightly better with White, then this is good enough. }
5... Bxd4 6. c3 Bb6 7. d4 c6 { This is very important, followed by d6. } 8. Bd3
{ I think that the automatic move that White usually plays is  8.Ba4  , but after  8...d6  Black follows with Nf6 and this is perfectly playable for Black. So instead I recommend the text move, 8.Bd3. }
8... d6 { This seems safer for Black. } 9. Be3 Nf6 10. h3 { Stopping Ng4. }
10... O-O 11. Nd2 Re8 12. Re1
{ Generally in these positions, if White manages to keep his center then he will be a bit better. }
12... d5 { This does not equalize here. } 13. dxe5
{ Black is not in time to equalize, and White should be slightly better. So all in all, I think that 3...Bc5 is better than its reputation, but not enough to equalize. }
*

