{ White has several options here, such as starting with Nc3, but I will show you the simplest. }
4. O-O { The simplest. } 4... g6 5. c3 a6
{ If you're playing Black you have to find the correct moment for when to play a6 because here again, it gives White the option of playing  6.Bc4  trying to get Ng5, even though I'm not sure if it's so dangerous here:  6...Bg7  . }
6. Ba4 Bg7 7. d4 exd4 8. cxd4 O-O 9. h3
{ I believe that White can just play this to stop Bg4. } 9... d5 10. e5
{ White gets the center and wants to develop. Black will probably try to get f6 at some point but this position should still at least be slightly better for White, therefore making it another good option. }
