1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Now we will investigate the Berlin defense with Bb5 Nf6. Of course, it is practically maybe the most popular opening nowadays in top-level chess and there is a lot of theory on it @@StartBracket@@much more than when I started to play it in 2000 in my match against Garry Kasparov@@EndBracket@@. Back then, I was already a bit worried about d3, as I understood that this move is much more dangerous than it looks. }
4. Qe2
{ Of course this is definitely a playable move, but I don't think it really gives White any chance for an opening advantage, but rather for a complicated game where Black will be less prepared. All in all, though, I wouldn't recommend this for White. }
4... Bc5 5. c3
{ So c3 is a better choice. And now Black has different ways of playing. } 5...
O-O { Logical. } 6. d3 h6
{ This is perfectly playable, but it's a bit risky as White can get some g4 ideas. Let's say White tries to organize an attack like this with  7.h3  d6  8.g4  now Black can always go  8...Nh7  followed by Ne7-Ng6 with a very double-edged position. }
7. O-O d6
{ Black has a perfect, excellent version of this typical structure because the queen on e2 is misplaced in my opinion. So White has nothing here. }
