1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Now we will investigate the Berlin defense with Bb5 Nf6. Of course, it is practically maybe the most popular opening nowadays in top-level chess and there is a lot of theory on it @@StartBracket@@much more than when I started to play it in 2000 in my match against Garry Kasparov@@EndBracket@@. Back then, I was already a bit worried about d3, as I understood that this move is much more dangerous than it looks. }
4. d4
{ This is of course a very direct and important move to know. But after exd4 White has nothing really here and the lines are quite simple. }
4... exd4 5. O-O
{ If White castles then Black has a6 which is important to know, even though it is not the only move, it is the most accurate one. Because if White is playing Ba4, and seemingly he doesn't have anything better than that, then simply Be7 and this will transpose to the variation after a6-Ba4-Nf6-d4 which I am going to present a little bit later in this course. }
5... a6 6. Ba4 Be7 7. Re1 b5 8. e5 { 8.Bb3  d6  9.Bd5  Nxd5  10.exd5  Ne5  . }
8... Nxe5 { Black is fine. } *

