[Black "Spanish Berlin 4. d3 d6 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Now we will investigate the Berlin defense with Bb5 Nf6. Of course, it is practically maybe the most popular opening nowadays in top-level chess and there is a lot of theory on it @@StartBracket@@much more than when I started to play it in 2000 in my match against Garry Kasparov@@EndBracket@@. Back then, I was already a bit worried about d3, as I understood that this move is much more dangerous than it looks. }
4. d3
{ The serious move. When I prepared Berlin against Garry Kasparov for our match, I was pretty sure that he was not going to play d3 because it's not in the concept of his play. He always tried to play the main line to fight for an opening advantage to play in a very principled way with White. Playing d3 gives Black lots of different choices, he can play d6-Bc5 and there is no way White can be much better here.  But I realized that things are not so easy here and I spent quite some time actually trying to find the best weapon against d3. So it is a serious move. Black's two main options are  4...Bc5  or  4...d6  , where Bc5 is more principled and more popular among top players nowadays. }
4... d6
{ This is very playable for Black and you need to know much less theory compared to Bc5. But of course, after d6 White also has a kind of normal Ruy Lopez with certain chances for an opening advantage or complicated games. So d6 is not a refutation of d3.   If you want really to play in a very principled way, probably you should rather play the  4...Bc5  variation but from time to time, especially in rapid time control, I played d6 and I can say that it's perfectly playable.So now White has a choice and it is quite important here to understand the move order. }
5. O-O
{ Most top-level players start with this because now, in the case of g6, d4 is already practically a tempo up for White. }
5... Be7
{ It does not matter if White starts with c3 or with O-O as it reaches the same position. }
6. c3 O-O 7. Re1 a6 { The more principled move. } 8. Ba4
{ Then you get this typical Ruy Lopez. I would prefer to have Bg7 with Black as I think then Black has more chances to equalize, but even here it is playable. Black has different ways of proceeding. }
8... b5 9. Bc2
{ It is very important that the bishop gets to c2, not on b3.  9.Bb3  would directly transpose into the closed Ruy Lopez variation  9...Na5  10.Bc2  c5  . }
9... d5
{ This is a big theoretical position. It's not bad for Black but all in all, I think that White has some pressure. First of all, there is an interesting move  10.d4  which is quite dangerous and Black really has to know how to deal with it. }
10. Nbd2 dxe4 { 10...d4  is also quite interesting. } 11. dxe4 Be6 12. Qe2
{ Trying to play a4 to attack the b5-pawn. This was very popular at some point and there are many games between strong players here.I would say the verdict is that Black has chances to equalize but it's not so easy as White also has chances to get some opening advantage. }
*

