[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Now we will investigate the Berlin defense with Bb5 Nf6. Of course, it is practically maybe the most popular opening nowadays in top-level chess and there is a lot of theory on it @@StartBracket@@much more than when I started to play it in 2000 in my match against Garry Kasparov@@EndBracket@@. Back then, I was already a bit worried about d3, as I understood that this move is much more dangerous than it looks. }
4. d3
{ The serious move. When I prepared Berlin against Garry Kasparov for our match, I was pretty sure that he was not going to play d3 because it's not in the concept of his play. He always tried to play the main line to fight for an opening advantage to play in a very principled way with White. Playing d3 gives Black lots of different choices, he can play d6-Bc5 and there is no way White can be much better here.  But I realized that things are not so easy here and I spent quite some time actually trying to find the best weapon against d3. So it is a serious move. Black's two main options are  4...Bc5  or  4...d6  , where Bc5 is more principled and more popular among top players nowadays. }
4... Ne7
{ A very strange move. The idea is that Black wants to play c6 and to transfer the knight directly to g6. Obviously, Nxe5 is not an option, but White has some options such as  5.d4  which is an interesting move to investigate. Otherwise,  5.Nc3  is also playable.   I have a short story which I find quite funny. Not too long ago, I was going through all my notes, and all of a sudden I found a very old notebook where I was writing down my chess games which included the very first tournament I ever played when I was 6 years old. My first game in my first ever tournament game was actually Berlin! I played Berlin with Black and I played this Ne7 move and, well, the thing is that actually I just had the one book of opening traps. Of course, I knew nothing and I didn't even know that it was Berlin but after d3 I knew that there was a trap with Ne7 after 5.Nxe5. }
5. Nxe5
{ This was played by my opponent who was not such a bad player, but I think he saw a six-year-old boy in front of him play this very strange move and I think he took the pawn very quickly. But then there was a trap with c6 and suddenly actually White is losing a piece. }
5... c6 6. Bc4 Qa5+ 7. Bd2 Qxe5
{ Black is a piece up and I rather quickly went on to win this game in my first ever tournament game with Berlin. It's a funny story, but actually Ne7 is not such a bad move. }
