[Black "Spanish Berlin 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Now we will investigate the Berlin defense with Bb5 Nf6. Of course, it is practically maybe the most popular opening nowadays in top-level chess and there is a lot of theory on it @@StartBracket@@much more than when I started to play it in 2000 in my match against Garry Kasparov@@EndBracket@@. Back then, I was already a bit worried about d3, as I understood that this move is much more dangerous than it looks. }
4. d3
{ The serious move. When I prepared Berlin against Garry Kasparov for our match, I was pretty sure that he was not going to play d3 because it's not in the concept of his play. He always tried to play the main line to fight for an opening advantage to play in a very principled way with White. Playing d3 gives Black lots of different choices, he can play d6-Bc5 and there is no way White can be much better here.  But I realized that things are not so easy here and I spent quite some time actually trying to find the best weapon against d3. So it is a serious move. Black's two main options are  4...Bc5  or  4...d6  , where Bc5 is more principled and more popular among top players nowadays. }
4... Bc5
{ Of course, the theory is huge here and I'll just try to give you the general structure of this variation, with certain ideas about different types of positions and the directions for both colors. But it's impossible to cover all the theory of this variation in a limited amount of time so, I will try to do my best to give you as much important knowledge as possible. }
5. Bxc6
{ The general summary of the state of theory is that this is playable for both sides. I would advise that you look at games from top players here as it is important to understand the general ideas. }
5... dxc6
{ Of course, the pawn on e5 is not hanging because of Qd4. So usually White is trying to play slow in this position. Of course, Black's bishop on c5 is somewhat misplaced, so sooner or later it will have to retreat from c5. Objectively, I still don't believe that White can really fight for any real advantage playing like this, but of course, it has its venom, and through that Black has to be careful. But, all in all, it shouldn't be a refutation of Berlin in my opinion.So the main moves are O-O and Nbd2 of course many other tries have been done. But in general, Black's plan is quite simple - to protect the pawn on e5, castle, develop, and maybe try to maneuver his knight to d4. This is one of the most logical plans in general, and Black doesn't really have weaknesses, has the bishop pair and there is no reason why if Black should be any worse.White also has different plans. One of the typical ideas in this position is at some point to play for f4. Another plan is to try to push d4 sooner or later in favorable circumstances. Then also to try and trade a knight for one of Black's bishops, which would put White in a favorable position. White has a flexible and slightly better pawn structure so that is the main asset of White's position and Black's light-squared bishop is a bit limited by pawns. The typical Capablanca concept is that you put pawns on the squares opposite to your bishop. White has a dark-squared bishop so most of his pawns on the light squares are limiting the black bishop on c8.Let's now come to the theory with some concrete lines. }
6. Nbd2 { Black has many different setups here. } 6... Be6 { A solid move. } 7.
O-O Qd6
{ This is not such a popular move, but the computer and statistics like it. } *

