9... f6 10. b4 Bf8 11. a4
{ White has some initiative and Black has to manage to develop his pieces as his bishops are not in good shape. }
11... Nb6
{ In case of  12.Ne3  @@StartBracket@@I think this is what Anand played against me@@EndBracket@@ then at least Black can develop the bishop with  12...Be6  followed by Qd7, and if White goes for a5 then there is always Nc8 and the position is just complicated and unclear. }
12. Na5 { Trying to somehow block the queenside. } 12... c5
{ This is working perfectly fine according to the computer. It is a position that is a bit more comfortable to play as White, but Black has his own potential because of the bishop pair. Black will be slightly better after developing the c8-bishop, so it is playable from both sides. }
13. b5 c4
{ Strange, but the computers like this move. You can also play  13...a6  which is quite complicated. }
14. dxc4 Rb8 15. Qe2 Be6
{ It's quite difficult for White actually to understand what to do with this c4-pawn because Black wants just to play Qe7-Qf7 to attack it and according to the engines, Black is perfectly fine in this position. }
