{ 5...d6  6.c3  O-O  and now play can transpose to:  7.Bg5 systems, 7.h3, 7.Re1, or finally 7.Nbd2. }
6. Nxd4 Bxd4 7. c3 Bb6 8. Na3 c6 9. Ba4 d6
{ There are many games here including the brilliant victory of Levon Aronian as Black against Magnus Carlsen a few years ago in classical chess. White is nominally a bit more comfortable, but in general Black is holding pretty well here and it's considered to be not too dangerous. Of course, you need to study the theory a bit more but there is no real danger - the worst thing that can happen with Black is that he will be nominally slightly worse. But Black has no bad pieces and no weaknesses, so logically there shouldn't be much for White. }
