8. b4 Bb6 9. Nbd2 { This is another move order again stopping e4. } 9... O-O
10. O-O Bf5
{ There was more than one game in rapid chess between Caruana-Grischuk here. This position is rather critical. Fabiano tried here to get some advantage with very direct play. Again, if you're playing this d5 variation yo really need to study it with the engines. }
11. Qc2 Rad8 12. a4 a5 13. b5 Ne7
{ And Fabiano tried different things here but it seems that again, that the engines are holding here as Black. So it seems that it equalizes as well. }
