4... Bc5
{ Of course, the theory is huge here and I'll just try to give you the general structure of this variation, with certain ideas about different types of positions and the directions for both colors. But it's impossible to cover all the theory of this variation in a limited amount of time so, I will try to do my best to give you as much important knowledge as possible. }
5. c3
{ The main move here. I have to mention that there are different move orders with White because lately all plans with playing d5 here or after castles are becoming quite popular and it is quite difficult for White to get anything substantial in those lines. That's why often White also tried to start with castle because without the pawn on c3, it's, of course, more difficult to play d5 and the idea is that now White is threatening Bxc6-Nxe5. }
5... O-O 6. O-O d6
{ I have played this myself many times in classical chess and in rapid chess - a lot of games with practically all top 10 players. The move 6...d6 was considered to be the main line until quite recently when, with new engines, players realized that Black can also play d5 immediately or after castles and it's much more straightforward. It seems that, according to the state of the theory, it's equalizing.But there is nothing wrong with d6, and it reminds very much of the Italian just with the bishop on b5 instead of c4, which has pluses and minuses. But all in all, I think that it's a perfectly solid move and perfectly playable and I can recommend this to you as Black if you want to get a more complicated game because after d6 you have some winning chances. The position is always very complex with lots of strategic ideas for both sides. 6... d5 is more of a concept of trying to equalize by force which is quite fashionable as nowadays in top-level chess, Black just wants to pose maximum concrete problems for his opponent, trying to equalize in a very straightforward manner.Otherwise, I will show you the main ideas here after d6. White has now different move orders and each of them has its own point so, in order to play this system with Black, you have to understand the ideas of the different move orders. }
7. h3 { is very popular move here. } 7... Ne7 8. d4 Bb6 9. Re1 d5
{ And it seems to be very close to equal, White has a slight nominal plus. }
10. Nxe5 Nxe4 11. Nd2 Nd6 12. Bd3 f6 13. Nef3 Bf5 14. Nf1 c6
{ Now we are actually moving pretty much similar to this Petroff defense variation, with perhaps an even better version for Black. So I believe this should equalize and actually might even be the simplest way of playing. }
