{ All in all, the advantage of playing @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d3  is that the position remains more complicated than after  4.O-O  , and White at least gets a game going.  4.d3  won’t give White an objective advantage, but it’s popular nowadays purely because it doesn’t lead to the sterile Berlin endgame @@StartBracket@@which we will examine in the next lesson@@EndBracket@@.   As Black, after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d3  the move  4...d6  is solid, but not the most principled. Instead, the setup with  4...Bc5  is doing perfectly fine, though it is true that Black needs to know a lot of theory. But one thing I like about this variation for Black is that you have a good choice of options which all seem to equalize: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b - - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d6  ,  6...d5  and even  6...Re8  is playable. I’ve played countless games as Black here with good results, and I’ve always thought Black’s position is quite comfortable. }
