[White "Lesson 19: Spanish, Berlin with 4. O-O"]
[Black "Spanish Berlin 4. O-O Nxe4, 7. Bf1 Nf5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O
{ The main line of the Berlin Defense, where Black should take the pawn. } 4...
Nxe4 { The best and probably only move to fight for equality. } 5. Re1
{ Quite an unpleasant move to face. White is completely safe and plays for a small advantage without any risk. I am certain that Black should equalize but care is required. I had many games here, and most of the time I would equalize, but from time to time I got into slightly worse positions.   Nonetheless, given the nature of the position and the symmetric pawn structure, even those slightly worse positions are of course not the end of the world, and the drawing tendencies are certainly high. I would, however, advise you to take the line seriously and plan for it. All in all, 5.Re1 is an excellent option for players wanting to play it safe and like to draw water out of stone. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1
{ Now White wants to play d2-d4, meaning Black has a choice between two moves:  7...Nxe5  and  7...Nf5  ,  which I have both played. }
7... Nf5
{ I used this move if I wanted the, even ever so slight, chance to play for a win. The positions are a little bit more complex than the ones after 7...Nxe5 and strangely enough, I did indeed manage to win some games with this move. Objectively though, I believe 7...Nxe5 to be more sound. }
8. Nf3 { The main move, once again preparing d2-d4. } 8... d5 9. d4 O-O 10. c3
{ White's setup is a bit more harmonious, given that the knights on c6 and f5 are not optimally placed and Black needs to regroup them to fully equalize. Black would do so with ...Be7-d6, ...Nc6-e7, ...c7-c6, sometimes ... f7-f6, or even ...g7-g6/5 which already shows the game can get a bit more complicated in comparison to 7...Nxe5. I am not totally sure Black fully equalizes and most top players indeed chose 7...Nxe5 these days. }
