[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 19: Spanish, Berlin with 4. O-O"]
[Black "Spanish Berlin 4. O-O Nxe4, 7. Bf1 Nxe5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O
{ The main line of the Berlin Defense, where Black should take the pawn. } 4...
Nxe4 { The best and probably only move to fight for equality. } 5. Re1
{ Quite an unpleasant move to face. White is completely safe and plays for a small advantage without any risk. I am certain that Black should equalize but care is required. I had many games here, and most of the time I would equalize, but from time to time I got into slightly worse positions.   Nonetheless, given the nature of the position and the symmetric pawn structure, even those slightly worse positions are of course not the end of the world, and the drawing tendencies are certainly high. I would, however, advise you to take the line seriously and plan for it. All in all, 5.Re1 is an excellent option for players wanting to play it safe and like to draw water out of stone. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1
{ Now White wants to play d2-d4, meaning Black has a choice between two moves:  7...Nxe5  and  7...Nf5  ,  which I have both played. }
7... Nxe5 { The most sound response. } 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. Nc3
{ I had a game with Michael Adams in London 2012 which continued } 9... Bf6 10.
Re1 Re8 11. Nd5 Rxe1 12. Qxe1 b6 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6
{ Black is well-developed and in general, of course, this position can never be much for White, but the pair of bishops does give White some long-term advantage. I did not manage to find a clear way to equality here. }
14. d3 Bb7 15. Qe3 Re8 16. Qf4 Qf5 17. Bd2
{ White will place the pawn on f3, exchange queens and enjoy a small plus. Black must be able to hold, but it's a two-result game. Therefore, I wanted a more clear-cut solution. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 19: Spanish, Berlin with 4. O-O"]
[Black "Spanish Berlin 4. O-O Nxe4, 7. Bf1 Nxe5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O
{ The main line of the Berlin Defense, where Black should take the pawn. } 4...
Nxe4 { The best and probably only move to fight for equality. } 5. Re1
{ Quite an unpleasant move to face. White is completely safe and plays for a small advantage without any risk. I am certain that Black should equalize but care is required. I had many games here, and most of the time I would equalize, but from time to time I got into slightly worse positions.   Nonetheless, given the nature of the position and the symmetric pawn structure, even those slightly worse positions are of course not the end of the world, and the drawing tendencies are certainly high. I would, however, advise you to take the line seriously and plan for it. All in all, 5.Re1 is an excellent option for players wanting to play it safe and like to draw water out of stone. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1
{ Now White wants to play d2-d4, meaning Black has a choice between two moves:  7...Nxe5  and  7...Nf5  ,  which I have both played. }
7... Nxe5 { The most sound response. } 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. Nc3
{ Using the fact that the knight is still on d6, White is trying to get the bishop pair. }
9... Ne8 { The most popular move in the position these days. } 10. Nd5 Bd6 11.
Re1 c6 12. Ne3
{ White's play looks somewhat strange, jumping around with the knight, but the point is that  12...Bc7  13.Nf5  comes. }
12... Bc7 13. Nf5 { White's point, chasing the bishop pair. } 13... d5 14. Ne7+
{ White takes the bishop pair. } 14... Kh8 15. Nxc8 Rxc8 16. d3
{ The engine evaluates this position to be slightly better for White, around 0.2-0.3, but in my opinion, Black's position is very safe and White is only nominally better. Black has the so-called 'Capablanca setup' with a dark-squared bishop and all pawns on light squares making it quite difficult for White to get something out of this position, yet it can be tried. }
16... f5
{ I like to place the pawn here, giving Black, potentially, some active options on the kingside and limiting White's options. Play can develop: }
17. Bd2 Nf6 18. Qf3 Qd7 19. g3
{ White often plays g2-g3 but we have the typical plan of ... Nf6-g4 followed by ...Rce8. All in all, I think Black is perfectly safe but computers still give a small plus for White. }
*

