7... Nxe5 { The most sound response. } 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 { The main move. }
9... Bf6 10. Re1 Re8
{ Lots of top-level games have reached this position. Magnus Carlsen sometimes used it to force a draw when he needed to, in order to win a tournament for instance, but at times he would also try to squeeze something out of this position. I would once again reiterate the need for precision, as it is very easy to land into a slightly worse, yet unpleasant position here. }
11. c3 Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Ne8
{ Black is aiming for ...d7-d5, when we have a symmetrical position where White has some extra tempi and I can add that the bishop on f6 would be better placed on d6 @@StartBracket@@after ...d7-d5@@EndBracket@@. That means White is pressing a bit but nowadays there isn't much space left because of the enormous amount of games that have been played here. It's very hard to find a new idea here and knowing the theory should be enough for Black to equalize. }
13. Bf4 d5 14. Nd2
{ Allowing the bishop to f5 but aiming at controlling the e-file. } 14... Bf5
15. Qe3 { White wants to follow up with Ra1-e1. } 15... Qd7
{ Or  15...c6  and Black should normally be able to hold with ease.  To sum up what we have seen in the 5.Re1 line: It is slightly uncomfortable for Black in the sense that we have zero winning chances, have to display some accuracy, while White enjoys a risk-free game. Once you study the variation though and know what to do against it, it of course isn't going to be a big problem objectively. }
