1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O
{ The main line of the Berlin Defense, where Black should take the pawn. } 4...
Nxe4 { The best and probably only move to fight for equality. } 5. d4
{ The main move in the position and practically the most dangerous. } 5... Nd6
{ 5...Be7  is possible, but we will not go into that any further. } 6. Ba4
{ This has recently become popular but I would be surprised if the trend lasts. Nowadays computers are very powerful, and I don't believe this pawn sacrifice should give White an advantage. Nevertheless, some very strong players like Ian Nepomniachtchi have played this way, multiple times and Black is currently searching for the most accurate way to neutralize this variation. }
6... e4 { One of the current battlegrounds. } 7. Re1 Be7 8. Ne5 O-O 9. Nc3 f5
{ A very complicated position where both sides are risking. Black is a pawn up but has a bad knight on d6, hampering the development and general piece coordination, which ensures that White has definite compensation. I would advise you to analyze it well before entering this position with either color. }
