9. Nc3
{ The most popular move in the position. Black now has two different concepts:   1@@EndBracket@@ One is to bring the king to the queenside, with ...Bc8-d7, ...Kd8-c8, ...b7-b6, ... Kc8-b7 followed by bringing the a8-rook into the game.   2@@EndBracket@@ The second is to bring the king to e8, from where it protects f7 and generally helps safeguard the kingside. Of course, in this case it is harder to connect the rooks.   Both plans are viable and in my match with Garry, where four Berlin Endgames were played, I twice brought my king to the queenside and twice brought it to e8. }
9... Bd7 { Planning to bring the king to c8. } 10. h3
{ Always a useful move, preparing the g2-g4 advance. } 10... h6
{ I played this way myself against Garry, and at the time it was thought to almost be a forced move. It still holds up to this day but requires some knowledge. }
11. b3
{ It is my understanding that when the black king develops to the queenside, it's best to develop the bishop on b2. The reasoning is very simple - with the king on the queenside, Black's kingside is a bit more vulnerable and with the bishop on b2 and a potential e5-e6 break, White can try to make use of that. }
11... Kc8 12. Bb2
{ White wants to play Nc3-e2-f4, Rf1-e1 and break with e5-e6, when there will be a lot of pressure on the kingside. With the king on e8, this plan is much less dangerous. }
12... b6
{ The whole plan of ...Bd7 and ...Kc8 first appeared just a few months before my match with Gary. Hungarian Grandmaster Zoltan Almasi introduced it and it took my interest, I started analyzing it, and essentially there was no theory whatsoever. Before, in the Berlin, the king would generally go to e8.   12...a5  This is a move as well, and when you analyze this opening, I would recommend that you always look out for these small nuances. }
13. Rad1
{ Trying to stop Black from developing, since the king can no longer move to  b7  now and  13...Be6  Ne2-Nf4  is problematic. The exchange on e6 generally always favors White. Another option could be  14.g4  Ne7  15.Nd4  hitting the bishop and following up with f2-f4. }
13... c5
{ Lately this move has taken center stage. Back in 2000 I did not want to play this move for the simple reason it allows the knight to reach d5 followed by c2-c4. This is indeed tricky to allow, but at the same time the nature of the position now becomes more direct. }
14. Rfe1
{ This was played in the very important, 11th game of the World Chess Championship match between Magnus Carlsen and Vishy Anand in Sochi, 2014. If you are interested in this particular variation of the Berlin Endgame, I recommend you to study it carefully. Magnus, obviously, knew that  14.Nd5  is not the best move in the position and instead makes a very useful waiting move, and gets ready for e5-e6. }
14... Be6
{ Black is just in time to execute the other desirable plan in the position and get the bishop to e6. }
15. Nd5 { White wants to go to f4 and take the bishop on e6. } 15... g5
{ The idea! Black takes the control of the f4 square and secures the bishop on e6. If White had time to play Nf4 and exchange, White would be better, therefore, the text move prevents this. Now the game continues in a very logical manner. }
16. c4 Kb7
{ While there is no counterplay on the a-file in this case, Black did manage to get the bishop to e6 and pawn to g5. A very strange position that is strategically dangerous for Black but it seems there is always enough counterplay. }
17. Kh2
{ White can also start with  17.g4  , but after  17...Ne7  ,  there is not much else to do but to place the king to g3 and break with h4. }
17... a5 18. a4 Ne7 19. g4 Ng6 20. Kg3 Be7 21. Nd2
{ 21.Nxe7  Nxe7  is not too dangerous as the knight on d5 is the main asset of White's position. If you are playing White, you should also be careful and not forget that one day, the black bishop can arrive to c2, when the queenside pawns would collapse 1 by 1.  @@StartFEN@@r6r/1kp1bp2/1p2b1np/p1pNP1p1/P1P3P1/1P3NKP/1B3P2/3RR3 w - - 3 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Nf6  is another idea, but I assume Vishy would have done something similar to what he did in the game. }
21... Rhd8 22. Ne4 { Magnus decides to bring the other knight to f6. } 22...
Bf8 { Very logical plan. Both sides are improving their position. } 23. Bc3
{ A very important point. I think Magnus should have played this move as it might be more accurate, as this is a prophylactic move against b5, even though it doesn't entirely stop it. }
23... b5
{ Still, Vishy could have probably done the same as he did in the game. This is a very important plan in the position as otherwise, Black is extremely passive, even though it is extremely difficult for White to break through. }
24. axb5 c6 25. bxc6+ Kxc6 { Black just wants to take the pawn on d5 back. }
26. Ndf6 Rxd1 27. Rxd1 a4
{ And Black is in time to organize enough counterplay for equality in this position. }
*

