9. Nc3
{ The most popular move in the position. Black now has two different concepts:   1@@EndBracket@@ One is to bring the king to the queenside, with ...Bc8-d7, ...Kd8-c8, ...b7-b6, ... Kc8-b7 followed by bringing the a8-rook into the game.   2@@EndBracket@@ The second is to bring the king to e8, from where it protects f7 and generally helps safeguard the kingside. Of course, in this case it is harder to connect the rooks.   Both plans are viable and in my match with Garry, where four Berlin Endgames were played, I twice brought my king to the queenside and twice brought it to e8. }
9... Bd7 { Planning to bring the king to c8. } 10. h3
{ Always a useful move, preparing the g2-g4 advance. } 10... Be7
{ A recent trend, with help of the engines. I was always worried about the type of positions arising after g4. }
11. g4 Nh4 12. Nxh4 Bxh4
{ White would just continue Kg1-g2 and f2-f4-f5. Black seems to be in time though, despite the position being strategically very dangerous. }
13. Ne4 h5
{ An important move, stopping f2-f4. After for instance  13...Re8  14.Bf4  , White is just better. }
14. f3 b6 15. Bg5+ Bxg5 16. Nxg5 Ke7 17. Kg2
{ White only needs to play Kg2-g3, Ra1-d1 with a clear advantage strategically, but Black, with help of engines, always holds here! It's hard for humans though, as we aren't always able to distinguish which strategically dangerous position is actually bad, and which one is in fact fine. I prefer not to play with this strategic danger as practically it is very difficult to make these assessments. Objectively though, it seems like Black is doing okay according to theory but it's not bullet-proof, not at all I would say! }
