9. Nc3
{ Lately, a third concept appeared - to keep the king on d8! Frankly, back in 2000 this had never occurred to me, but it is now becoming very popular. }
9... Be7 10. h3 Nh4
{ A very direct way of playing, the difference is that the king can sometimes still go to c8 meaning Black retains more flexibility. The line has been played by Wesley So and Alexander Grischuk and is maybe the place to start studying this endgame as for players from the White side, it is essential to have an idea here, as it may well become the main line. }
