{ This move is much safer, as the king is protecting the kingside and the pawn on f7. But it is a bit more difficult for Black to coordinate the rooks and there is no clear plan as in the lines with Bd7.This variation is a bit more safe for Black, but it is not bulletproof and White still has some ideas. }
10. h3
{ As I mentioned already, always useful. There is a little waiting game ongoing here where both sides are eager to see their opponent's plan. Depending on the setup Black chooses, White will react accordingly. In the meantime, White makes the useful waiting move 10.h3, which is very useful as it prepares the kingside expansion in the future - which is White's most dangerous plan in this position. Black has a wide range of setups here. }
10... Ne7
{ And old and half forgotten move. This plan was very popular many years ago. The idea is to maneuver the knight to g6, preventing the whole idea associated with g4. It does make sense as the knight on g6 is bothering the pawn on e5, but it is also a bit slow. Nowadays, this move has almost disappeared from tournament practice, even though White really needs to know what they are doing in order to get an advantage. }
11. Re1 { 11.Ne4  Ng6  12.Re1  transposes. } 11... Ng6 12. Ne4
{ A very important position of this variation. Black's problem is that they can't develop comfortable here. }
12... Be6 { Is not that reliable. } 13. Nd4
{ Bothering the bishop on  e6  .  13.Neg5  Bd5  14.e6  also needs to be checked, as it looks extremely dangerous. }
13... Bd5 14. b3 { Very annoying move, trying to play c4 in the future. } 14...
Rd8 { Creating some threats against the knight on d4. } 15. Bb2
{ Covering the knight. c4 is a serious threat and there are also some tactics in this position. }
15... Nf4 { Trying to get the knight to d3 in case of c4. } 16. e6
{ A very typical idea with the rook on e1 and king on e8. } 16... Nxe6 17. Ng5
{ Threats now include taking on e6 as well as c4 and Black is in serious trouble. }
