9. Nc3
{ The most popular move in the position. Black now has two different concepts:   1@@EndBracket@@ One is to bring the king to the queenside, with ...Bc8-d7, ...Kd8-c8, ...b7-b6, ... Kc8-b7 followed by bringing the a8-rook into the game.   2@@EndBracket@@ The second is to bring the king to e8, from where it protects f7 and generally helps safeguard the kingside. Of course, in this case it is harder to connect the rooks.   Both plans are viable and in my match with Garry, where four Berlin Endgames were played, I twice brought my king to the queenside and twice brought it to e8. }
9... Ke8
{ This move is much safer, as the king is protecting the kingside and the pawn on f7. But it is a bit more difficult for Black to coordinate the rooks and there is no clear plan as in the lines with Bd7.This variation is a bit more safe for Black, but it is not bulletproof and White still has some ideas. }
10. h3
{ As I mentioned already, always useful. There is a little waiting game ongoing here where both sides are eager to see their opponent's plan. Depending on the setup Black chooses, White will react accordingly. In the meantime, White makes the useful waiting move 10.h3, which is very useful as it prepares the kingside expansion in the future - which is White's most dangerous plan in this position. Black has a wide range of setups here. }
10... Be6 { Here this move is dangerous for Black. } 11. g4
{ 11.Ng5  is also dangerous, but this move, followed by  12.Nd4  is also possible.  @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/ppp2ppp/2p1b3/4Pn2/8/2N2N1P/PPP2PP1/R1B2RK1 w - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Rd1  is also possible and it is something I would recommend you to study if you want to avoid long, forced lines. }
11... Ne7 12. Nd4
{ And here you can see why @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/ppp2ppp/2p5/4Pn2/8/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B2RK1 w - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.h3  is useful - g4 is not hanging in this variation. Now White wants to play f4-f5 here. }
12... Bd7 { If White manages to capture the bishop, they have the advantage. }
13. f4 { Now this is very dangerous for Black. } 13... h5 14. f5 hxg4 15. hxg4
{ Now if White is left in peace, they will have the advantage due to more space, but there are some tactics that might work for Black in the end. }
15... Rh4 16. Rf4 Nd5 17. Nxd5 cxd5
{ At least Black managed to exchange one pair of knights and undouble the pawns. }
18. Nf3 Rh8
{ And here there is a lot of theory. Black's position looks extremely dangerous and it is quite a risky line, although with the help of the engines it can probably be proven that it is holdable. In any case, it is necessary to memorize a number of long, forced computer variations and the reward will be - at best - a forced draw. All in all, it is a dubious line that is not to be particularly recommended. }
*

