1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O
{ The main line of the Berlin Defense, where Black should take the pawn. } 4...
Nxe4 { The best and probably only move to fight for equality. } 5. d4
{ The main move in the position and practically the most dangerous. } 5... Nd6
{ 5...Be7  is possible, but we will not go into that any further. } 6. Bxc6
dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Quite a familiar position for me! Let's first discuss some general things about this endgame. I played a World Championship match against Garry Kasparov in the year 2000 and this endgame was one of the key positions in this match. I held it pretty well during the match and continued playing it afterward as well. By now, an enormous amount of theory has been amassed, but in 2000 this was not at all the case. The number of theoretical lines can almost be compared to the Najdorf! :@@EndBracket@@   The endgame is extremely subtle, and even Garry Kasparov needed serious time to get to the nuances of it. In my opinion, the endgame is very strange and a rare case in the opening theory. Even some very strong players make mistakes, lose the right path, or simply outright lose this endgame from either side. It shows just how complicated it is. The position at hand is probably the most important one in modern opening theory and I won't be able to show you a complete overview of the variations. Instead, I will try to give my impressions on the endgame in which understanding and getting a general feeling is perhaps just as important as concrete lines.   At first glance, it looks like Black must be doing perfectly fine. Black has the pair of bishops and usually, with the pawn on e4, instead of e5, Black's light-squared bishop is more limited making it strategically more sound for White. With the pawn being on e5, the light squares are weakened, and the light-squared bishop can potentially become very powerful in this variation. The main problem for Black is that it is very difficult to connect the rooks. And in general, developing pieces in such a way that they won't get attacked or traded off is not simple either. For instance, if Black wants to play ...Bc8-e6 here, Nf3-g5 will come, which is usually a problem because after an exchange on e6 White is better most of the time, unless Black has a direct tactical resource. It is difficult for White to find a clear way of playing, as there are many setups for either side. Black, ideally, would play ...Bc8-e6, ...Bf8-e7, and somehow double rooks on the d-file etc. But it is next to impossible to achieve.  To sum up, I would say Black's main problem is coordination.   What makes this endgame hard to play for White is the fact that Black has the long-term asset of the bishop pair and there are no clear targets in Black's position. While White has a better pawn structure, Black's queenside pawns should also not be underestimated, as often the double c-pawns can be undoubled by pushing them forward while in general the structure a7, b6, c7, c5 with the light-squared bishop on, say, b7, is not that bad either.  The two main ideas for White are to push e5-e6, often preparing it by bringing a knight to f4 and rook to e1, which would make use of the pawn majority on the kingside. The second plan also comes down to that pawn majority. Instead of aiming for e5-e6, White can also try to push the entire kingside forward, h2-h3, g2-g4, and potentially f2-f4-f5 which is of course easier said than done. Often after White pushes g2-g4, Black aims for a counterattack with ...h7-h5 meaning those pawn pushes should be treated with great care. It can easily backfire!   When I started studying and playing the Berlin there was almost no theory, and it was almost exclusively about strategical understanding. I tried various setups and analyzed those in a strategic manner. Conceptually, with the rise of engines and the popularity of the Berlin in general, the opening changed a lot. It became a lot more forced and, as a professional who wants to play the Berlin Endgame, you need to know a lot of concrete lines. }
9. Nc3
{ The most popular move in the position. Black now has two different concepts:   1@@EndBracket@@ One is to bring the king to the queenside, with ...Bc8-d7, ...Kd8-c8, ...b7-b6, ... Kc8-b7 followed by bringing the a8-rook into the game.   2@@EndBracket@@ The second is to bring the king to e8, from where it protects f7 and generally helps safeguard the kingside. Of course, in this case it is harder to connect the rooks.   Both plans are viable and in my match with Garry, where four Berlin Endgames were played, I twice brought my king to the queenside and twice brought it to e8. }
9... Ke8
{ This move is much safer, as the king is protecting the kingside and the pawn on f7. But it is a bit more difficult for Black to coordinate the rooks and there is no clear plan as in the lines with Bd7.This variation is a bit more safe for Black, but it is not bulletproof and White still has some ideas. }
10. h3
{ As I mentioned already, always useful. There is a little waiting game ongoing here where both sides are eager to see their opponent's plan. Depending on the setup Black chooses, White will react accordingly. In the meantime, White makes the useful waiting move 10.h3, which is very useful as it prepares the kingside expansion in the future - which is White's most dangerous plan in this position. Black has a wide range of setups here. }
10... Be7
{ This is a very logical move, simply developing the pieces. I played it against Garry Kasparov in 2001 after the match. This was the first time this move was employed at the very top level. }
11. g4
{ Very important and dangerous. Garry played  11.Bg5  against me. I don't think this is necessarily the most dangerous try for Black. I did suffer in that game a little bit, but managed to make a draw in the end. }
11... Nh4 12. Nxh4 Bxh4
{ And this is a strange position and a strange opening line. In general, if White manages to achieve the setup I am going to show, it can become very unpleasant for Black. There was a very important game I am going to show you - Jakovenko - Wang Yue, where Jakovenko managed to find the correct plan and pose problems to his opponent. }
13. Rd1 { This was Jakovenko's move order. } 13... Be7
{ Black wanted to get his desired setup. } 14. Kg2 h5 15. f3
{ This is the tabiya of this variation. } 15... Be6
{ Outwardly, it seems to be quite harmless, but White found a very unpleasant plan in this position. I wouldn't say it is winning, but it doesn't make playing the Black position fun. }
16. Ne2 Rd8 17. Be3 a6 18. Nf4 g6 { This was the setup of the Chinese player. }
19. Rxd8+ Kxd8 20. Rd1+ Kc8 21. Nxe6 fxe6
{ Play will soon go into a rook endgame and Wang Yue thought it is a draw. But as Jakovenko explained in an interview - he started to analyze this endgame and the final position he had on the board @@StartBracket@@that happened on move 54@@EndBracket@@ was still part of his home preparation. In the end, he found some study-like way to win it, although this does not have much to do with practical chess.In any case, the whole 10...Be7 system is simply trying to fight for a draw. I definitely don't recommend you to go for this line, but maybe there is an improvement in move orders along the way that allows Black to avoid the most dangerous line. }
*

