[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 19: Spanish, Berlin with 4. O-O"]
[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ 1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Nf6  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.d4  Nd6  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  The Berlin Endgame used to be assessed quite differently by the engines, back in 2000. Fritz, which was the best engine at the time, gave White a +1 advantage in the starting position @@StartBracket@@after the exchange on d8@@EndBracket@@. The engine did not like the doubled pawns and king in the center, which accounted for the high evaluation. That made it very hard to analyze the endgame properly because I felt it wasn't that bad at all, but when I started analyzing with Fritz it was always '+1' which made it a bit hard, psychologically, always to go against the machine.   Right now, we are on the other side of radicalism, with computers claiming equality almost in every single position, but I believe it is not that easy at all. White can try, and to equalize the Berlin Endgame isn't that easy at all.  9.Nc3  Objectively, I believe Kasparov was right that here is the best chance to fight for an opening advantage in the entire Berlin. There are still ideas left to be found, with both colors, and it's not easy for Black to fully equalize.   Players I can advise you to follow are Alexander Grischuk who won some very good games from White's side of the endgame, where he shows that things are not that trivial. Maxime Vachier-Lagrave is definitely another player to follow here. It's very important to get the practice and feel for this endgame, apart from learning the theory.    9...Ke8  10.h3  h5  Black is currently in fine shape after 10...h5 but you need to do your homework. The endgame inhibits a mix of theory, calculation, and positional/strategic understanding which is not easy to develop. Any idea that is played always needs to be backed up with good calculation in the endgame.   I think Black, in general, should equalize, though I would emphasize again that it is not as simple as people believe nowadays. Many players have moved to 4.d3 or the 5.Re1 line, agreeing that the endgame is fine for Black, but I am sure that if you invest the time, problems can still be posed for Black in the endgame.  In this limited time, I tried to give an overview of the Berlin where I gave some directions and a certain structure to the opening as well as a look at the current opening theory. I also tried to show you most of the typical ideas.   The Berlin is probably the most important opening after 1.e4 which is why we spent more time here than on some other big lines. My aim was to give you a base of knowledge and understanding of the Berlin, but as usual, some work will still need to be done. The Berlin is here to stay for years to come so it's important for any 1. e4 player to get a good understanding of this opening.   To close this lesson, AlphaZero, after playing itself for countless games, and developing its own opening theory from scratch, came to the conclusion that the Berlin is the best opening after 1.e4. Of course, with a small margin, as other openings are fine as well, but as Black, it decided on employing the Berlin. It is a serious opening and I hope after these two long lessons you now have a clearer picture about this opening variation. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 20: Open Spanish & White's Early Alternatives"]
[Black "Spanish Early Alternatives: Exchange 3... a6 4. Bxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Even though the Berlin Defense is very popular, the move 3... a6 has not yet been refuted :@@EndBracket@@ Black has many options in this variation and objectively White is struggling to get an advantage. At the same time, none of these variations are easy for Black, and require a lot of @@StartBracket@@concrete@@EndBracket@@ knowledge as White has a number of options as well. In this lesson, we look at the Open Ruy Lopez, and will also consider some lines in which White avoids this variation. }
4. Bxc6
{ The Exchange Variation of the Ruy Lopez, which is currently out of fashion. There is some logic to the line, as, instead of losing a tempo retreating the bishop to a4, White captures the knight and follows up with castling. Robert James Fischer was quite successful with this variation, though it should be said Fischer was successful with most of the variations he played. He was, after all, a much stronger player than his opponents. In his time, without computers and less tournament practice, it was harder to equalize not just in the Exchange Variation, but in many variations in general. As it stands currently, Black has many ways to meet this opening and most of them are doing well. It is not clear what White is hoping for theoretically. }
4... dxc6 5. O-O
{ Most played since e5 is not really hanging.  5.Nxe5  Qd4  wins back the pawn immediately. }
5... Qf6
{ Even a seemingly illogical move as this one, is playable.   5...Ne7  is possible too. }
6. d4 { 6.d3  Ne7  is quite good for Black. } 6... exd4 7. Bg5 Qd6
{ There is some theory on this position, but Black doesn't experience any problems here. }
*

