[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Even though the Berlin Defense is very popular, the move 3... a6 has not yet been refuted :@@EndBracket@@ Black has many options in this variation and objectively White is struggling to get an advantage. At the same time, none of these variations are easy for Black, and require a lot of @@StartBracket@@concrete@@EndBracket@@ knowledge as White has a number of options as well. In this lesson, we look at the Open Ruy Lopez, and will also consider some lines in which White avoids this variation. }
4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3
{ The most serious of the 5th move sidelines. We will see more d3-setups in later lessons. White avoids the Open Ruy Lopez and tries to reach a position similar to the standard, closed Ruy Lopez. }
5... Bc5 { The most precise way of playing, in my opinion. } 6. c3 d6
{ This is how I wanted to play myself against this variation, some years ago. If I checked it well, Black should be doing fine here. }
7. Bg5
{ Without ...b5 Bb3 included, this is a better version of the Bg5-line we saw earlier. }
7... Ba7 8. Nbd2 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 O-O
{ We always have to be careful with castling, having played the move ...g7-g5, but the computers approve it here.   A recent idea is  10...Bd7  followed by ... Ne7-g6. }
11. O-O Ne7
{ This already works, which is an important difference with the Italian. } 12.
d4
{ The only critical move. If Black is allowed to put the knight on g6, there will surely be no problems. }
12... Nh5 13. dxe5 Nxg3 14. hxg3 dxe5 15. Nxe5 Qd6
{ Winning back the pawn on g3. } 16. Ndf3 g4
{ White loses material in this case. To conclude, 5.d3 is a good side-option. It avoids a lot of theory and is not completely harmless. It is a good weapon for Ruy Lopez players to have in their arsenal. For players from the Black side, it shouldn't be too worrying. Simply a system has to be chosen and theoretically, there are no major problems. }
