{ This move is closely related to 9.c3, but gives Black an extra option of  9...Nc5  . }
9... Nc5 { A very serious variation as well. } 10. c3 d4
{ Most of you may recall the famous Kasparov-Anand game from their World Championship match of 1995, where Kasparov won in brilliant style. I was part of Kasparov's team during that match and we spent a lot of time analyzing these lines. }
11. Ng5
{ A beautiful move that was discovered before the computer era by Karpov's trainer Igor Zaitsev. You need quite an imagination to come up with such a move! It was for a long time the main line in this variation. }
11... Qxg5 12. Qf3 O-O-O 13. Bxe6+ fxe6 14. Qxc6 Qxe5
{ Extremely direct play, which still continued. } 15. b4 Qd5 16. Qxd5 exd5 17.
bxc5 dxc3 18. Nb3 d4
{ What a position! In 1995 there weren't any serious engines around, so I was mostly analyzing it with Garry over the board. }
19. Ba3
{ White is still fighting for an advantage but the final assessment these days is that it is practically a forced draw. }
