{ This move is closely related to 9.c3, but gives Black an extra option of  9...Nc5  . }
9... Nc5 { A very serious variation as well. } 10. c3 d4
{ Most of you may recall the famous Kasparov-Anand game from their World Championship match of 1995, where Kasparov won in brilliant style. I was part of Kasparov's team during that match and we spent a lot of time analyzing these lines. }
11. Bxe6 { Nowadays, the main test. } 11... Nxe6 12. cxd4 Ncxd4
{ This position was discussed, amongst other places, in the 1978 Karpov-Korchnoi match. }
13. a4
{ Karpov's novelty, introduced in 1981 and still the critical way of playing. Frankly, it's a position I wouldn't like to play with either side! With White, the fear is that the advantage is too little, while with Black the feeling is that we haven't really equalized just yet.   On the other hand, holding it with Black means 9.Nbd2 is no longer an issue, so it is worth spending time here to see if it is possible to equalize this way. }
13... Bb4 { 13...Be7  is possible as well. } 14. axb5 Nxb5
{ The solid choice, leading to a more positional game. The pawn structure is a bit compromised but Black will manage to castle. White is slightly better, but it is definitely not much. This situation is very much the case in many variations of the Open Ruy Lopez. }
