{ The tabiya. Black has active pieces, no clear weaknesses, but there is strategic danger in the form of a backward pawn on c7 and the knight on e4, which is vulnerable to attack. If Black plays it too slowly, White plays Nbd2 and after exchanging on d2, follows up with Re1, c3, Bc2 and has a potential attack on the kingside. This was perhaps the reason why before the computer era this opening variation wasn't as popular as White has many different systems and ideas. Korchnoi used it in his World Championship matches against Anatoly Karpov, not always with great success.   Nowadays though, with computers, and the nature of this opening, which is very direct, the opening took a different turn. Top players have secured equal chances in all the main lines, though it requires a lot of memory and White has many tries.   Without pretending to be complete, I will show you the main lines that White can choose from here to give you an idea of what the Open Ruy Lopez is about. Of course, if you wish to play this variation, you will have to study those small sidelines as well. }
9. c3
{ Closely related to 9.Nbd2, but giving Black the extra option of  9...Bc5  . }
9... Bc5
{ Black's extra option which, according to modern theory, leads to balanced play, but it's a very demanding variation. }
10. Qe2 O-O 11. Be3 { White's safe choice. } 11... Bxe3 12. Qxe3 f6 13. exf6
Qxf6 14. Nbd2 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Rad8
{ It looks like Black has equalized comfortably but some care is required because of the queenside structure. All in all, though Black is of course very close to equalizing completely. }
