[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Even though the Berlin Defense is very popular, the move 3... a6 has not yet been refuted :@@EndBracket@@ Black has many options in this variation and objectively White is struggling to get an advantage. At the same time, none of these variations are easy for Black, and require a lot of @@StartBracket@@concrete@@EndBracket@@ knowledge as White has a number of options as well. In this lesson, we look at the Open Ruy Lopez, and will also consider some lines in which White avoids this variation. }
4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ The Open variation of the Ruy Lopez. Essentially, we have a Berlin Defense with the moves ...a7-a6 and Bb5-a4 included. That 'little' difference actually means a lot and leads to completely different types of positions. Taking on e4 is very logical and in the 90s, when I saw everyone playing the main line Ruy Lopez variation, like Zaitsev and Breyer, I was wondering why more players didn't go for this variation.   Just like in the Berlin Defense, where Black takes on e4 as well, this is the real test of White's play as Black is capturing a pawn. Theoretically speaking, Black is doing very well as I don't see any advantage for White. I am a bit surprised it's not more popular, but perhaps it's a matter of fashion.   The only problem I see is that a big number of lines need to be remembered and most of the time Black is not having realistic winning chances, at the top level that is. Black is essentially trying to force a draw, and as White, you really need to have something prepared here. }
6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6
{ The tabiya. Black has active pieces, no clear weaknesses, but there is strategic danger in the form of a backward pawn on c7 and the knight on e4, which is vulnerable to attack. If Black plays it too slowly, White plays Nbd2 and after exchanging on d2, follows up with Re1, c3, Bc2 and has a potential attack on the kingside. This was perhaps the reason why before the computer era this opening variation wasn't as popular as White has many different systems and ideas. Korchnoi used it in his World Championship matches against Anatoly Karpov, not always with great success.   Nowadays though, with computers, and the nature of this opening, which is very direct, the opening took a different turn. Top players have secured equal chances in all the main lines, though it requires a lot of memory and White has many tries.   Without pretending to be complete, I will show you the main lines that White can choose from here to give you an idea of what the Open Ruy Lopez is about. Of course, if you wish to play this variation, you will have to study those small sidelines as well. }
9. c3
{ Closely related to 9.Nbd2, but giving Black the extra option of  9...Bc5  . }
9... Be7 { The safer choice. } 10. Nbd2
{ A very important position, as we said it can be reached via both 9.c3 and 9.Nbd2 move orders.   10.Be3  transposes to the9.Be3 variation. }
10... O-O 11. Bc2 f5
{ This line used to be considered slightly worse/dubious, but I see more and more top players applying this variation, and not without success. }
12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nfd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5
{ The main position for this line, which optically looks quite dubious for Black. White usually tries to take on g5 and follow up with f3-f4 to start a kingside initiative, potentially with g2-g4 in the future as well. Playing f3-f4 immediately would of course allow the knight to jump back to e4. }
17. a4 Rad8 18. axb5 axb5
{ There are many games here, and Black is clearly only fighting for a draw, but it seems to also work. }
19. Bxg5 Bxg5 20. f4 Be7 21. Kh1 Kh8 22. Qe2 c4
{ Top players will certainly have notes well beyond this point, but if you aren't one of them, this would be a fine moment to stop. Black is definitely holding but needs, at all times, to be ready for the g2-g4 push. As long as that is kept in mind, it is definitely playable. }
