[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ 1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.O-O  Nxe4  That concludes the Open Ruy Lopez.   A very principled line, which is not very fashionable nowadays. I think that is because, as we have seen, in the main lines, Black has to know a lot of things, in order 'just' to make a draw. This may not be to everyone's liking. On the other hand, if you analyzed it well and you are confident, mentally ready, there is no reason not to play it.   There is quite a wide choice for White, especially for one game, but at the very top, it is very hard to avoid a 'forced draw'. At the same time, there is a psychological twist as well, where players from the White side know it's not easy for the opponent to memorize all the different tries, so playing it is quite a heavy burden. In that sense it's slightly uncomfortable for both sides; White objectively doesn't have many weapons, Black needs to be ready from all possible angles. All in all, it's a very serious variation with a rich history. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 21: Spanish 5... b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 and 5... Bc5"]
[Black "Spanish 5... b5 6. Bb3 Bb7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O
{ In this Lesson we'll consider all of Black's systems after  5.O-O  where Black develops the bishop to c5. There are different move orders Black can use to achieve this, but the most popular one is  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  .  On c5 the bishop is, of course, more active than on e7, putting some pressure on White's center @@StartBracket@@after White continues with c3 and d4, as he usually does@@EndBracket@@, so it makes sense to develop the bishop to the a7-g1 diagonal, especially if Black is going to choose a setup with ...d6 anyway.The drawback of developing the bishop to c5 is that Black will lose time, e.g. after White plays c3 and d4, forcing Black to move the bishop from c5. The question is whether Black is in time to develop normally - ...d6, ...O-O and so on. If he can achieve normal development, then Black essentially has an improved version of the 'standard' Ruy Lopez where the bishop is on e7 instead.One of the advantages of this system is that Black's play is easy and natural. The disadvantage is that it's less solid than the lines with ...Be7 and Black will need to know a lot of theory. At the same time, though, it is also more demanding for White.At the moment, the system with ...Bc5 is doing well as there's no clear way for White to get an advantage according to theory, but there are certain lines where I feel that it's possible for White to find new ideas and moves that are unpleasant for Black. So, I'm not sure that the ...Bc5 system is bullet-proof. }
5... b5 6. Bb3 Bb7
{ Speaking about the history of the variation, this was for a long time supposed to be the only way for Black to develop the bishop to c5. This move remains playable, and even Magnus Carlsen has played it. }
7. d4 { This is a dangerous move which Black has to consider in this line. }
7... Nxd4 { However, this seems to be working well for Black. } 8. Bxf7+
{ A dangerous move that has to be checked. After  8.Nxd4  exd4  it seems that everything works out for Black - e.g. the pawn on d4 can't be captured due to the threat of ...c5-c4. }
8... Kxf7 9. Nxe5+ Kg8 10. Qxd4 c5 11. Qd1 Qe8
{ This position is perfectly fine for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 21: Spanish 5... b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 and 5... Bc5"]
[Black "Spanish 5... b5 6. Bb3 Bb7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O
{ In this Lesson we'll consider all of Black's systems after  5.O-O  where Black develops the bishop to c5. There are different move orders Black can use to achieve this, but the most popular one is  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  .  On c5 the bishop is, of course, more active than on e7, putting some pressure on White's center @@StartBracket@@after White continues with c3 and d4, as he usually does@@EndBracket@@, so it makes sense to develop the bishop to the a7-g1 diagonal, especially if Black is going to choose a setup with ...d6 anyway.The drawback of developing the bishop to c5 is that Black will lose time, e.g. after White plays c3 and d4, forcing Black to move the bishop from c5. The question is whether Black is in time to develop normally - ...d6, ...O-O and so on. If he can achieve normal development, then Black essentially has an improved version of the 'standard' Ruy Lopez where the bishop is on e7 instead.One of the advantages of this system is that Black's play is easy and natural. The disadvantage is that it's less solid than the lines with ...Be7 and Black will need to know a lot of theory. At the same time, though, it is also more demanding for White.At the moment, the system with ...Bc5 is doing well as there's no clear way for White to get an advantage according to theory, but there are certain lines where I feel that it's possible for White to find new ideas and moves that are unpleasant for Black. So, I'm not sure that the ...Bc5 system is bullet-proof. }
5... b5 6. Bb3 Bb7
{ Speaking about the history of the variation, this was for a long time supposed to be the only way for Black to develop the bishop to c5. This move remains playable, and even Magnus Carlsen has played it. }
7. Re1
{ Now Black should develop the bishop to c5, otherwise his play doesn't make much sense. After  7...Be7  White might even try a direct move like  8.d4  . }
7... Bc5 8. c3 d6 9. d4 Bb6
{ This position is very much like the main line of the ...Bc5 system, apart from the fact that Black has put the c8-bishop on b7 a bit too early. It's not super bad, but as you will see later on, in the ...Bc5 Ruy Lopez Black usually keeps the bishop on c8 longer so that he keeps the possibility of playing ...Bg4, which could force White to 'waste' a move playing h2-h3 at some point. }
10. Be3 O-O 11. Nbd2
{ We will later see a similar line where the bishop is on c8 instead of b7 - again, this bishop is not necessarily so well-placed on b7. }
