5... b5 6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move started gaining popularity in the beginning of the 90s. What happened is that players realized a certain forcing variation -  7.c3  d6  8.d4  Bb6  9.dxe5  - which was considered to be losing a pawn, is not actually bad for Black at all. Let's take a look at that line. }
7. c3 d6 8. d4 Bb6 9. a4
{ Here Black can at the very least transpose to the two mainlines @@StartBracket@@which we will examine later@@EndBracket@@ by playing either  9...Rb8  or  9...Bb7  , but I think  9...Bg4  is already perfectly fine. }
9... Bg4
{ This is why, if you want to play a2-a4 as White, you should rather do it on move 7 instead. Then Black hasn't played ...d6 yet and thus doesn't have the option of playing ...Bg4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 21: Spanish 5... b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 and 5... Bc5"]
[Black "Spanish 5... b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 - lines with Nxe5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O
{ In this Lesson we'll consider all of Black's systems after  5.O-O  where Black develops the bishop to c5. There are different move orders Black can use to achieve this, but the most popular one is  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  .  On c5 the bishop is, of course, more active than on e7, putting some pressure on White's center @@StartBracket@@after White continues with c3 and d4, as he usually does@@EndBracket@@, so it makes sense to develop the bishop to the a7-g1 diagonal, especially if Black is going to choose a setup with ...d6 anyway.The drawback of developing the bishop to c5 is that Black will lose time, e.g. after White plays c3 and d4, forcing Black to move the bishop from c5. The question is whether Black is in time to develop normally - ...d6, ...O-O and so on. If he can achieve normal development, then Black essentially has an improved version of the 'standard' Ruy Lopez where the bishop is on e7 instead.One of the advantages of this system is that Black's play is easy and natural. The disadvantage is that it's less solid than the lines with ...Be7 and Black will need to know a lot of theory. At the same time, though, it is also more demanding for White.At the moment, the system with ...Bc5 is doing well as there's no clear way for White to get an advantage according to theory, but there are certain lines where I feel that it's possible for White to find new ideas and moves that are unpleasant for Black. So, I'm not sure that the ...Bc5 system is bullet-proof. }
5... b5 6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move started gaining popularity in the beginning of the 90s. What happened is that players realized a certain forcing variation -  7.c3  d6  8.d4  Bb6  9.dxe5  - which was considered to be losing a pawn, is not actually bad for Black at all. Let's take a look at that line. }
7. a4
{ The main move, forcing Black to make up his mind what he is going to do with the b5-pawn: either defend it with ...Rb8 or neutralize the pin on the a-file with ...Bb7.  7...Rb8  is the main move, but  7...Bb7  is not at all bad either. }
7... b4 { This is not good for a tactical reason. } 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. d4
{ We will see this motif multiple times, but in this particular version of Nxe5, White gets a better position. }
9... Bxd4 10. Qxd4 d6
{ Without the moves a4 and ...b4 inserted Black is supposed to be fine, but here the pawn is hanging on b4. }
11. Qxb4
{ White is better. This is why after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2pp1ppp/p1n2n2/1pb1p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.a4  Black's choice is just between  7...Bb7  and  7...Rb8  . }
