5... b5 6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move started gaining popularity in the beginning of the 90s. What happened is that players realized a certain forcing variation -  7.c3  d6  8.d4  Bb6  9.dxe5  - which was considered to be losing a pawn, is not actually bad for Black at all. Let's take a look at that line. }
7. a4
{ The main move, forcing Black to make up his mind what he is going to do with the b5-pawn: either defend it with ...Rb8 or neutralize the pin on the a-file with ...Bb7.  7...Rb8  is the main move, but  7...Bb7  is not at all bad either. }
7... Bb7
{ This is not bad, but it does give White a decent choice. Now  8.Nxe5  Nxe5  9.d4  is probably not special for White - in the position after  9...Bxd4  10.Qxd4  d6  ,  the bishop on b7 is not necessarily worse than the rook would have been on b8. I don't think this is dangerous for Black.   However,  8.d3  and  8.c3  are both quite threatening to Black.  8.d3  is a more quiet positional way of playing, while  8.c3  is very direct and sharp. }
8. c3
{ The most direct approach. Sorry for repeating myself over and over, but in many such Ruy Lopez variations you need a powerful engine to understand what is going on, as the game becomes very direct. This variation is no exception. }
8... d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. Bg5
{ White has this extra option because the bishop is on b7. This move was considered quite annoying back in the 90s, when computers were much weaker or even non-existing. }
10... h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Bd5
{ This is the idea of 10. Bg5. The pin is quite unpleasant for Black. } 12...
O-O 13. Na3 exd4 14. cxd4 Rfb8
{ Or  14...Ra7  is also played. It doesn't look convincing for Black, but computers cannot find anything special for White and Black is close to equalizing. Next Black will move the knight somewhere, exchange light-squared bishops, and then play ... bxa4 just to secure the bishop on b6. His pawn structure will be slightly compromised, but it seems to equalize. }
