{ The most direct approach. Sorry for repeating myself over and over, but in many such Ruy Lopez variations you need a powerful engine to understand what is going on, as the game becomes very direct. This variation is no exception. }
8... d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. Re1
{ Perhaps the most dangerous move. Now the question is whether Black should castle @@StartBracket@@which allows Bg5@@EndBracket@@ or play ...h6 first. }
10... O-O
{ Now if White plays slowly with  11.h3  h6  then everything is okay for Black. }
11. Bg5
{ This move is a problem for Black. I analyzed this position some years ago, when engines were less powerful, but the position is so complicated that you need the most up to date engines to get a good understanding of what is happening. }
11... h6 12. Bh4
{ The issue is that Black at some point needs to play ...g5, otherwise it is hard to see how he will get rid of the pin on the f6-knight. But, as Black has already castled, this would significantly weaken the position of Black's king, and allow White a piece sacrifice on g5. }
12... exd4 13. cxd4 g5 14. Nxg5 { The critical move. } 14... hxg5 15. Bxg5
{ There were quite a number of computer games from this position, from 10 years ago. Even those computers were not totally sure what the final outcome of this position is - can Black hold the draw or not? }
15... Nxd4 16. Bd5
{ This is best play according to the engines. You should analyze it yourself with a computer, as it is difficult for me to explain the purpose of such a concrete move. }
16... Ne6 17. Bh4
{ One of White's ideas, very typical for the Ruy Lopez, is to play Ra3 and bring the rook to the kingside that way.If Black can defend this position, if it's holdable, the whole variation with 7... Bb7 is playable for Black. So it's not refuted yet, but nowadays 7... Rb8 is more popular. }
