10. a5
{ This is, perhaps, even more dangerous than  10.Na3  . As Black seems to be doing fine after  10.Na3  , I would recommend White players to pay attention to the move  10.a5  . }
10... Ba7
{ The computer says that  10...Ba7  is practically the only move as  10...Nxa5  doesn't work. Now after  10...Ba7  we get similar play to what we've seen before, except that White has a bit more control over the queenside and Black doesn't have the ...Na5 idea anymore. The only drawback for White is that sometimes the pawn on a5 may turn out to be weak. }
11. Be3
{ White usually plays  11.h3  first, because after  11.Be3  the move  11...Bg4  works out quite well for Black. }
11... Bg4 12. dxe5
{ After  12.Nbd2  Black can already take the pawn on d4. Without the moves a5 and ...Ba7 included, if you remember well, Black should castle instead of taking the d4-pawn. }
12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nxe5 14. Qe2 Bxe3 15. Qxe3 O-O
{ After some captures the position has stabilized, and Black has solved most of his problems. Now after the likely continuation  16.Nd2  Re8  17.Rfd1  Qe7  White is maybe nominally better, as he has a bishop against a knight and slightly more space, but Black has no weaknesses and a healthy position. This is why 11. h3 is the main move instead of 11. Be3. }
