[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O
{ In this Lesson we'll consider all of Black's systems after  5.O-O  where Black develops the bishop to c5. There are different move orders Black can use to achieve this, but the most popular one is  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  .  On c5 the bishop is, of course, more active than on e7, putting some pressure on White's center @@StartBracket@@after White continues with c3 and d4, as he usually does@@EndBracket@@, so it makes sense to develop the bishop to the a7-g1 diagonal, especially if Black is going to choose a setup with ...d6 anyway.The drawback of developing the bishop to c5 is that Black will lose time, e.g. after White plays c3 and d4, forcing Black to move the bishop from c5. The question is whether Black is in time to develop normally - ...d6, ...O-O and so on. If he can achieve normal development, then Black essentially has an improved version of the 'standard' Ruy Lopez where the bishop is on e7 instead.One of the advantages of this system is that Black's play is easy and natural. The disadvantage is that it's less solid than the lines with ...Be7 and Black will need to know a lot of theory. At the same time, though, it is also more demanding for White.At the moment, the system with ...Bc5 is doing well as there's no clear way for White to get an advantage according to theory, but there are certain lines where I feel that it's possible for White to find new ideas and moves that are unpleasant for Black. So, I'm not sure that the ...Bc5 system is bullet-proof. }
5... b5 6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move started gaining popularity in the beginning of the 90s. What happened is that players realized a certain forcing variation -  7.c3  d6  8.d4  Bb6  9.dxe5  - which was considered to be losing a pawn, is not actually bad for Black at all. Let's take a look at that line. }
7. a4
{ The main move, forcing Black to make up his mind what he is going to do with the b5-pawn: either defend it with ...Rb8 or neutralize the pin on the a-file with ...Bb7.  7...Rb8  is the main move, but  7...Bb7  is not at all bad either. }
7... Rb8
{ The most popular move, and it's quite logical. The pawn on b5 is protected, and Black retains the flexibility of having the bishop on c8 - it can later go to g4 if necessary. At the top level, 9 games out of 10 with this position continue with 7... Rb8. }
8. c3
{ If White now plays  8.d3  then Black replies  8...d6  and has no problem at all because the c8-bishop is much better placed. Therefore 8. c3 is the only real chance to play for an advantage. }
8... d6 9. d4 Bb6
{ We arrive at a very important position. Now  10.dxe5  doesn't bring much - similarly to what we've seen before, after  10...Nxe5  Black will be in time to regain the pawn. White has tried almost everything in this position already, but - apart from the main moves  10.Na3  and  10.a5  - I don't think there is anything that will trouble you as Black, especially if you study the lines with an engine. }
10. a5
{ This is, perhaps, even more dangerous than  10.Na3  . As Black seems to be doing fine after  10.Na3  , I would recommend White players to pay attention to the move  10.a5  . }
10... Ba7
{ The computer says that  10...Ba7  is practically the only move as  10...Nxa5  doesn't work. Now after  10...Ba7  we get similar play to what we've seen before, except that White has a bit more control over the queenside and Black doesn't have the ...Na5 idea anymore. The only drawback for White is that sometimes the pawn on a5 may turn out to be weak. }
11. h3
{ Quite an important position nowadays. It's not yet clear what Black's best move is here. }
11... O-O
{ This used to be Black's main move, until some new engines came along that were much less materialistic, much more inclined to sacrifice pawns for a long-term initiative. Such engines have changed the assessment of certain variations in different openings, and this line is one concrete example. }
12. Be3
{ One of the ideas of this move is to play dxe5 to exploit the position of the bishop on a7. For instance  12...h6?!  13.dxe5  Bxe3  14.exf6  followed by fxg7. }
12... exd4
{ As mentioned, this move was considered to be fine 10 years ago, until the new engines came along that were less materialistic. }
13. cxd4 Nxe4 14. Qc2 Qe8
{ This is an idea we've seen before - now White cannot grab a piece with  15.Bd5  . }
15. Bd5 Nb4 16. Qxe4 Qxe4 17. Bxe4 f5
{ In this particular case this move is even stronger than  17...d5  , which would also regain the piece. }
*

