[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O
{ In this Lesson we'll consider all of Black's systems after  5.O-O  where Black develops the bishop to c5. There are different move orders Black can use to achieve this, but the most popular one is  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  .  On c5 the bishop is, of course, more active than on e7, putting some pressure on White's center @@StartBracket@@after White continues with c3 and d4, as he usually does@@EndBracket@@, so it makes sense to develop the bishop to the a7-g1 diagonal, especially if Black is going to choose a setup with ...d6 anyway.The drawback of developing the bishop to c5 is that Black will lose time, e.g. after White plays c3 and d4, forcing Black to move the bishop from c5. The question is whether Black is in time to develop normally - ...d6, ...O-O and so on. If he can achieve normal development, then Black essentially has an improved version of the 'standard' Ruy Lopez where the bishop is on e7 instead.One of the advantages of this system is that Black's play is easy and natural. The disadvantage is that it's less solid than the lines with ...Be7 and Black will need to know a lot of theory. At the same time, though, it is also more demanding for White.At the moment, the system with ...Bc5 is doing well as there's no clear way for White to get an advantage according to theory, but there are certain lines where I feel that it's possible for White to find new ideas and moves that are unpleasant for Black. So, I'm not sure that the ...Bc5 system is bullet-proof. }
5... Bc5
{ I wanted to show you this alternate move order that Black can utilize. This way White gets some additional options @@StartBracket@@but according to theory Black is holding there, though not without difficulties@@EndBracket@@, but Black is also able to avoid some important lines that occur after  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  .  This is a sort of sub-variation of the ...Bc5 system, which it can transpose to, but you can also play it as a separate system. }
6. c3 b5
{ This is how Black usually continues in this move order. The advantage for Black is that after  7.Bb3  d6  ,  he has avoided several important lines. If Black intends to continue ...Bb7, he has avoided lines where White plays d3; and if White continues with  8.a4  ,  Black gets additional options.   There is one big disadvantage: White now has the additional option of playing  7.Bc2  . }
7. Bb3
{ If White continues with this move, then, as explained previously, Black has avoided a few important lines and gained some important options compared to the 'normal' move order @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  . }
7... d6 8. a4
{ Here Black can transpose to the ...Bc5 mainlines with either  8...Bb7  or  8...Rb8  , but here he can also play either  8...Bg4  or  8...b4  . }
8... b4
{ This is a very new and computerish way of playing, which I have tried myself. }
9. d4 Ba7
{ 9...Bb6  is really bad, for tactical reasons which you'll have to analyze yourself with an engine. However, there is no clear refutation of  9...Ba7  . I played this move against Nepomniachtchi in Dortmund 2018. At the end of the day, I lost the game, but I had a normal position after the opening.There has not been much development in this variation. I doubt that 8... b4 is objectively sound, but I haven't been able to find a refutation. In any case, the point is that after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p2ppp/p1np1n2/1pb1p3/4P3/1BP2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.a4  you don't necessarily have to transpose to the mainlines with  8...Bb7  or  8...Rb8  . }
