d5
{ If Black is doing fine after this move, then there is no reason to start with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  but it's much more convenient to start with  5...Bc5  instead. However, you need to learn a lot of forcing lines here. To my understanding Black holds, but without a high level of preparation and a good memory you better not enter these lines! }
8. d4
{ The main move. There is also the strange move  8.a4  . You can check the games, as top players such as Caruana have also played this as Black. It leads to a very long forcing line, up to move 30-35, if I remember it correctly.Another line is  8.exd5  Qxd5  9.d4  exd4  10.Re1+  , but it doesn't seem to bring anything to White. }
8... dxe4
{ Now White has a number of options. You just need to check games. The play is extremely direct, so the explanations of the engine will be more useful than what I can say here. You just need to push the button and memorize the variations. }
9. Nbd2 { This looks very strange, but it's actually very dangerous. } 9...
exf3 10. Qxf3 { Now Black has to return the piece. } 10... Be7 11. Qxc6+ Bd7
12. Qf3 exd4 13. Ne4
{ Theory goes on and on, but it seems that Black is just in time to equalize. }
