[White "Lesson 21: Spanish 5... b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 and 5... Bc5"]
[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ In the ...Bc5 Ruy Lopez, like in all Ruy Lopez variations, if you are playing Black, you have a choice: if you don't want to study too many forcing lines and play solid and safe, you usually get a slightly worse position. If you really want to equalize and play principled lines, then you need to study a lot of theory. Of course, this is mainly relevant for professional play. For club level players, just learning the lines I have shown you in this chapter will provide you with enough information to play this variation as either White or Black.The situation in the ...Bc5 Ruy Lopez is quite similar to the Open Ruy Lopez with ...Nxe4. It seems that White doesn't have a clear way to an advantage, but he has a few tries, and I cannot be sure that Black will be doing fine for the next coming 30 years in this variation. White has some options, and the last word hasn't been said yet in all of these direct variations, including @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  .  However, it's an interesting and quite simple line to play. If you do your homework and know that you can hold the balance in every single variation, then it's a quite serious weapon as Black.As White you need to know what you want to do against ...Bc5. The difference with the Berlin is that if you have an interesting novelty as White, you can get a large advantage if your opponent is not well prepared. The importance of preparation is much higher, as the positions are much more tactical.Next, we are going to examine Black's classical way of playing the Ruy Lopez - the variations with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7  .  It's also not easy for White to find an advantage there. We will slowly go through all the serious existing systems for Black @@StartBracket@@ and White's deviations @@EndBracket@@, the main one of which is the Marshall Attack, which will be considered last. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 22: Spanish 5... Be7 - White's Alternatives"]
[Black "Spanish 5... Be7 6. d4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ Now we move to the  5...Be7  variations.  5...Be7  is the most solid and popular move. While nowadays the lines with ...Bc5 are also fashionable, since the beginning of the Ruy Lopez 5... Be7 was by far the most popular move. At that time, the Berlin defense  @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  @@EndBracket@@ was considered to be passive and not leading to equality, so most players as Black played  3...a6  followed by a setup with ... Be7.However, computers have changed how many of these variations are assessed. In general, I think the most reliable line for Black in the Ruy Lopez, and the one which poses White the most problems, is the Marshall, which I will show you in a later lesson.Today I want to show you everything White can try after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7  , apart from the main move  6.Re1  .  This move is very logical, defending the e4-pawn and preparing to play c3 and d4 next, to occupy the center. But as we will see in later lessons, this central occupation cannot always be realized, mainly due to the Marshall.Lately, White, out of desperation as @@StartBracket@@on the top level@@EndBracket@@ the Marshall is doing so well, is trying various alternatives to 6. Re1 to try to get a slightly more comfortable position. These alternatives, the main one of which is 6. d3, will be considered in this lesson. }
6. d4 exd4
{ This is a transposition to a line we've seen in a previous lesson. It's totally harmless. You can find my analysis of this position in the lesson on the Open Spanish. There we considered this position via the move order @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.d4  exd4  and if White now castles  6.O-O  , then  6...Be7  is the best move and we transpose. There is no problem at all for Black, who might even get a slightly better position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 22: Spanish 5... Be7 - White's Alternatives"]
[Black "Spanish 5... Be7 6. Bxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ Now we move to the  5...Be7  variations.  5...Be7  is the most solid and popular move. While nowadays the lines with ...Bc5 are also fashionable, since the beginning of the Ruy Lopez 5... Be7 was by far the most popular move. At that time, the Berlin defense  @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  @@EndBracket@@ was considered to be passive and not leading to equality, so most players as Black played  3...a6  followed by a setup with ... Be7.However, computers have changed how many of these variations are assessed. In general, I think the most reliable line for Black in the Ruy Lopez, and the one which poses White the most problems, is the Marshall, which I will show you in a later lesson.Today I want to show you everything White can try after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7  , apart from the main move  6.Re1  .  This move is very logical, defending the e4-pawn and preparing to play c3 and d4 next, to occupy the center. But as we will see in later lessons, this central occupation cannot always be realized, mainly due to the Marshall.Lately, White, out of desperation as @@StartBracket@@on the top level@@EndBracket@@ the Marshall is doing so well, is trying various alternatives to 6. Re1 to try to get a slightly more comfortable position. These alternatives, the main one of which is 6. d3, will be considered in this lesson. }
6. Bxc6
{ Sometimes White takes on  c6  here. Of course, this looks very strange. A couple of moves ago Black played @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  , and at that point White could have taken  4.Bxc6  immediately @@StartBracket@@we considered this variation in a previous lesson - in my opinion Black is doing fine@@EndBracket@@.Here, too, Black has no problems, but there is a point to 6. Bxc6: now Black's knight is already on f6, which means it becomes a bit more awkward for Black to defend the pawn on e5, as there is no ...f7-f6. }
6... dxc6
{ 6...bxc6  is inferior, as it shuts down the pieces, isolates Black's pawn structure and even allows something like  7.Nxe5  Nxe4  8.d4  when White has the advantage. }
7. d3 { For instance, here Black probably has to play ...Nd7. } 7... Nd7
{ Now the bishop is a bit passive on c8. However, this seems to me to be a better version of the line we discussed in the Berlin 4. d3 lesson, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.Bxc6  dxc6  ,  because the dark-squared bishop is better placed on e7 than on c5. There are some high-level games in this position which you could analyze, but I don't think Black has the slightest problem at all. }
