[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 22: Spanish 5... Be7 - White's Alternatives"]
[Black "Spanish 5... Be7 6. d3 - Berlin Transposition"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ Now we move to the  5...Be7  variations.  5...Be7  is the most solid and popular move. While nowadays the lines with ...Bc5 are also fashionable, since the beginning of the Ruy Lopez 5... Be7 was by far the most popular move. At that time, the Berlin defense  @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  @@EndBracket@@ was considered to be passive and not leading to equality, so most players as Black played  3...a6  followed by a setup with ... Be7.However, computers have changed how many of these variations are assessed. In general, I think the most reliable line for Black in the Ruy Lopez, and the one which poses White the most problems, is the Marshall, which I will show you in a later lesson.Today I want to show you everything White can try after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7  , apart from the main move  6.Re1  .  This move is very logical, defending the e4-pawn and preparing to play c3 and d4 next, to occupy the center. But as we will see in later lessons, this central occupation cannot always be realized, mainly due to the Marshall.Lately, White, out of desperation as @@StartBracket@@on the top level@@EndBracket@@ the Marshall is doing so well, is trying various alternatives to 6. Re1 to try to get a slightly more comfortable position. These alternatives, the main one of which is 6. d3, will be considered in this lesson. }
6. d3
{ This move has become more popular over the last years. Frankly, I don't think it's very dangerous. I've played it myself a few years ago, in particular the system with d3, a3 and Nc3. This system started becoming popular maybe 10 years ago.The situation after 6. d3 is strange because Black has a lot of options, and it seems that in almost every single line Black is very close to equalizing, but never fully. I always felt that it doesn't matter too much which variation Black chooses to play against 6. d3.But, at the same time, you do need to make a choice, and you need to be sure that you know how to play that line; you need to analyze your chosen approach deeply. Whichever approach Black chooses, White always seems to keep a little bit of pressure, a tiny plus. It's almost nothing, but still there is no way yet to kill the 6. d3 variation completely. It's not dead yet. And one top player who is scoring very well with the seemingly harmless 6. d3 is Nepomniachtchi.   After  6.d3  the pawn on e5 is hanging, so Black has to play either  6...b5  or  6...d6  . }
6... d6
{ This is the main alternative to  6...b5  . However, now we will soon transpose to a line covered in an earlier lesson. }
7. c3 O-O 8. Re1
{ If you remember well, we now have transposed to a position that can also occur via a Berlin move order: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  d6  5.O-O  Be7  6.c3  O-O  7.Re1  and here Black's best is to anyway play  7...a6  , when White replies  8.Ba4  and we get the same position. This variation is discussed in the Lesson on the Berlin with d3.I can repeat a bit from that Lesson: I think this position is not a clear-cut equality. It is definitely playable for White, even though with very precise play Black should manage to get a good game.It's possible for Black to play in a typical Ruy Lopez fashion with  8...Re8  9.Nbd2  Bf8  10.h3  h6  , but this is a bit slow. Black's plan, of course, is that if White plays  11.Nf1  , to then strike with  11...b5  12.Bc2  d5  .  That might be good enough to equalize.However, White has an interesting try in  @@StartFEN@@r1bqrbk1/1pp2pp1/p1np1n1p/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N1P/PP1N1PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.d4  b5  12.Bc2  .  A typical Ruy Lopez position then arises, which resembles the Zaitsev Variation which we'll study in lesson 23. It's playable for White, but I'm not sure if he's better. In general, I think that if White manages to occupy the center  @@StartBracket@@d4/e4@@EndBracket@@ in the Ruy Lopez, even if it's not enough to get an advantage, it at least means he'll get an interesting, playable game.Instead, Black can also continue  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1bppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...b5  9.Bc2  d5  . The point is that  10.exd5  Qxd5  seems to be okay for Black. There is also the move @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/2p1bppp/p1n2n2/1p1pp3/4P3/2PP1N2/PPB2PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.d4  which is interesting and needs to be investigated. The mainline, however, continues with  10.Nbd2  . Here Black could play  10...d4  11.h3  Nd7  ,  and this is not doing bad statistically speaking, but I don't like this way of playing. This pawn structure often gives White an intiative in the center and on the kingside.More popular is to take  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/2p1bppp/p1n2n2/1p1pp3/4P3/2PP1N2/PPBN1PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...dxe4  11.dxe4  Be6  , and after  12.Qe2  one of White's ideas is to play a2-a4 to probe Black's pawn on b5. Some 10 years ago many games were played in this variation - Aronian played this a lot, for example. I think Black is close to equalizing, but not completely yet. Somehow White has a slightly more comfortable game. For instance,  12...Nd7  13.Rd1  and here  13...Qc8  is possible but  13...Qb8  looks logical. White then plays  14.Bb3  ,  trying to exchange the bishops and then put a knight on the d5-square. All in all, the position is not very special for White, but it's also not dead equal. }
