[White "Lesson 22: Spanish 5... Be7 - White's Alternatives"]
[Black "Spanish 5... Be7 6. d3, 8. a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ Now we move to the  5...Be7  variations.  5...Be7  is the most solid and popular move. While nowadays the lines with ...Bc5 are also fashionable, since the beginning of the Ruy Lopez 5... Be7 was by far the most popular move. At that time, the Berlin defense  @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  @@EndBracket@@ was considered to be passive and not leading to equality, so most players as Black played  3...a6  followed by a setup with ... Be7.However, computers have changed how many of these variations are assessed. In general, I think the most reliable line for Black in the Ruy Lopez, and the one which poses White the most problems, is the Marshall, which I will show you in a later lesson.Today I want to show you everything White can try after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7  , apart from the main move  6.Re1  .  This move is very logical, defending the e4-pawn and preparing to play c3 and d4 next, to occupy the center. But as we will see in later lessons, this central occupation cannot always be realized, mainly due to the Marshall.Lately, White, out of desperation as @@StartBracket@@on the top level@@EndBracket@@ the Marshall is doing so well, is trying various alternatives to 6. Re1 to try to get a slightly more comfortable position. These alternatives, the main one of which is 6. d3, will be considered in this lesson. }
6. d3
{ This move has become more popular over the last years. Frankly, I don't think it's very dangerous. I've played it myself a few years ago, in particular the system with d3, a3 and Nc3. This system started becoming popular maybe 10 years ago.The situation after 6. d3 is strange because Black has a lot of options, and it seems that in almost every single line Black is very close to equalizing, but never fully. I always felt that it doesn't matter too much which variation Black chooses to play against 6. d3.But, at the same time, you do need to make a choice, and you need to be sure that you know how to play that line; you need to analyze your chosen approach deeply. Whichever approach Black chooses, White always seems to keep a little bit of pressure, a tiny plus. It's almost nothing, but still there is no way yet to kill the 6. d3 variation completely. It's not dead yet. And one top player who is scoring very well with the seemingly harmless 6. d3 is Nepomniachtchi.   After  6.d3  the pawn on e5 is hanging, so Black has to play either  6...b5  or  6...d6  . }
6... b5
{ A very principled reply. One of the ideas is that Black is trying to win a tempo, in case White eventually wants to play c3 and retreat the bishop to c2. For instance, in the line  6...d6  7.c3  ,  if Black at some point plays ...b5, White always retreats the bishop to c2 immediately instead of first putting it on b3.   Meanwhile in the current line after  6...b5  , if the game continues  7.Bb3  d6  , after  8.c3  Black can continue with ...Na5 and ...c5, and this isn't as dangerous for Black as when White could retreat the bishop to c2 in one go. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ Here it's hard to say whether Black should castle first  7...O-O  and later play ...d6, or first play  7...d6  and then castle. For the main system that White has, 8. a3 followed by 9. Nc3, Black's move order doesn't really matter. Nor does it matter in the variation with 8. c3 and 9. Re1.Perhaps the only way for White to make use of the move order  7...O-O  is to play  8.a4  , but after both  8...b4  and  8...Bb7  it isn't really possible for White to manage without the move Re1, which would transpose to lesson 25 on the Anti-Marshall. Sooner or later he will anyway have to play this move, because otherwise Black can get in the move ...d5 too easily. So whether to start with 7... O-O or 7... d6 is a matter of taste. }
8. a4
{ In this case, I'm not sure whether  8...Bb7  is good enough, because maybe White can make use of the fact that his rook is not yet on e1 by playing, for instance,  9.Nc3  . That might be a bit tricky for Black. }
8... b4
{ This move is the main problem for White after 8. a4, as I understand it. } 9.
a5 O-O
{ We'll consider the position in more detail in Lesson 25, but suffice to say that Black is very solid and completely fine. }
