11. Nh4 { The most principled move, which looks very strange. } 11... Bxa2
{ The position after  11...O-O  12.Nf5  becomes very concrete, and it seems that it's not so easy for Black to equalize. }
12. Rxa2 Nxe4
{ Black can grab a pawn this way, but there is a tactical justification of White's play. }
13. dxe4 Bxh4 14. Nd5
{ Followed by Qg4. It seems that White has very powerful compensation for the pawn. There have not been that not many games with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p1bppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/4P3/PB1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Na5  , though. Usually Black just castles, either  8...O-O  or even a move earlier. }
