12... Nd7 { This is the old mainline here. Black is threatening ...Ne5. } 13.
h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 c6
{ Tomashevsky has played a lot of games here, so if you want to study this variation you can start with his games. You do need to know what you're doing as Black, because White keeps a little bit of pressure even though it's close to equality. }
15. Nf4
{ I saw that Caruana played this move, keeping the knight on the board. The plan could be g4, Qg3, Ne2 and f4. Of course, strategically Black's position is a bit dangerous as White's bishop is very strong, being unopposed. Black's bishop is definitely much more passive. As in many other lines in this system, it's close to equal according to the computer, but in a practical game it's perhaps not so easy.Maybe 9... Bg4 is equalizing, but it's a bit more pleasant for White to play, and in general when I studied this variation I was quite happy to be White - there is no forced draw and I can still press. So as Black I wouldn't play 9... Bg4, not because it's bad, but because I think there are other variations which are perhaps easier to play and which also lead to equality. }
