{ Here, again,  11...Nc6  12.Nd5  is already quite unpleasant for Black. } 12.
Rxa2 Nc6 13. Bg5
{ It's hard for me to believe that White has anything in the position, but the statistics are somewhat in White's favor. So, apparently it's not that easy. Even the current engines show a tiny plus for White.But again, I'm quite sure that if you spend some time analyzing this position, you'll find some way for Black to equalize. Even Ding Liren has lost a couple of games from this position, though. So it's a position to further investigate for both colors, whether you want to play it as White or as Black. }
13... Ng4
{ If Black plays like this, trying to exchange bishops, then White just retreats to d2. }
14. Bd2 Nf6 15. Re1 { White is very slowly improving the position. } 15... Qd7
16. Nd5
{ White now intends to continue with a4 and c4, getting play on the queenside. For instance  16...Nxd5  17.exd5  Na7  18.a4  .  Vachier-Lagrave played a few games in this line. It looks very close to equal, but perhaps White still has some pressure. }
