[White "Lesson 22: Spanish 5... Be7 - White's Alternatives"]
[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ To sum up, in the @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p1bppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.a3  variation there are some small problems to solve for Black. In the end, though, it shouldn't prove to be anything special for White. As I've mentioned, as Black you had better choose one @@StartBracket@@or two@@EndBracket@@ of Black's many possible replies and analyze it thoroughly. You have quite a large choice; there seem to be many ways to get a position that is close to equal.For White, the 8. a3 variation is a good weapon to have in your repertoire. If you play it all the time, your opponents will find some ways to equality in one of these lines. However, it's good to play this variation from time to time, as it's quite simple, there are not too many lines to learn, and there is no 100% bulletproof way for Black to equalize.That concludes our investigation of the sideline  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pppbppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d3  , which has become quite popular in recent years. Now we move on to the main move  6.Re1  .  First, in the next lesson, I will show you first all those old-fashioned variations where Black plays ...d6, and then in lesson 24 I will cover the Marshall where Black castles and sacrifices a pawn with ...d5. In the final lesson we will consider all attempts for White to avoid the Marshall. So after  6.Re1  b5  7.Bb3  O-O  , instead of playing  8.c3  d5  , White can also try @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.a4  or  8.d4  .  In my opinion the Marshall is the most reliable weapon for Black against the Ruy Lopez. Black really has no problems there, but the lines with  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1BP2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...d6  are also okay. d6 is a move for someone who wants to get a typical game in the Ruy Lopez without having to memorize too many forced lines. Sometimes a player doesn't play an opening based on the objective assessment, but because it will lead to interesting, playable positions. }
