1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1
{ In the previouschapter, we looked at the  6.d3  line. Now, let's move to the main and most ambitious continuation:  6.Re1  .  With this move, White defends the e4-pawn in order to be able to get in c3-d4.It is a very logical and most ambitious plan. As we have seen in the previous chapter, when White plays more slowly with  6.d3  ,  White can't objectively count on achieving any real advantage @@StartBracket@@even though things are not so easy for Black from a practical perspective@@EndBracket@@. Even so,  6.Re1  is a more ambitious way of playing. If White manages to get in c3-d4, the position will be favourable @@StartBracket@@even though the situation is much more complicated, as you will see in this lesson@@EndBracket@@. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 d6
{ One of the reasons why many players who aim for d6-setups with Black start with 7...d6 is the existence of the anti-Marshall line with 8.a4, as mentioned above. However, here this move is considered not to be that dangerous. }
8. a4 { However, even here, this is a valid move. } 8... Bg4
{ This is the difference compared to setups with 7... O-O @@StartBracket@@there, this bishop move was not possible@@EndBracket@@. However, I wouldn't say that this developing move leads to a simple equality. If you are playing Black in this variation, it is a matter of choice whether you want to start with castling or not. It has to be mentioned that in the given line, there is less theory compared to the analogous line arising after 7...d6 8.a4. }
9. c3
{ This is still very much playable for White. I am not sure if White can count on any real advantage, but it will definitely be a game. }
9... O-O 10. h3
{ Is not critical, as - strangely enough - Black can just give up the bishop. }
10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3
{ In general, giving up two bishops is not a great idea in the Ruy Lopez, but here White has already pushed the pawn to a4 which gives Black certain strategic ideas. }
11... Na5 12. Bc2 { Black can also play } 12... b4
{ and then follow it up with Rb8 eventually, which might fully compensate for the absence of the two bishops. It is true that here White can get in the desired advance of the d-pawn: }
13. d4 { but here Black can calmly retreat the knight. } 13... Nd7
{ And now  14.cxb4  is always met with  14...Nc6  when Black regains the pawn. Otherwise, Black wants to play Rb8, maybe even get Bg5 to exchange the dark-squared bishops and the knight on a5 is a pretty good piece. }
