1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1
{ In the previouschapter, we looked at the  6.d3  line. Now, let's move to the main and most ambitious continuation:  6.Re1  .  With this move, White defends the e4-pawn in order to be able to get in c3-d4.It is a very logical and most ambitious plan. As we have seen in the previous chapter, when White plays more slowly with  6.d3  ,  White can't objectively count on achieving any real advantage @@StartBracket@@even though things are not so easy for Black from a practical perspective@@EndBracket@@. Even so,  6.Re1  is a more ambitious way of playing. If White manages to get in c3-d4, the position will be favourable @@StartBracket@@even though the situation is much more complicated, as you will see in this lesson@@EndBracket@@. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 d6
{ First, I would like to start considering all the lines where Black moves the pawn to d6. Only in the next lesson will we give more attention to Black playing  7...O-O  ,  aiming for the infamous Marshall Gambit/Attack. These days, the latter approach @@StartBracket@@involving the d5 push@@EndBracket@@ is much more popular because it is much harder for White to prove an advantage in the mainlines @@StartBracket@@which is one of the reasons why White often deviates with  8.a4  or  8.h3  @@EndBracket@@.However, it is a matter of choice, and quite many Black players who play the Ruy Lopez want to play a very solid, positional game and don't necessarily want to learn all the forced variations that can arise from the Marshall. Therefore, if you are playing the White side of this opening, you need to be ready for both of these systems. }
8. c3 { This is the main line. } 8... O-O { Now White has a choice. } 9. d4
{ This was considered to be harmless some 20-30 years ago, but nowadays it is becoming more and more popular as things are not at all so easy for Black. I still believe it is not the most dangerous one if Black knows what to do against it, but it is more serious than it was initially thought. }
9... Bg4
{ Of course, this is why 9. h3 is the main move here - in the mainlines, White wants to prevent this intrusion by the bishop. Now Black immediately puts pressure on the center. }
10. Be3 { Definitely the best move in this position - defending the d4-pawn. }
10... exd4 { By far the main move in the position. } 11. cxd4 Na5
{ The most logical move in the position and the old mainline. } 12. Bc2
{ The most logical. Now Black has two options. } 12... c5
{ This was considered to be the simplest move to equalize. This is still probably a good move, but it turned out that the situation is much more complicated than it was initially thought @@StartBracket@@some 30 years ago@@EndBracket@@. }
13. h3
{ It is very important to include this move.  13.dxc5  was considered to be the main line. After  13...dxc5  there is quite some theory, but Black should be fine in the resulting position. }
13... cxd4
{ I recommend you to insert this intermediate move and take on d4 instead of retreating the bishop in this position. }
14. Bxd4 Bxf3 { Taking on f3 is wrong. } 15. Qxf3 Rc8
{ This position was considered to be completely equal, but computers have changed the evaluation of this position. }
16. Qd1 Nc6 17. Nc3
{ And the engines point out that White has the advantage here. Even if the position can be defended, there is no denying that Black is clearly worse and I again don't recommend you to go for it as Black, as you will be very passive and have zero winning chances. }
