[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1
{ In the previouschapter, we looked at the  6.d3  line. Now, let's move to the main and most ambitious continuation:  6.Re1  .  With this move, White defends the e4-pawn in order to be able to get in c3-d4.It is a very logical and most ambitious plan. As we have seen in the previous chapter, when White plays more slowly with  6.d3  ,  White can't objectively count on achieving any real advantage @@StartBracket@@even though things are not so easy for Black from a practical perspective@@EndBracket@@. Even so,  6.Re1  is a more ambitious way of playing. If White manages to get in c3-d4, the position will be favourable @@StartBracket@@even though the situation is much more complicated, as you will see in this lesson@@EndBracket@@. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 d6
{ First, I would like to start considering all the lines where Black moves the pawn to d6. Only in the next lesson will we give more attention to Black playing  7...O-O  ,  aiming for the infamous Marshall Gambit/Attack. These days, the latter approach @@StartBracket@@involving the d5 push@@EndBracket@@ is much more popular because it is much harder for White to prove an advantage in the mainlines @@StartBracket@@which is one of the reasons why White often deviates with  8.a4  or  8.h3  @@EndBracket@@.However, it is a matter of choice, and quite many Black players who play the Ruy Lopez want to play a very solid, positional game and don't necessarily want to learn all the forced variations that can arise from the Marshall. Therefore, if you are playing the White side of this opening, you need to be ready for both of these systems. }
8. c3 { This is the main line. } 8... O-O { Now White has a choice. } 9. h3
{ This is by far the most popular move and the main line of the entire variation. White prevents Bg4. In my opinion, this is much more dangerous than playing for d4 immediately. }
9... Na5
{ In the 60s, 70s and 80s, the so-called Chigorin variation, starting with the move Na5, was very popular. Karpov, in particular, was very successful from the White side, winning many classic games. }
10. Bc2 c5 11. d4
{ I believe @@StartBracket@@and computers confirm this assessment@@EndBracket@@that Black doesn't have full equality here. Of course, there are many different systems, but none of them - in my opinion - equalize. That doesn't mean that they aren't playable - in fact, a number of top players employ them from time to time. But even so, I would be very happy to play this as White in every game. Nowadays, it is very difficult to gain anything out of the opening and in this line, White has significant chances of obtaining an actual opening advantage. }
11... Nd7
{ This is another system which gained some popularity, but it is very dangerous for Black. }
12. Nbd2
{ This is good enough for White. Here Black has to study some dangerous lines and it is hard to say whether it works out or not in the end. They are definitely not to my taste. }
12... exd4 13. cxd4 Nc6
{ Black's idea is to place a knight on e5 after White plays d5. } 14. d5
{ This is really dangerous for Black and a highly critical move for this variation. }
14... Nce5 15. Nxe5
{ The most logical and main move. The other knight move is examined in a separate variation. It is also interesting to try to play with 15.a4 first. }
15... Nxe5 16. a4 Bd7 { This seems to be the best move according to engines. }
17. f4 { This line is extremely dangerous for Black. } 17... Ng6 18. Nf3
{ White is ready to push in the center with f5 and e5. The only justification of Black's opening is the surprising 18th move. }
18... Bh4
{ Of course, this is quite tricky for White to handle and against not-so-well prepared opponent this might work for Black, but objectively it is very dangerous. }
19. Re2 { Probably more convincing than the other rook move. } 19... Bg3
{ Otherwise there is no point in playing Bh4. } 20. e5
{ And this seems very dangerous for Black. I will show you the main computer line so you can see for yourselves. }
20... f5 21. e6 Be8 22. Ng5 Qe7 23. Qf1
{ Now it looks like it is time for Black to resign because everything is hanging, Qf3 is coming, etc. But all of a sudden there is a surprising reply. }
23... bxa4 24. Ra3 Bh4
{ And maybe the position is not so clear. However, it is certainly not to everyone's taste to have the pawn on e6 and also there are deviations along the way that Black needs to take into account.All in all, my impression is that with good analysis and preparation, White will find the way how to be better against 11... Nd7. }
