{ In the 60s, 70s and 80s, the so-called Chigorin variation, starting with the move Na5, was very popular. Karpov, in particular, was very successful from the White side, winning many classic games. }
10. Bc2 c5 11. d4
{ I believe @@StartBracket@@and computers confirm this assessment@@EndBracket@@that Black doesn't have full equality here. Of course, there are many different systems, but none of them - in my opinion - equalize. That doesn't mean that they aren't playable - in fact, a number of top players employ them from time to time. But even so, I would be very happy to play this as White in every game. Nowadays, it is very difficult to gain anything out of the opening and in this line, White has significant chances of obtaining an actual opening advantage. }
11... Qc7 { This is the main move in the position. } 12. Nbd2
{ The main line for White is tried and tested way of posing problems to Black. Black has tried many different ways of playing and they are all playable, but in every line the statistic is heavily in White's favour. }
12... cxd4
{ This is probably the best line for Black, but still White has many different options and the overall situation is quite promising for the first player. }
13. cxd4 Nc6 14. Nb3 { The main line of the variation. } 14... a5
{ The idea behind Black's setup. } 15. Be3 a4 16. Nbd2 Bd7 17. Rc1 Qb7
{ A lot of games were played in this position. Among others, I played this against Michael Adams in Sofia in 2005. This line is playable for Black and if you want to play the Chigorin, you should probably go for it. But still, White has a big range of different possibilities and is in general, slightly better in a number of variations. }
18. Nf1
{ This seems to be very logical, direct and straightforward. White executes a typical Ruy Lopez maneuver and tries to get the knight to g3. }
18... Rfc8 19. Ng3 { Very logical and healthy play. } 19... Bd8 20. Qe2 g6
{ 20...exd4  21.Nxd4  very often doesn't fully equalize. } 21. Bb1
{ I think this is slightly better for White, even though you can check the games of Michael Adams who used to play this regularly as Black and had pretty good results. Still, nowadays the engine are showing quite stable advantage for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 23: Spanish Mainline - Systems with ...d6"]
[Black "Classical Spanish - 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1
{ In the previouschapter, we looked at the  6.d3  line. Now, let's move to the main and most ambitious continuation:  6.Re1  .  With this move, White defends the e4-pawn in order to be able to get in c3-d4.It is a very logical and most ambitious plan. As we have seen in the previous chapter, when White plays more slowly with  6.d3  ,  White can't objectively count on achieving any real advantage @@StartBracket@@even though things are not so easy for Black from a practical perspective@@EndBracket@@. Even so,  6.Re1  is a more ambitious way of playing. If White manages to get in c3-d4, the position will be favourable @@StartBracket@@even though the situation is much more complicated, as you will see in this lesson@@EndBracket@@. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 d6
{ First, I would like to start considering all the lines where Black moves the pawn to d6. Only in the next lesson will we give more attention to Black playing  7...O-O  ,  aiming for the infamous Marshall Gambit/Attack. These days, the latter approach @@StartBracket@@involving the d5 push@@EndBracket@@ is much more popular because it is much harder for White to prove an advantage in the mainlines @@StartBracket@@which is one of the reasons why White often deviates with  8.a4  or  8.h3  @@EndBracket@@.However, it is a matter of choice, and quite many Black players who play the Ruy Lopez want to play a very solid, positional game and don't necessarily want to learn all the forced variations that can arise from the Marshall. Therefore, if you are playing the White side of this opening, you need to be ready for both of these systems. }
8. c3 { This is the main line. } 8... O-O { Now White has a choice. } 9. h3
{ This is by far the most popular move and the main line of the entire variation. White prevents Bg4. In my opinion, this is much more dangerous than playing for d4 immediately. }
9... Nb8
{ This is the so-called Breyer system. It is definitely playable @@StartBracket@@I have played it myself @@EndBracket@@, but nowadays, I would be happy to face it with White. }
10. d4 Nbd7
{ This is a very logical and solid way of playing for Black. However, one day I was studying it and comparing it with Pirc @@StartBracket@@ which is a playable opening, but objectively somewhat worse for Black @@EndBracket@@. I started wondering why exactly would this system be any different from the Pirc.If we look purely from the viewpoint of chess principles, Black's system is not logical, as they have undeveloped the knight and spent two tempi to place it on a passive d7-square. Therefore, I don't believe this system equalizes fully, even though it is playable - particularly at the club level and amateur level. }
11. c4
{ In fact, this is a very dangerous line. It is not that popular nowadays, but I am not sure what is the reason. When I was looking at the Breyer from the Black side, I was always quite worried about it. White wants to put the knight on c3, bishop on e3 and pawn on a3 - very healthy play. }
11... c6 { Now, the question is - how exactly does White achieve it. } 12. a3
{ Provides Black with a tactical opportunity. } 12... bxc4 13. Bxc4 Nxe4
{ Which actually works for Black. } 14. Rxe4
{ 14.dxe5  d5  15.Ba2  seems to work for Black, but needs to be checked as well. }
14... d5 15. Nxe5
{ White sacrifices an exchange and gains sufficient compensation, but probably not more than that. }
15... dxe4 16. Nxc6 Qe8 { And this is probably not that dangerous for Black. }
*

