6... b5 7. Bb3 d6
{ First, I would like to start considering all the lines where Black moves the pawn to d6. Only in the next lesson will we give more attention to Black playing  7...O-O  ,  aiming for the infamous Marshall Gambit/Attack. These days, the latter approach @@StartBracket@@involving the d5 push@@EndBracket@@ is much more popular because it is much harder for White to prove an advantage in the mainlines @@StartBracket@@which is one of the reasons why White often deviates with  8.a4  or  8.h3  @@EndBracket@@.However, it is a matter of choice, and quite many Black players who play the Ruy Lopez want to play a very solid, positional game and don't necessarily want to learn all the forced variations that can arise from the Marshall. Therefore, if you are playing the White side of this opening, you need to be ready for both of these systems. }
8. c3 { This is the main line. } 8... O-O { Now White has a choice. } 9. h3
{ This is by far the most popular move and the main line of the entire variation. White prevents Bg4. In my opinion, this is much more dangerous than playing for d4 immediately. }
9... Nb8
{ This is the so-called Breyer system. It is definitely playable @@StartBracket@@I have played it myself @@EndBracket@@, but nowadays, I would be happy to face it with White. }
10. d4 Nbd7
{ This is a very logical and solid way of playing for Black. However, one day I was studying it and comparing it with Pirc @@StartBracket@@ which is a playable opening, but objectively somewhat worse for Black @@EndBracket@@. I started wondering why exactly would this system be any different from the Pirc.If we look purely from the viewpoint of chess principles, Black's system is not logical, as they have undeveloped the knight and spent two tempi to place it on a passive d7-square. Therefore, I don't believe this system equalizes fully, even though it is playable - particularly at the club level and amateur level. }
11. Nbd2
{ This move I consider to be good enough for White. Probably this is the reason why most White players don't bother analyzing  11.c4  . }
11... Bb7 12. Bc2
{ The main difference compared with the Zaitsev system, which we will consider next, is White's ability to place the knight to g3 @@StartBracket@@which is not the case in Zaitsev@@EndBracket@@, which makes a big difference. }
12... Re8 13. Nf1
{ The drawback of the Breyer system. I remember when I was 7, my trainer told me that White should place the knight on g3 in the Ruy Lopez whenever White gets a chance. Since it is such an important maneuver, I would definitely be inclined toward executing it with White here. }
13... Bf8 14. Ng3 g6
{ Here, there is a lot of theory and many games were played from this position. }
15. Bg5
{ White can always play something slower, such as  15.b3  ,  but this move, is considered to be the most dangerous. I actually dropped Breyer myself because of this variation. }
15... h6
{ Black probably has to play this, because  15...Bg7  16.Qd2  is very annoying as White might have some attacking possibilities. }
16. Bd2
{ White can't retreat to  e3  because after  16.Be3  exd4  the pawn on e4 is hanging. }
16... Bg7 { The most common move. } 17. a4
{ In case of  17.Qc1  Kh7  simply protects the pawn, but I didn't like Black's position here. White has the center and very harmonious setup, but the additional problem is revealed in the continuation of the line. }
17... c5
{ Maybe  17...Nb6  is a better move. It is probably playable, but I don't believe Black can be equal when White has the center and harmonious pieces. }
18. d5 c4
{ Black is hoping to get the knight to c5, but White is able to prevent it. }
19. b4 cxb3 20. Bxb3
{ Now the pawn on c3 is defended. It seems that statistics are overwhelmingly in White's favor as Black is not in time to block the flank. }
20... Nc5 21. c4
{ 21.Bc2  is also very good enough. White scored around 70% from this position and in my opinion, it is not to be recommended to Black. All in all, the Breyer system is by no means refuted and depending on the level of play - you can have it in your repertoire. But against strong players and very top grandmasters who are well-prepared and who know all these details and typical ideas - it is probably not the best choice. }
