8. c3 { This is the main line. } 8... O-O { Now White has a choice. } 9. h3
{ This is by far the most popular move and the main line of the entire variation. White prevents Bg4. In my opinion, this is much more dangerous than playing for d4 immediately. }
9... Nd7 { This variation is a little strange, but quite playable. } 10. d4 Bf6
{ It doesn't look great, but it is not so bad. It was played by Karpov in one of the matches against Garry Kasparov @@StartBracket@@in 1990@@EndBracket@@ - and he obtained some good positions. Black's idea is to prevent the knight from coming to d2 by pressuring the d4-pawn. }
11. a4 { Probably the most dangerous move. } 11... Bb7 12. Na3
{ If I recall correctly, this is what ultimately Garry ended up playing and he won one or two games in this line. Since then, life seems to be difficult for Black in this variation and I somehow don't fully believe in it, but feel free to investigate it on your own. }
*

