exd4 { Black is almost forced to go into the following sharp line. } 14. cxd4
Nb4 15. Bb1 c5
{ This is a very interesting, sharp position that was discussed extensively in Kasparov - Karpov encounters @@StartBracket@@in more than one match@@EndBracket@@ and the results were pretty disastrous for Karpov.However, it may be a matter of taste. The position is very sharp and double-edged and all three results are possible. If you play it with either color, you need to be well-prepared as there is no final verdict - things are too complicated even for the most powerful engines as there are too many options for both sides. }
16. d5 { White has to play this. } 16... Nd7 17. Ra3
{ The main move and a very typical maneuver in this position. White wants to include the rook via the 3rd rank @@StartBracket@@after moving the knight to h2 potentially@@EndBracket@@ and start the attack on the kingside. It is very logical to do so, considering that all White's pieces are looking at the Black king and considering that Black's bishop on b7 and knight on b4 are far away from the king, creating counterplay on the other side of the board.   17.Nf1  is met with  17...f5  . }
17... f5
{ I don't think that this move, which was Karpov's main choice, is refuted by any means. I suspect most top players have analyzed it and concluded it is in White's favor, but according to the theory, there is no clear refutation. }
18. Nh2
{ White has a wide choice. This move, clearing the 3rd rank for the rook makes a lot of sense.  18.exf5  and  18.Rae3  were both played by Kasparov in the match and nowadays, even  18.g4  is played. }
18... Qe7
{ I will give you just one possible line in this crazy variation, just to get the feeling how the game might continue. This move is played very often in computer games. }
19. g4
{ White is starting a direct attack, but Black's pieces are also quite harmonious. }
19... fxe4 20. Nxe4 Qf7 21. g5 Qxd5 22. Bd2 Ne5
{ And the position is extremely sharp and complicated. In computer games, statistics are equally favorable for both players, but you never know. Nowadays, more powerful engines can change an assessment of the line completely, as it is extremely complicated. }
