[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 23: Spanish Mainline - Systems with ...d6"]
[Black "Classical Spanish - 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 #21"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1
{ In the previouschapter, we looked at the  6.d3  line. Now, let's move to the main and most ambitious continuation:  6.Re1  .  With this move, White defends the e4-pawn in order to be able to get in c3-d4.It is a very logical and most ambitious plan. As we have seen in the previous chapter, when White plays more slowly with  6.d3  ,  White can't objectively count on achieving any real advantage @@StartBracket@@even though things are not so easy for Black from a practical perspective@@EndBracket@@. Even so,  6.Re1  is a more ambitious way of playing. If White manages to get in c3-d4, the position will be favourable @@StartBracket@@even though the situation is much more complicated, as you will see in this lesson@@EndBracket@@. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 d6
{ First, I would like to start considering all the lines where Black moves the pawn to d6. Only in the next lesson will we give more attention to Black playing  7...O-O  ,  aiming for the infamous Marshall Gambit/Attack. These days, the latter approach @@StartBracket@@involving the d5 push@@EndBracket@@ is much more popular because it is much harder for White to prove an advantage in the mainlines @@StartBracket@@which is one of the reasons why White often deviates with  8.a4  or  8.h3  @@EndBracket@@.However, it is a matter of choice, and quite many Black players who play the Ruy Lopez want to play a very solid, positional game and don't necessarily want to learn all the forced variations that can arise from the Marshall. Therefore, if you are playing the White side of this opening, you need to be ready for both of these systems. }
8. c3 { This is the main line. } 8... O-O { Now White has a choice. } 9. h3
{ This is by far the most popular move and the main line of the entire variation. White prevents Bg4. In my opinion, this is much more dangerous than playing for d4 immediately. }
9... Bb7
{ In my opinion @@StartBracket@@and I know this might sound very harsh@@EndBracket@@ - the only system here that might fully equalize for Black is the so-called Zaitsev system, associated with the development of the bishop to  b7  . Of course, there are many other lines that are very much playable, but I believe that Zaitsev is the only system that actually leads to objective equality. Of course, it all depends on the level of the players associated - I am primarily talking from the perspective of the top level chess.Of course Black has many other moves. Even something like  9...Rb8  and  9...Be6  is not completely pointless, but then White gets in d4 and Black's position looks a little strange. We will focus on the text move and a few other, more mainstream options. }
10. d4 Re8
{ The fact that Black doesn't have to include the move h6 here was a very important discovery of Zaitsev. }
11. Nbd2 Bf8
{ Now White is simply not in time to transfer the knight to g3, which makes a very serious difference. Now White has many choices @@StartBracket@@as always in the Ruy Lopez@@EndBracket@@. And even though none of them lead to a clear advantage, there is still some room for White to try and pose concrete problems. }
12. a4
{ This is the main line, which leads to very complicated and sharp positions, which was extensively tested in matches against Kasparov and Karpov. I remember I was a kid when the matches were played. Kasparov managed to pose very concrete problems to his opponent and I remember I was very surprised when Karpov repeatedly went for these positions as it seemed the character of play suited his opponent much more. Nowadays, these positions are easier to play when Black has checked them with the engines. }
12... h6
{ Taking on  d4  with  12...exd4  13.cxd4  h6  has little sense, because at the very least White can play  14.Bc2  transposing to text. But there might be a better alternative on move 14 available to White. }
13. Bc2 { Defending the e4-pawn now that Black has committed to h6. } 13...
exd4 { Black is almost forced to go into the following sharp line. } 14. cxd4
Nb4 15. Bb1 c5
{ This is a very interesting, sharp position that was discussed extensively in Kasparov - Karpov encounters @@StartBracket@@in more than one match@@EndBracket@@ and the results were pretty disastrous for Karpov.However, it may be a matter of taste. The position is very sharp and double-edged and all three results are possible. If you play it with either color, you need to be well-prepared as there is no final verdict - things are too complicated even for the most powerful engines as there are too many options for both sides. }
16. d5 { White has to play this. } 16... Nd7 17. Ra3
{ The main move and a very typical maneuver in this position. White wants to include the rook via the 3rd rank @@StartBracket@@after moving the knight to h2 potentially@@EndBracket@@ and start the attack on the kingside. It is very logical to do so, considering that all White's pieces are looking at the Black king and considering that Black's bishop on b7 and knight on b4 are far away from the king, creating counterplay on the other side of the board.   17.Nf1  is met with  17...f5  . }
17... c4
{ For some reason, most strong players nowadays advance the c-pawn and  17...f5  seems to have gone completely out of fashion. }
18. Ree3
{ Computer also likes to play this move, a move that wouldn't normally cross your mind. }
18... Nc5 { The idea is to undermine the structure. } 19. b3 f5
{ With big complications. All in all, this is the most important variation of Zaitsev. My general feeling is that Black has a lot of resources here. Another question is whether you like it or not. The position is definitely sharp and very dangerous. But on the other hand - you have very reasonable winning chances, as well. }
*

