{ To sum up: of the lines after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.O-O  Be7  6.Re1  b5  7.Bb3  d6  8.c3  O-O  9.h3  , I think White has some advantage in the Chigorin system with  9...Na5  10.Bc2  c5  11.d4  and also in the Breyer  9...Nb8  10.d4  Nbd7  . The only system where I think Black has enough resources to equalize is the Zaitsev,  9...Bb7  10.d4  Re8  .  However, the question is really whether you like playing the Zaitsev as Black, as the arising positions are very sharp and dangerous for the second player @@StartBracket@@at least in the main line@@EndBracket@@, and having the better opening preparation will be very important. At the same time, this increases your winning chances as Black.   Objectively, though, the Marshall @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.c3  d5  @@EndBracket@@ is more reliable and is, in my opinion, simply stronger than  7...d6  . The Marshall is also why most White players nowadays actually try to avoid the positions after  7...O-O  8.c3  . We will examine why this is the case in the next lesson. }
