{ If White doesn't want to take the pawn, there is only one serious alternative. }
9. d4 { With Black, it's important to know what to do here. } 9... dxe4
{ The problem of White's 9th move, after which the game is heading practically to a forced draw. As in most Marshall lines, the game is very straightforward. }
10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Bxd1 Nd7 13. Bc2 Nxe5
{ Tested and approved at the highest level.   13...Bb7  may be fine as well. }
14. Bxe4 Rb8 15. Bf4 { The only way to fight for an advantage. } 15... Bd6 16.
Bxe5 Bxe5 17. Bxh7+ Kxh7 18. Rxe5
{ It looks like White is a pawn up, but there is just not enough time to bring the knight into the game. }
18... Rd8 19. Kf1 f6 20. Re3 Rd1+ 21. Re1 Rxe1+ 22. Kxe1 Bf5
{ It still looks like White is a pawn up, but because of the bad development it's a forced draw. }
23. Na3 Re8+ 24. Kf1 { This is not an improvement compared to  24.Kd2  . }
24... Bd3+ { Followed by ...Re8-e2. } *

