1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ This lesson is devoted to the Marshall Attack of the Ruy Lopez where Black castles instead of playing  7...d6  . }
8. c3
{ In the next lesson, we will have a look at the many alternatives that White has, like, for instance,  8.a4  , But also  8.h3  and  8.d4  , which are all attempts to avoid the Marshall Attack.   8.c3  ,  however, has always been the most popular move. }
8... d5
{ The point of the variation, Black is ready to invest a pawn. About a century ago, it was invented by American chess player Frank Marshall who had a very aggressive style. He used it for the first time against the 3rd World Champion, Jose Raul Capablanca, and got... crushed! He later explained how he had prepared it and had waited for the right moment to play it, but Capablanca conducted the game absolutely brilliantly.   Of course  8...d6  would transpose to the subject of our previous lesson. }
