1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ This lesson is devoted to the Marshall Attack of the Ruy Lopez where Black castles instead of playing  7...d6  . }
8. c3
{ In the next lesson, we will have a look at the many alternatives that White has, like, for instance,  8.a4  , But also  8.h3  and  8.d4  , which are all attempts to avoid the Marshall Attack.   8.c3  ,  however, has always been the most popular move. }
8... d5
{ The point of the variation, Black is ready to invest a pawn. About a century ago, it was invented by American chess player Frank Marshall who had a very aggressive style. He used it for the first time against the 3rd World Champion, Jose Raul Capablanca, and got... crushed! He later explained how he had prepared it and had waited for the right moment to play it, but Capablanca conducted the game absolutely brilliantly.   Of course  8...d6  would transpose to the subject of our previous lesson. }
9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe5
{ White can of course make a move like  10.d3  but obviously it can't be a serious stake at an advantage. }
10... Nxe5 11. Rxe5 Bb7
{ It was only when people started realizing there are other moves in the position, like the text and the main move,  11...c6  , which we will analyze in great detail, that a surge in popularity ensued. I see little reason to play  11...Bb7  , since  11...c6  is doing very well. }
12. d4 Bf6 13. Re1 Re8 14. Nd2
{ Black, according to theory, does not have enough compensation. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 24: Spanish Mainline - Marshall Gambit"]
[Black "Marshall Gambit 8... d5 9. exd5 Nxd5, 11. Rxe5 c6 12. d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ This lesson is devoted to the Marshall Attack of the Ruy Lopez where Black castles instead of playing  7...d6  . }
8. c3
{ In the next lesson, we will have a look at the many alternatives that White has, like, for instance,  8.a4  , But also  8.h3  and  8.d4  , which are all attempts to avoid the Marshall Attack.   8.c3  ,  however, has always been the most popular move. }
8... d5
{ The point of the variation, Black is ready to invest a pawn. About a century ago, it was invented by American chess player Frank Marshall who had a very aggressive style. He used it for the first time against the 3rd World Champion, Jose Raul Capablanca, and got... crushed! He later explained how he had prepared it and had waited for the right moment to play it, but Capablanca conducted the game absolutely brilliantly.   Of course  8...d6  would transpose to the subject of our previous lesson. }
9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe5
{ White can of course make a move like  10.d3  but obviously it can't be a serious stake at an advantage. }
10... Nxe5 11. Rxe5 c6
{ The starting position of the Marshall Attack. White is slightly lacking in development but it looks like after d2-d4, followed by Nb1-d2-f3, a healthy extra central pawn is in the pocket. It is a bit sad to me, as the position is very interesting and there were a lot of theoretical battles, at the very highest level, already before the computers appeared. Improvements were found for both sides and the validity of the pawn sacrifice was tested countless times. In short, there was a lot of life in this position. Now, however, in my opinion, the line is dead.   Nowadays, on top of the databases with all the relevant human games, there are computer games as well. Just 2-3 years ago I wanted to update my knowledge on the Marshall and found in my database 230.000 computer games! I quickly understood there is no more play left in this variation and all that is left is to memorize the critical lines. I don't believe there is anything left to be found in this variation. And that is somehow saddening and one of the drawbacks of the modern computer era, as it is in some way limiting our game on the professional level.  There is nothing for White and I would be very surprised if anything would change in the future. As a result, top grandmasters are going for this variation less and less often with White. When they do, they do so to test the memory of the opponent, trying to surprise them.   I can obviously wholeheartedly recommend players from the black side to adopt this opening, as in all the critical lines Black more or less forces the draw. And on the way to these forced draws, Black often even has alternatives that may not be fully correct but still give rise to interesting compensation and positions where it is easier to play with Black. Playing it with White it's a bit sad these days, as it's difficult to find any advantage and, as I said, Black often has a number of options despite the established lines.   Memory is the main factor in this variation. Of course, I am speaking again from a professional viewpoint. For club players, the story is a bit different as I don't expect them to know all the lines by heart, and in that case, it's simply a sharp position where either side has chances to win from the opening. I will of course not be able to show you every single line but will try to present the main attempts by White to play for an advantage, and how Black should react. }
12. d4 Bd6 13. Re1 Qh4 14. g3 Qh3
{ Logical moves, and at this point White has a few options. Preparation is vital because the position is very sharp and Black has plenty of tricks! }
15. Re4
{ A very serious move, preparing to switch the rook to h4. Given the current state of theory, however, it is not a very promising direction for White. }
15... g5
{ A very important move, which is not available in the 12.d3 line. The g-pawn can't be taken and ...f7-f5-f4 is prepared. }
16. Qf1 { 16.Bxg5  Qf5  is a successful double attack. } 16... Qxf1+
{ Black may also be able to play this way, but it is probably inferior to  16...Qh5  . }
17. Kxf1 Bf5 18. Nd2 Bc7 19. a4
{ It is clear, in any case, that only White can be playing for an advantage. }
*

