peaking again from a professional viewpoint. For club players, the story is a bit different as I don't expect them to know all the lines by heart, and in that case, it's simply a sharp position where either side has chances to win from the opening. I will of course not be able to show you every single line but will try to present the main attempts by White to play for an advantage, and how Black should react. }
12. d4 Bd6 13. Re1 Qh4 14. g3 Qh3
{ Logical moves, and at this point White has a few options. Preparation is vital because the position is very sharp and Black has plenty of tricks! }
15. Be3 Bg4 16. Qd3 Rae8 17. Nd2 Re6
{ 10 years ago I played a rapid match with Levon Aronian and managed to surprise him with an, at the time, new idea. }
18. Qf1 Qh5 19. f3 { Looks like a blunder, but it is not! } 19... Rf6 20. Qg2
Bh3 21. Qf2 Bf5 22. a4
{ This is complicated but objectively in White's favor. } *

