peaking again from a professional viewpoint. For club players, the story is a bit different as I don't expect them to know all the lines by heart, and in that case, it's simply a sharp position where either side has chances to win from the opening. I will of course not be able to show you every single line but will try to present the main attempts by White to play for an advantage, and how Black should react. }
12. d3
{ This has virtually replaced  12.d4  at Grandmaster level and is a safer option. }
12... Bd6 13. Re1 Bf5 14. Qf3 Qh4 { Played almost exclusively now. } 15. g3 Qh3
{ Players interested in picking up the Marshall with Black should definitely study the games of Levon Aronian. He has been making draws in this position in 'factory fashion'. }
16. Be3 Bxd3 17. Bxd5
{ White can do this very often in this line, but the light-squared bishop will be missed. }
17... cxd5 18. Qxd5 Rad8 { Black has long-term compensation for the pawn. } 19.
Qf3 Bc4 20. Nd2 Be6 21. Bd4
{ This is a nice square for the bishop but it's not enough to claim an advantage. Some games have reached this position and continued }
21... Bb8 22. Qg2 Qh5
{ Black has fine compensation. I believe objectively the position is equal but subjectively I think it's easier to play with Black as there is always play on the light squares. Black doesn't even need to do anything fast or forceful, as the weaknesses of the light squares guarantees long-term compensation. }
