[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ We saw in the previous lesson that the Marshall is in very good shape which is why players have started looking for ways to avoid it. One option I showed earlier is 6. d3. }
6. d3 b5 7. Bb3
{ We will now have a look at the options with the rook already on e1. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 25: Spanish Mainline - Anti-Marshalls"]
[Black "Anti-Marshalls 6. Re1, 8. d3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ White's main alternatives to  8.c3  are  8.a4  ,  8.h3  , and  8.d4  , which we will examine one by one. }
8. d3
{ A possible move as well, leading to similar positions from the Closed Spanish that I have shown earlier. }
8... d6 9. a3
{ Doesn't make much sense, in combination with Re1, as White is now essentially a tempo down compared to the 6.d3 line. }
9... Na5
{ Black has various ways to equalize and the simplest is probably the text move. }
10. Ba2 c5
{ With the rook on f1 and b1-knight on c3, as in the 6.d3 line, White had the option of playing b2-b4 followed by Nc3-d5 here, but obviously that's not possible now. }
11. Nc3 { Or  11.b4  Nc6  . } 11... Be6 { Black has no problems at all. } *

