[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 25: Spanish Mainline - Anti-Marshalls"]
[Black "Anti-Marshalls 6. Re1, 8. d4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ White's main alternatives to  8.c3  are  8.a4  ,  8.h3  , and  8.d4  , which we will examine one by one. }
8. d4 { An important move, that needs to be studied. } 8... Nxd4
{ This move equalizes in very direct fashion and is the reason this line isn't seen much at the top level anymore. }
9. Bxf7+ Rxf7 10. Nxe5 Rf8
{ Removing the knight from d4 doesn't work as White will take on f7 and follow up with e4-e5. That's why Black needs to move the rook, essentially turning it into a pawn sacrifice. }
11. Qxd4 Bb7
{ Black has enough compensation and the main line runs as follows: } 12. Nc3 c5
13. Qd1 Qc7 14. Ng4 Nxg4 15. Qxg4 Bd6 { Or  15...Rae8  . } 16. g3 Rae8
{ And Black wants to play ...Bd6-e5. Black is very active and has no worries at all, as many @@StartBracket@@computer@@EndBracket@@ games have already shown. }
*

