[White "Lesson 25: Spanish Mainline - Anti-Marshalls"]
[Black "Anti-Marshalls 6. Re1, 8. h3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ White's main alternatives to  8.c3  are  8.a4  ,  8.h3  , and  8.d4  , which we will examine one by one. }
8. h3
{ This had a surge in popularity some time ago, and I played it myself, including in my match with Leko in 2004. }
8... Bb7
{ Black's best option. In case of  8...d6  , White is happy to transpose to the Closed Ruy Lopez with  9.c3  . }
9. d3 { 9.c3  d5  is already fine for Black again. } 9... d6
{ Some 15-20 years ago this was the main continuation. } 10. a3
{ Play greatly resembles the 6.d3 variation but Black's bishop being on b7 is a little bit in White's favor. Nevertheless, Black is of course very solid and the line is still completely playable. White does have chances to fight for an advantage here though. }
10... Qd7
{ Played by Carlsen in game four of his World Championship match against Sergey Karjakin. I always preferred  10...Nb8  and I drew against Kasparov in Linares 2003 using this move. }
11. Nbd2 Rfe8 12. c3 Bf8 13. Nf1
{ Magnus managed to get a fine game out of the opening but perhaps White's play could have been improved. I could go much deeper into the subtleties of the move 9...d6, but the problem is that, over the years, Black has found a much stronger continuation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 25: Spanish Mainline - Anti-Marshalls"]
[Black "Anti-Marshalls 6. Re1, 8. h3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ White's main alternatives to  8.c3  are  8.a4  ,  8.h3  , and  8.d4  , which we will examine one by one. }
8. h3
{ This had a surge in popularity some time ago, and I played it myself, including in my match with Leko in 2004. }
8... Bb7
{ Black's best option. In case of  8...d6  , White is happy to transpose to the Closed Ruy Lopez with  9.c3  . }
9. d3 { 9.c3  d5  is already fine for Black again. } 9... d5
{ Very strong, and more or less killing the line. In my time, this pawn sacrifice was considered to be insufficient, but with modern engines the picture is quite different. This move has made 8. h3 disappear from the top level. }
10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxe5
{ 11.a4  exists, but shouldn't give anything.  11.Nc3  is another possibility that is worth investigating. }
11... Nd4
{ Very direct, here it suffices to memorize the concrete lines.  11...Nxe5  12.Rxe5  is another way to play, and computers also think Black has good chances to equalize. }
12. Nc3
{ Played by Karjakin in game 6 of that same World Championship match. In the meantime, Magnus had repeated all the critical lines in 9...d5 and switched to that variation.   12.Nd2  c5  is OK as well. }
12... Nb4 13. Bf4 Nxb3 14. axb3 c5
{ After  15.Ne4  The players blitzed out a few more moves before the game ended in a draw − one of the quickest draws in the match. Visually, it's very clear that Black has fine compensation in the form of the bishop pair and an active position. If Black also manages to play ...f7-f6 and ...Qd8-d7, I don't see any reason for White to claim an edge. This shows why 8.h3 is no longer that popular. Black can choose to force things with 9...d5, or to play a game with 9... d6. }
