1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ White's main alternatives to  8.c3  are  8.a4  ,  8.h3  , and  8.d4  , which we will examine one by one. }
8. a4
{ Maybe the most popular move to avoid the Marshall and, in my opinion, the most interesting way to do so too. In this line there are still some small problems to solve for Black here and there. }
8... b4
{ The most popular move in the position and a bit more direct than  8...Bb7  which I consider to be completely fine as well. This move has been analyzed considerably more compared to 8...Bb7 but it's hard for me to make a distinction of one over the other. }
9. d4 d6 10. dxe5
{ The position is a bit trickier than it looks. Many top players have tried to get a small plus here as White. Over the years, the right ways of playing have been discovered for Black. }
10... Nxe5 11. Nxe5 dxe5
{ Here Black needs to be a bit careful. If White manages to develop the queenside with Qd1-e2, Bc1-e3, Nb1-d2 it may get unpleasant. For now, White is far from reaching this setup though and Black should be in time to create play. }
12. Qf3 Bc5 13. h3 { Preventing any piece from reaching g4. } 13... Bb7 14. Nd2
a5 15. Nc4 Re8 16. Bg5 Ra6
{ Just a sample line to illustrate how play may develop. White has a good knight on c4 and a5 may be a potential weakness, but at the same time Black is very active and theory considers the position to be dynamically balanced. }
