1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ White's main alternatives to  8.c3  are  8.a4  ,  8.h3  , and  8.d4  , which we will examine one by one. }
8. a4
{ Maybe the most popular move to avoid the Marshall and, in my opinion, the most interesting way to do so too. In this line there are still some small problems to solve for Black here and there. }
8... b4
{ The most popular move in the position and a bit more direct than  8...Bb7  which I consider to be completely fine as well. This move has been analyzed considerably more compared to 8...Bb7 but it's hard for me to make a distinction of one over the other. }
9. a5 { An interesting move. } 9... d6
{ 9...d5  10.exd5  I am unsure what this version of Marshall looks like, but it is not often seen. }
10. c3 { The fashionable move.  10.d3  is possible too. } 10... Rb8 11. Bc4
{ A strange looking move, trying to prevent ...Bc8-e6. } 11... d5
{ Perhaps Black's best option. The waiting move  11...h6  makes sense as well. }
12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Rxe5 Bb7
{ A good version of the Marshall Attack. } 15. d4 Bf6 16. Re1 c5
{ This is what computers like to play, Black has pressure in the center and, potentially, on the b-file. All in all, 9.a5 is a very ambitious and interesting move but it does give Black a wide range of options. }
