1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ White's main alternatives to  8.c3  are  8.a4  ,  8.h3  , and  8.d4  , which we will examine one by one. }
8. a4
{ Maybe the most popular move to avoid the Marshall and, in my opinion, the most interesting way to do so too. In this line there are still some small problems to solve for Black here and there. }
8... b4
{ The most popular move in the position and a bit more direct than  8...Bb7  which I consider to be completely fine as well. This move has been analyzed considerably more compared to 8...Bb7 but it's hard for me to make a distinction of one over the other. }
9. d3 { The most common move. } 9... d6 { Preparing ...Nc6-a5 and ...c7-c5. }
10. a5 { Stopping Black's main move ... Nc6-a5. } 10... Be6 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12.
c3
{ This has become fashionable, because of the strategic complexity where White can play for an advantage. }
12... Qe8 13. Nbd2 Rb8
{ Preparing a lift to b5, while White is aiming to push d3-d4 in the right moment. The position got tested already at the highest levels, with for instance Magnus Carlsen defeating Levon Aronian some years ago. Black is doing fine objectively, but the position is strategically complex and needs to be analyzed. It is probably the main Anti-Marshall weapon these days where statistically speaking, White is doing a bit better. It's not at all certain White has an advantage, but at least White can play for an advantage in this line. On top of that, it's not as easy in this line, as in most of the other lines. }
