{ Tomashevsky's move, and it's not clear to me why it's not as popular as 8...b4. Black is doing completely fine, theoretically speaking. }
9. d3 { 9.c3  d5!  is excellent for Black. } 9... d6
{ The good old way of playing here. A high amount of theory has been established after White's two main responses,  10.Nbd2  and  10.Nc3  . }
10. Bd2
{ I am a bit skeptical about such moves, but it may be possible to get an unconventional type of position this way. It has been played on the highest level. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 25: Spanish Mainline - Anti-Marshalls"]
[Black "Anti-Marshalls 6. Re1, 8. a4 Bb7, 9... d6 10. Nbd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ White's main alternatives to  8.c3  are  8.a4  ,  8.h3  , and  8.d4  , which we will examine one by one. }
8. a4
{ Maybe the most popular move to avoid the Marshall and, in my opinion, the most interesting way to do so too. In this line there are still some small problems to solve for Black here and there. }
8... Bb7
{ Tomashevsky's move, and it's not clear to me why it's not as popular as 8...b4. Black is doing completely fine, theoretically speaking. }
9. d3 { 9.c3  d5!  is excellent for Black. } 9... d6
{ The good old way of playing here. A high amount of theory has been established after White's two main responses,  10.Nbd2  and  10.Nc3  . }
10. Nbd2 Na5 11. Ba2 c5 12. Nf1 b4
{ Black follows the same plan as after 10.Nc3, but White's setup is a bit more flexible as from f1 there is the option for the knight to go to e3 and g3, while from e2, there is only one reasonable square to jump to. }
13. c3 Nc6
{ Again, White seems to be doing well, but objectively not much is happening. }
14. Ne3 Rb8
{ Even allowing the knight to f5, doesn't scare the engines. My feeling is White should be able to try to fight for an advantage, though objectively Black may be fine. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 25: Spanish Mainline - Anti-Marshalls"]
[Black "Anti-Marshalls 6. Re1, 8. a4 Bb7, 9... d6 10. Nbd2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ White's main alternatives to  8.c3  are  8.a4  ,  8.h3  , and  8.d4  , which we will examine one by one. }
8. a4
{ Maybe the most popular move to avoid the Marshall and, in my opinion, the most interesting way to do so too. In this line there are still some small problems to solve for Black here and there. }
8... Bb7
