[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 25: Spanish Mainline - Anti-Marshalls"]
[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ 1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.O-O  Be7  6.Re1  b5  7.Bb3  O-O  8.a4  To conclude, 8.a4 is definitely the Anti-Marshall line where most theory has accumulated and where the positions are most complex.    8...Bb7  If you are playing this line with Black, you need to study it very carefully and decide on 8... Bb7 or 8...b4, or perhaps to switch them around as both seem to be equally playable.  From White's side, 8.a4 is the most interesting direction, and even though Black may be able to equalize, the positions are difficult enough to remain playable. Combined with the 6.d3 system, it is the modern way to fight for an opening advantage against Marshall players. }
